{"title_page": "Box Hill, Surrey", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Box Hill (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Hill in Surrey, England}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox protected area\n| name = Box Hill\n| alt_name = Part of the [[Mole Gap to Reigate Escarpment]] SSSI\n| iucn_category = IV\n| iucn_ref =\n| photo = Towards_Box_Hill_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1805314.jpg\n| photo_width = 290\n| photo_alt = \n| photo_caption = Box Hill viewed from the south. <br>Photograph taken from Betchworth Park Golf Course.\n| map = United Kingdom Surrey\n| map_width = \n| map_alt = \n| map_caption = \n| relief = 1\n| label = Box Hill\n| label_position = top\n| mark =\n| marker_size =\n| location = \n| nearest_city = \n| nearest_town = [[Dorking]], [[Surrey]], England\n| coordinates = {{coord|51|15|18|N|0|18|31|W|type:mountain_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coords_ref = \n| length =\n| length_mi =\n| length_km =\n| width =\n| width_mi = \n| width_km =\n| area = \n| area_ha =\n| area_acre =\n| area_km2 = 11\n| area_sqmi =\n| area_ref = \n| elevation = \n| elevation_avg = \n| elevation_min = \n| elevation_max = \n| dimensions = \n| designation =\n| authorized =\n| created =\n| designated = \n| established = \n| named_for = \n| visitation_num = \n| visitation_year = \n| visitation_ref =\n| governing_body = \n| administrator =\n| operator =\n| owner =\n| world_heritage_site =\n| website = \n| url = \n| child = \n| embedded = \n{{Infobox mountain\n| name            = Box Hill\n| photo           = \n| photo_size      = \n| photo_alt       = \n| photo_caption   = \n| elevation_m     = 224\n| elevation_ref   =<ref name=Wooldridge_1957_79>{{harvnb|Wooldridge|Hutchings|1957|p=79}}</ref>\n| prominence_m    = 49\n| listing         =\n| location        = \n| range           = [[North Downs]]\n| map_image       = Box hill map.png\n| map_alt         =\n| map_caption     = Map of Box Hill, showing the areas managed by the National Trust (purple), Surrey Wildlife Trust (turquoise) and Surrey County Council (green).  The urban area of Box Hill village is shown in grey.\n| grid_ref_UK     = TQ 178 514\n| topo            = [[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Landranger'' 187\n| type            = [[Cuesta]]\n| geology         = [[Chalk]]\n| geology2        = [[Clay-with-Flints]]\n| age             = Cretaceous and Eocene\n| last_eruption   =\n| first_ascent    =\n| easiest_route   =\n| child = yes\n}}\n}}\n'''Box Hill''' is a summit of the [[North Downs]] in [[Surrey]], approximately {{convert|30|km|mi|abbr=on}} south-west of [[London]].  The hill gets its name from the ancient [[Buxus sempervirens|box woodland]] found on the steepest west-facing chalk slopes overlooking the [[River Mole]]. The western part of the hill is owned and managed by the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]], whilst the village of Box Hill lies on higher ground to the east. The highest point is Betchworth Clumps at {{convert|224|m|ft|abbr=on}} [[Ordnance Datum|above OD]],<ref name=Wooldridge_1957_79/> although the Salomons Memorial (at 172 metres) overlooking the town of [[Dorking]] is the most popular viewpoint.<ref name=MVDC_planning>{{cite web |url= http://www.mole-valley.gov.uk/cwi/getDocument?docId=188328&account=planning&ref=MO/2009/0647&filename=Design%20Statement |title= Box Hill Visitor Facilities and Car Park: Planning Application for Proposed Improvements |publisher= Mole Valley District Council |accessdate=3 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nBox Hill lies within the [[Surrey Hills AONB|Surrey Hills Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]] and forms part of the [[Mole Gap to Reigate Escarpment]] Site of Special Scientific Interest.  The north- and south-facing slopes support an area of chalk downland, noted for its orchids and other rare plant species.<ref name=NT_wildlife>{{cite web |url= http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-vh/w-visits/w-great_days_out/w-nature-places_to_visit/w-nature-places_to_visit-boxhill.htm |title= Box Hill |author= Oates M |year= 2008 |work= Places to Visit for Wildlife |publisher= National Trust |accessdate= 3 April 2011 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110517040554/http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-vh/w-visits/w-great_days_out/w-nature-places_to_visit/w-nature-places_to_visit-boxhill.htm |archivedate= 17 May 2011 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The hill provides a habitat for 40 species of butterfly,<ref name=NT_wildlife/> and has given its name to a species of [[Coreidae|squash bug]], now found throughout south-east England.<ref name=british_bugs>{{cite web |url=http://www.britishbugs.org.uk/heteroptera/Coreidae/gonocerus_acuteangulatus.html |title= ''Gonocerus acuteangulatus'' Box Bug |author= Bantock T and Botting J |year= 2010 |work= British Bugs: An online identification guide to UK Hemiptera |publisher= britishbugs.org.uk |accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nAn estimated 850,000 people visit Box Hill each year.<ref name=MVDC_planning/> The National Trust visitors' centre provides both a cafeteria and gift shop, and the panoramic views of the western Weald may be enjoyed from the [[North Downs Way]], a long-distance footpath that runs along the southern escarpment.  Box Hill featured prominently on the route of the [[Cycling at the 2012 Summer Olympics|2012 Summer Olympics cycling]] road race events.<ref name=\"guardian1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/interactive/2011/feb/10/olympics-2012-cycling-road-race-route |title=Olympics 2012: cycling road race route |work=Guardian|date=11 February 2011 |format=Adobe Flash |accessdate=18 February 2011}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:St Andrew's Church, Box Hill (Geograph Image 2266120 e41e2a89).jpg|thumb|St Andrew's Church, Box Hill village.]]\nBox Hill, approximately {{convert|30|km|mi|abbr=on}} south-west of central London, stands at the south-eastern corner of the Mole Gap, the valley carved by the River Mole through the North Downs.<ref name=Bannister_p2>{{harvnb|Bannister|1999|p=2}}</ref> Its summit, {{convert|224|m|ft}} above [[Ordnance Datum]], is the 12th highest in Surrey.<ref>[http://www.hills-database.co.uk/downloads.html Database of British and Irish Hills] Retrieved 6 March 2015</ref> The western boundary of the hill is defined by the River Mole, which has cut a steep [[cliff]], exposing the chalk bedrock. The [[Vale of Holmesdale]] lies immediately to the south, below the scarp slope. The northern and eastern boundaries are defined by [[dry valley|dry river valleys]], which were created during the [[last glacial period|last Ice Age]]. The total area of the hill is approximately {{convert|11|km2|sqmi}}, of which half is owned by the National Trust.\n\nThe village of Box Hill is within the civil parish of Headley. The earliest flint cottages date from the 1800s, although much of the village was constructed in the first half of the 20th century.<ref>{{harvnb|Mountford|1974|pp=3\u20134}}</ref> By 2005 there were more than 800 dwellings, of which over five hundred were mobile homes.  An estimated 41% of the community is aged 60 or over.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.connectedsurrey.com/stylesheet.asp?file=17032006112104 |title= Box Hill Project |author= Fry R |year= 2006 |work= Community Case Studies |publisher= The Connected Surrey Partnership |accessdate=13 April 2011}}</ref> St Andrew's Church, part of the [[ecclesiastical parish]] of Headley, was consecrated in 1969 and the village hall opened in 1974.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://myweb.tiscali.co.uk/friendsofstandrewsbh/history_part_1.htm |title=History |author=Langley D |year=2000 |work=The Church on the Hill |publisher=Friends of St Andrews Box Hill |accessdate=24 July 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6IMGmoaPS?url=http://myweb.tiscali.co.uk/friendsofstandrewsbh/history_part_1.htm |archivedate=24 July 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Mountford|1974|p=3}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Early history===\n[[File:Beech pollard - Box Hill, Surrey.jpg|thumb|Ancient [[pollarding|pollarded]] [[beech]] tree between the Viewpoint and the Donkey Green.{{refn|The tree marks the boundary between two parishes: [[Mickleham, Surrey|Mickleham]] (to the north) and [[Dorking]] (to the south).<ref name=Bannister6-7>{{harvnb|Bannister|1999|pp=6\u20137}}</ref>|group=note}}]]\nTwo Bronze Age [[round barrow]]s, located close to the Salomons Memorial, provide the earliest archaeological evidence of human activity on Box Hill.<ref>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1007888}}</ref><ref>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1007889}}</ref> The larger barrow is {{convert|20|m|abbr=on}} in diameter and {{convert|2.2|m|abbr=on}} high.  In medieval times the larger barrow was used as a [[boundary marker]] or ''mere'' for the parish of [[Mickleham, Surrey|Mickleham]].<ref name=Bannister12>{{harvnb|Bannister|1999|p=12}}</ref> Traces of prehistoric [[field system|field boundaries]] are visible on Burford Spur and the low [[flint]] banks on the steeper and more wooded White Hill may be contemporaneous.<ref name=Bannister12/>\n\nAn [[Harrow Way|ancient trackway]] along the [[North Downs]] escarpment can be dated to around 600\u2013450&nbsp;BC, but has probably been in existence since the [[stone age]]<ref>{{harvnb|Brayley|Britton|1841|p=218}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Fagg|first=C. C.|author2=Hutchings, G. E.  |others=Tansley, A. G|title=Great Britain: essays in regional geography |editor=Ogilvie, Alan Grant|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge, England|year=1928|page=29|chapter=Prehistory|oclc=59447377}}</ref> and may have crossed the [[River Mole]] at a ford close to the location of the present day stepping stones. In Victorian times the route was dubbed the [[Pilgrims' Way]] and was supposedly followed by visitors to the shrines of [[Thomas Becket]] and [[Swithun]] at [[Canterbury Cathedral|Canterbury]] and [[Winchester Cathedral|Winchester]] respectively.<ref>{{harvnb|Margary|1948|pp=260\u2013263}}</ref>\n\n[[Stane Street (Chichester)|Stane Street]] was constructed by the [[Roman Britain|Romans]] in around 60\u201370 AD to link London ([[Londinium]]) to Chichester ([[Noviomagus Reginorum]]) on the south coast of England.<ref>{{harvnb|Margary|1948|p=XX}}</ref> The course of the road runs in a southwesterly direction across Mickleham Downs,<ref name=Hall>{{cite journal |author= Hall A |year= 2008 |title= The archaeological evidence for the route of Stane Street from Mickleham Downs to London Road, Ewell |journal= Surrey Archaeological Collections |publisher= Surrey Archaeological Society |volume= 94 |pages= 225\u2013250 }}</ref> before turning south to cross the [[River Mole]] at a ford close to the site of the [[Burford Bridge Hotel]].<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= The Mole Crossing at Burford |work= The Times |location= London |date= 25 March 1937 |issue= 47642 |page= 17}}</ref>\n\n===Medieval and early modern periods===\nThe [[Warren#Pillow mounds|pillow mounds]] to the north-east of the Salomons Memorial are thought to date from the medieval period and were probably constructed as artificial [[Warren (domestic)|warrens]] for rabbits. High Ashurst warren is recorded as remaining in use until the late 18th century.<ref name=Bannister20>{{harvnb|Bannister|1999|p=20}}</ref> A second warren was probably situated close to Warren Farm in the Headley Valley and it has been speculated that the present farmhouse was originally the warrener's cottage.<ref name=Bannister20/>\n\n[[File:Boxhill surrey trees.jpg|thumb|right|Box and yew trees growing on the steep, western slope of Box Hill, above the River Mole.]]\nThe origin of the [[buxus|box trees]] growing on the hill is disputed: Several sources from the late 18th century suggest that the first box trees on the hill were planted by [[Thomas Howard, 21st Earl of Arundel]] during the reign of [[Charles I of England|Charles I]].<ref>{{harvnb|Beavan|1777|p=2}}</ref> However Howard never owned the Box Hill estate<ref>{{harvnb|Littledale|Locock|Sankey|1984|p=12}}</ref> and older medieval documents make reference to local individuals with surnames including ''Atteboxe'', ''de la Boxe'' and ''Buxeto'', suggesting that the trees were already common in the area by the 13th century.<ref>{{harvnb|Brayley|Britton|1841|p=461}}</ref> The diarist [[John Evelyn]] records a visit to the hill in August 1655 to view \"those natural bowers, cabinets and shady walks in the box copses.\" The close grain of the box wood made it highly prized for its [[lumber|timber]] for carving and there are numerous accounts of the sale of trees from the hill throughout the 17th and 18th centuries.<ref name=\"Littledale 1984 13\">{{harvnb|Littledale|Locock|Sankey|1984|p=13}}</ref> At the end of the eighteenth century, imports from Portugal reduced the market value of box wood and commercial exploitation of timber from Box Hill appears to have ended with a final sale in 1797.<ref name=\"Littledale 1984 13\"/>\n\n===Ownership and public access <small>(19th and 20th centuries)</small>===\nThe hill was purchased by [[Thomas Hope (banker, born 1769)|Thomas Hope]], shortly before his death in 1831. (Hope was the owner of [[Deepdene House and Gardens|The Deepdene]], the mansion to the east of [[Dorking]].<ref name=\"Littledale 1984 13\"/>) The [[Mickleham, Surrey|Mickleham Parish]] Records credit Hope's widow, Louisa de la Poer Beresford (whom he had married six years previously), with allowing \"free access to the beauties of this hill,\"<ref name=\"Littledale 1984 13\"/> however day-trippers had been arriving in significant numbers for at least a century before that.<ref>{{cite book |last= Macky |first= John |year= 1714 |volume= 1 |title= A journey through England. In familiar letters. From a gentleman here, to his friend abroad |location= London |publisher= J. Hooke |author-link= John Macky}}</ref>\n\nDevelopments in local transport infrastructure over the course of the 18th and 19th centuries, enabled increasing numbers to visit the area. Following the completion of the [[turnpike trust|turnpike road]] between [[Leatherhead]] and [[Dorking]] in 1750, [[stagecoach]]es stopped regularly at the [[Burford Bridge Hotel]].<ref name=Shepperd128>{{harvnb|Shepperd|1991|p=128}}</ref> As late as 1879, a daily coach ran non-stop to Box Hill from [[Piccadilly]] with a journey time of 2.5 hours.<ref name=DailyNews1>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= The Boxhill Coach |work= Daily News |location= London |date= 31 March 1879}}</ref>{{refn|In March 1879 the coach left Piccadilly at 10:30am every day, arriving at the Burford Bridge Hotel at 1pm. The return journey left Box Hill at 4pm, arriving back in London at 6:30pm.<ref name=DailyNews1/>|group=note}}\n\nThe [[South Eastern Railway (England)|South Eastern Railway]] opened the first railway station in Dorking in 1849,{{refn|Now known as [[Dorking West railway station|Dorking West]] station on the [[North Downs Line]].|group=note}} followed in 1867 by the [[London, Brighton and South Coast Railway]] (LBSCR), which opened the station in the village of Westhumble.<ref name=Chapman150-151>{{harvnb|Shepperd|1991|pp=150\u2013151}}</ref><ref name=Shepperd137>{{harvnb|Shepperd|1991|p=137}}</ref> The LBSCR ran dedicated excursion trains to Box Hill on Bank Holiday weekends and over 1300 day-trippers were recorded arriving at Westhumble station on 6 August 1883.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= The Bank Holiday |work= The Times |location= London |date= 7 August 1883}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Box Hill Salomons Memorial 2.jpg|right|thumb|The Salomons Memorial commemorates the gift of {{convert|95|ha|acre|abbr=on|sigfig=2}} of land on Box Hill to the National Trust in 1914.{{refn|Salomons died in September 1915, just over a year after donating the land on Box Hill to the National Trust. His widow opened the Memorial at the viewpoint in 1920.<ref>{{cite news |last= Edwards |first= Mark |date= 11 September 2014 |title= Box Hill viewing point reopens to mark 100th anniversary |url= https://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/nostalgia/box-hill-viewing-point-reopens-7756789 |work= Surrey Live |access-date= 21 October 2019 }}</ref>|group=note}}]]\nThe proposals for a [[land value tax]] outlined by Chancellor [[David Lloyd George]] in his [[People's Budget]] of 1909 prompted the trustees of the Deepdene estate to start to sell the unimproved land on the western side of Box Hill.<ref name=Littledale15>{{harvnb|Littledale|Locock|Sankey|1984|p=15}}</ref> As a result of negotiations led by [[Robert Hunter (National Trust)|Sir Robert Hunter]], [[Leopold Salomons]] of [[Norbury Park]] purchased {{convert|95|ha|acre|abbr=on|sigfig=2}} of Box Hill in 1913 for \u00a316,000. The following year, Salomons donated the land, which included the Old Fort, Swiss Cottage and the western flank of the hill above the River Mole, to the National Trust.<ref name=Littledale15-16>{{harvnb|Littledale|Locock|Sankey|1984|pp=15\u201316}}</ref>\n\nTwo further purchases of {{convert|28|ha|acre|abbr=on|sigfig=2}} and {{convert|102|ha|acre|abbr=on|sigfig=2}} transferred Lodge Hill and Ashurst Rough to National Trust ownership in 1921 and 1923.<ref name=NT_acq>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/servlet/file/store5/item724521/version1/nt_acquisitions_dec2011-2.pdf |title=National Trust Acquisition Data |year=2010 |publisher=National Trust |accessdate=12 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120603070439/http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/servlet/file/store5/item724521/version1/nt_acquisitions_dec2011-2.pdf |archivedate=3 June 2012}}</ref> Following World War 2, National Trust acquired Headley Heath, a geologically distinct area of heathland which lies to the north-east of Box Hill village, in a single purchase in 1946.<ref name=NT_acq/> The Trust continued to purchase land, and by the mid-1980s the estate comprised some {{convert|500|ha|acre|abbr=on|sigfig=2}}.<ref name=NT_acq/> The most recent additions to the Box Hill Estate include farmland at Westhumble and at the foot of the hill, purchased in the late 1990s.<ref name=NT_acq/>\n\n===Military History <small>(19th and 20th centuries)</small>===\n\n[[File:Box Hill Fort.JPG|thumb|Box Hill Fort, constructed in 1899. Note the earth [[blast wall|blast bank]] (left) which protects the south west face of the flat-roofed main building (right).<ref name=NHL_Boxhill_Fort>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1018074}}</ref>]]\nIn the latter half of the 19th century, growing public concern over the ability of the British armed forces to repel an invasion (stoked, in part, by the serialisation of [[George Tomkyns Chesney|George Tomkyns Chesney's]] 1871 novella [[The Battle of Dorking]]<ref name=Tuson-20-21>{{harvnb|Tuson|2013|pp=20\u201321}}</ref>), prompted the government to announce the construction of thirteen fortified mobilisation centres, collectively known as the [[London Defence Positions]].{{refn|A common misconception is that the forts were built to protect against invasion by the French Emperor [[Napoleon]], however he had died in 1821, almost 80 years before construction began. <br>The aftermath of the [[Franco-Prussian War]] of 1870 (which led to the [[unification of Germany]]), the reform of the Russian Army following the Crimean War and colonial disputes with France, prompted British fears of a war against an alliance of the main European powers. Lobbying by [[Edward Bruce Hamley|Sir Edward Hamley MP]]<ref>{{Cite Hansard|house=House of Commons |title= Defences of the Empire - Coast defences of Great Britain |url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/commons/1887/mar/14/observations#S3V0312P0_18870314_HOC_240 |date= 14 March 1887 |volume 312 |column_start=238 |column_end=325}}</ref> resulted in the Secretary of State for War, [[Edward Stanhope]],  presenting the bill for construction of the London Defence Positions to Parliament in 1889.<ref name=Beanse-4-6>{{harvnb|Beanse|Gill|2011|pp=4\u20136}}</ref>|group=note}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WMGCY |title= Box Hill Fort |year= 2006 |work= Historic Forts on Waymarking.com |publisher= waymarking.com |accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> Two centres were built on Box Hill, approximately {{convert|2.5|km|mi|abbr=on}} apart: one close to the present National Trust visitor centre (commonly called Box Hill Fort)<ref name=Beanse-Boxhill>{{harvnb|Beanse|Gill|2011|pp=17\u201319}}</ref> and the other close to the summit of the hill, to the south of the present day Box Hill village (known as Betchworth Fort).<ref name=Beanse-Betchworth>{{harvnb|Beanse|Gill|2011|pp=14\u201316}}</ref>\n\nThe sites were purchased from the trustees of the Hope estate by the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] in 1891, and construction began in 1899.<ref name=Beanse-Boxhill/><ref name=Beanse-Betchworth/> The two centres were laid out in the form of an [[redoubt|infantry redoubt]] typical of the period, but also included [[magazine (artillery)|magazines]] (partially below ground level) for the storage of [[Shell (projectile)|shells]] and [[Cartridge (firearms)|cartridges]].<ref name=Beanse-Betchworth/><ref name=Littledale23>{{harvnb|Littledale|Locock|Sankey|1984|p=23}}</ref> (In common with the majority of the eleven other mobilisation centres, the forts were designed for the use of the infantry only and the stored ammunition was intended for the use of [[Field artillery|mobile field artillery]] which would be deployed nearby as required.)<ref name=Littledale23/> The main flat-roofed buildings were built in brick and reinforced concrete and were protected from [[artillery]] fire by crescent-shaped earth blast banks, surrounded by an outer ditch.<ref name=NHL_Boxhill_Fort/>\n\nA [[Haldane reforms|reform of defence policy]] by the Secretary of War [[Richard Haldane, 1st Viscount Haldane|Viscount Haldane]] in 1905 resulted in all 13 centres being declared redundant, and both forts were sold back to the estate trustees in 1908.<ref name=Beanse-Betchworth/><ref name=Bannister27>{{harvnb|Bannister|1999|p=27}}</ref> Both forts are protected by a Scheduled Monument listing.<ref name=NHL_Boxhill_Fort/><ref name=NHL_Betchworth_Fort>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1020370}}</ref> The National Trust owns the Box Hill Fort and a metal grill has been placed over the entrance to allow bats to access to their roosts.<ref name=NHL_Boxhill_Fort/><ref name=Bannister27/> The Betchworth Fort is in private ownership and is not accessible to the public.<ref name=Beanse-Betchworth/>\n\n[[File:Pill Box - geograph.org.uk - 657135.jpg|thumb|[[Pillbox (military)|Pillbox]] on the south-facing scarp slope of Box Hill (to the north of [[Betchworth Castle]]).]]\nDuring the [[Second World War]] the River Mole, comprised part of the fortified [[GHQ Line|GHQ Line B]]. This defensive line ran along the North Downs from [[Farnham]] via [[Guildford]] to Dorking, before following the river to [[Horley]].<ref name=DA12>{{cite web |url= http://ads.ahds.ac.uk/catalogue//adsdata/arch-455-1/dissemination/pdf/Text_Reports/DA12_TEXT_-_DORKING_GAP.pdf |title= Defence Area 12: Dorking Gap |author= Foot W |year= 2009 |work= Defence Areas: a national study of Second World War anti-invasion landscapes in England |publisher= English Heritage |accessdate=11 December 2010}}</ref> Between Betchworth and Box Hill, the north bank of the River Mole was stabilised and made steeper to prevent wheeled vehicles from crossing. At Boxhill Farm, where access to the river from the north bank was required for the herd of dairy cows, a row of twelve concrete cylinders were cast as an anti-tank measure. Gun mounts were also installed to protect both Boxhill and Deepdene bridges and several [[Pillbox (military)|pillboxes]] were constructed.<ref name=DA12/><ref name=\"Marchington T 2000 96\u2013100\">{{cite journal |author= Marchington T |year= 2000 |title= Wartime Defences: A Second Look |journal= Proceedings of the Leatherhead and District Local History Society |volume= 6 |issue= 4 |pages= 96\u2013100 |publisher= Leatherhead and District Local History Society}}</ref><ref name=Telegraph_walk>{{cite journal |date= 2 March 2011 |title=Box Hill, Surrey: walk of the week |journal=Daily Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/activityandadventure/walkingholidays/8356605/Box-Hill-Surrey-walk-of-the-week.html |accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref> The Stepping Stones at the foot of the hill were removed as an anti-invasion measure.<ref name=Telegraph_walk/>\n\nFrom 1940, [[Headley Court]] was used as the Headquarters for the [[VII Corps (United Kingdom)|VII Corps]] and later for the [[Canadian Corps (World War II)|Canadian Corps]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/UN/Canada/CA/OpSumm/OpSumm-2.html|title=On Guard in Britain, 1940\u20131941|publisher=The Department of National Defense, Government of Canada|accessdate=13 February 2016}}</ref> and Canadian troops were billeted at [[High Ashurst]].<ref name=Denyer>{{cite web|last= Denyer |first= Peter |url=https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/headley-heath/features/the-second-world-war-on-headley-heath |title=The Second World War on Headley Heath |publisher=The National Trust |accessdate= 21 October 2019}}</ref> Bellasis House was used as training centre both for Czech agents of the [[Special Operations Executive]] and for German [[Prisoner of war|Prisoners of War]].<ref name=Denyer/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://dorkingmuseum.org.uk/wartime-at-dorkings-mansions/ |title= Wartime at Dorking\u2019s mansions|publisher= Dorking Museum |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref> In preparation for [[Normandy landings|D-Day]], Headley Heath was used for tank and combat training by the Canadian armed forces,<ref name=Tuson-30-31>{{harvnb|Tuson|2013|pp=30\u201331}}</ref><ref name=Matharu>{{cite news|last= Matharu |first= Hardeep |url= https://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/news/9943474.unexploded-mortar-shells-discovered-on-headley-heath/ |title=Unexploded mortar shells discovered on Headley Heath |work= Sutton and Croydon Guardian |date= 21 September 2012 |accessdate= 21 October 2019}}</ref> and [[Betchworth Quarry and Lime Kilns|Betchworth Quarry]] was used by the British Army in early 1944, to test the firing capabilities of [[Churchill tank]]s.<ref>{{harvnb|Chapman|Young|1979|p=154}}</ref>\n\n==Geology==\n===Rock types===\n[[File:Chalk_Face,_Betchworth_Quarry,_Box_Hill,_Surrey.jpg|thumb|The exposed chalk workings of the former Betchworth Quarry on the south-facing scarp slope of Box Hill. {{refn|Note the transmitter mast in the top-left corner of the photograph which, together with the adjacent water tower (not visible in the picture), marks the true summit of Box Hill at {{convert|224|m|ft|abbr=on}} above OD.|group=note}}]]\nThe [[Chalk Group|chalk]] which comprises the majority of Box Hill (and the rest of the [[North Downs]]), has its origins in the late [[Cretaceous]] period (approximately 100 \u2013 66 million years ago). For the entirety of this period, south east England was covered by a warm, shallow sea in which [[coccolithophores]], single-celled [[alga]]e with small [[calcite]] skeletons, thrived. As the phytoplankton died, their calcium-rich shells were deposited on the sea bed and, over time, formed the chalk we know today.\n\nOverlying the chalk across much of the higher ground on the hill, is a deposit of [[clay-with-flints]]. Although the origins of this layer are uncertain, the clay is thought to have been formed during several periods of glaciation and was produced by [[cryoturbation]] and decalcification of the chalk.<ref name=Gallois>{{cite journal |last1=Gallois |first1= RW |title= The origin of the Clay-with-flints: the missing link|journal=Geoscience in South-West England|date=2009|volume=12|pages=153\u2013161}}</ref> This hypothesis is supported by the presence of flint, which is also found in the underlying strata.<ref name=Gallois/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Anon|title=Clay-with Flints formation|url=http://www.bgs.ac.uk/lexicon/lexicon.cfm?pub=CWF|website=The BGS Lexicon of Named Rock Units|publisher=BGS|accessdate=3 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Betchworth limekiln - geograph.org.uk - 869914.jpg|thumb|right|upright|The Smidth Kiln at [[Betchworth Quarry and Lime Kilns|Betchworth Quarry]] was constructed in around 1901.<ref name=NHL_Betchworth>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1021346}}</ref>]]\nThe sandy deposits on Headley Heath have their origin in the [[Quaternary]]. During this period, south east England began to rise from the sea bed, as a result of the same geological processes which [[Alpine orogeny|formed the Alps]] in central Europe. The sand and gravels found in this area, indicate the presence of the sea shore.<ref name=Chapman26>{{harvnb|Chapman|Young|1979|p=26}}</ref> On Headley Heath, these deposits are thin and the chalk also comes to the surface in several places, allowing [[calcifuge|acid-loving plants]] to thrive alongside those that [[calcicole|prefer alkaline conditions]], producing the rare [[chalk heath]] habitat.<ref name=Tuson-30-31/>\n\n===Quarries and lime kilns===\nChalk and flint have been quarried from Box Hill and the surrounding area for many centuries. There are limited surviving examples of the incorporation of chalk blocks (or [[clunch]]) into the stonework of local buildings (including [[Mickleham, Surrey|Mickleham Church]]).<ref name=Shepperd112>{{harvnb|Shepperd|1991|p=112}}</ref> Walls made of flints, bound together by [[lime mortar]], are particularly common in [[Surrey]]<ref name=Bannister22>{{harvnb|Bannister|1999|p=22}}</ref> and [[calcium oxide|quicklime]] could be produced with relative ease, by heating chalk above {{convert|825|C|F}} in a [[lime kiln|kiln]].<ref>{{cite book |last= Stecher |first= Paul G |year= 1968 |title= The Merck index : an encyclopedia of chemicals and drugs |location= Rahway NJ |publisher= Merck |edition= 8th}}</ref>\n\nEvidence remains of the small-scale chalk quarrying that occurred prior to the [[Industrial Revolution]], including chalk pits both at Warren Farm and close to the Burford Bridge Hotel.<ref name=Bannister22/> The opening of the [[North Downs Line|Dorking to Reigate railway line]] at the bottom of the hill in 1849, enabled new quarry faces to be opened at [[Brockham]]<ref name=NHL_Brockham>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1021322}}</ref> and [[Betchworth]].<ref name=NHL_Betchworth/> Sidings were provided adjacent to the main line and there was an extensive network of narrow-gauge railway tracks at both sites.<ref name=NHL_Betchworth/><ref name=NHL_Brockham/> The [[Brockham Limeworks]] closed in 1935, however a battery of eight kilns (dating from 1870) still stands and is Grade II listed.<ref name=NHL_Brockham/> The larger [[Betchworth Quarry and Lime Kilns]] (approximately 1&nbsp;km to the east) closed in 1960 and a variety of different kiln types have been preserved and protected with a Grade II listing.<ref name=NHL_Betchworth/> The two sites have been designated as Nature Reserves and are managed by [[Surrey Wildlife Trust]].<ref name=SWT_Betchworth>{{cite web |url= https://www.surreywildlifetrust.org/nature-reserves/betchworth-quarry-lime-kilns |title= Betchworth Quarry & Lime Kilns |author=<!--Not stated--> |publisher= Surrey Wildlife Trust |access-date= 23 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=SWT_Brockham>{{cite web |url= https://www.surreywildlifetrust.org/nature-reserves/brockham-limeworks |title= Brockham Limeworks |author=<!--Not stated--> |publisher= Surrey Wildlife Trust |access-date= 23 October 2019}}</ref> A wide range of bat species now roost in the former kilns.<ref name=SWT_Betchworth/><ref name=SWT_Brockham/>\n\nGravel was quarried on the northern side of Headley Heath during the 18th and early 19th centuries, most likely to provide material for building local roads.\n\n==Ecology==\n===Conservation===\n[[File:Belted Galloway Cattle on Box Hill, Surrey.jpg|thumb|[[Belted Galloway]] cattle grazing the Burford Spur on the north western side of the hill.]]\nThe entirety of Box Hill lies within the [[Surrey Hills AONB|Surrey Hills Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.surreyhills.org/board/map-of-the-aonb/ |title= Map of the AONB |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= Surrey Hills AONB |publisher= Surrey Hills Society |access-date= 25 October 2019 }}</ref> The vast majority of the publicly accessible areas of the hill that are managed by the National Trust and Surrey Wildlife Trust, form part of the [[Mole Gap to Reigate Escarpment]] [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]] and have been designated a [[Special Area of Conservation]].<ref name=dsv>{{cite web|url=  https://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/SiteDetail.aspx?SiteCode=S1000977&SiteName=&countyCode=41&responsiblePerson=&SeaArea=&IFCAArea= |title=Designated Sites View: Mole Gap to Reigate Escarpment   | series= Sites of Special Scientific Interest|publisher=Natural England|accessdate = 9 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=map>{{cite web|url= https://magic.defra.gov.uk/MagicMap.aspx?startTopic=Designations&activelayer=sssiIndex&query=HYPERLINK%3D%271000977%27|title=Map of Mole Gap to Reigate Escarpment  |series= Sites of Special Scientific Interest|publisher=Natural England|accessdate= 9 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe chalk downland of Box Hill provides a habitat for a wide range of plant species, which in turn support a varied population of insect species. The alkaline soils are thin and nutrient poor, which prevents deeper-rooted lush grasses (with a high water demand) from dominating. Each square metre of chalk downland may support up to 40 different species.<ref name=Tuson-27>{{harvnb|Tuson|2013|p=27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/features/whats-special-about-chalk-grassland |title= What's special about chalk grassland? |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= National Trust |publisher= National Trust |access-date=  25 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nWithout careful management, the grassland would [[ecological succession|revert to woodland]] and so these areas of the hill are [[conservation grazing|grazed]] in order to prevent [[shrubland|scrub]] from becoming overestablished.<ref name=SWT_CG>{{cite web |url= https://www.surreywildlifetrust.org/what-we-do/restoring-surreys-nature/conservation-grazing |title= Conservation grazing |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= Surrey Wildlife Trust |publisher= Surrey Wildlife Trust |access-date=  25 October 2019}}</ref>{{refn|Although its spread is often considered undesirable, scrub provides valuable habitat for a range of invertebrates on Box Hill, including the [[Helix pomatia|Roman snail]], [[rufous grasshopper]] and the [[dark green fritillary]].<ref name=FOBH+NT_Woodland>{{cite web |url= http://www.friendsofboxhill.org.uk/what-we-do-3/conservation/ |title= Box Hill Woodland Plan 2009: The condition and habitat management of the woodland compartments of Box Hill |last= Dawson |first= Mark |last2= Creasey |first2= Peter |year= 2009 |website= Friends of Box Hill |publisher= Friends of Box Hill |location= Dorking |access-date= 27 October 2019}}</ref>|group=note}} Both the National Trust and Surrey Wildlife Trust use [[Belted Galloway]] cattle (affectionately nicknamed 'Belties'), which crop the grass less hard than other grazers and allow the more delicate wild flowers (including orchids) to flourish.<ref name=SWT_CG/><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/features/conservation-grazing |title= Conservation grazing |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= National Trust |publisher= National Trust |access-date=  25 October 2019}}</ref> At Betchworth Quarry, Surrey Wildlife Trust allows goats to graze, which can eat woodier plants such as [[Ulex europaeus|gorse]] and [[bramble]].<ref name=SWT_CG/> [[European rabbit|Rabbits]] also make a significant contribution to the control of scrub and coarse grasses on the hill, although their numbers have declined since the introduction of [[myxomatosis]] in 1953.<ref>{{harvnb|Chapman|Young|1979|p=95}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Olympic Rings Box Hill-by-Ian-Capper.jpg|thumb|[[Olympic symbols#Olympic rings|Olympic Rings]] were installed at the viewpoint in July 2012.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= London 2012: Box Hill Olympic road race rings unveiled |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-surrey-18920560 |work= BBC News |location= London |date= 20 July 2012 |access-date= 25 October 2012}}</ref>]]\nFor any conservation area, it is important to find a balance between the interests of people visiting and the needs of the wildlife that it seeks to protect. After the announcement that the Olympic cycling road races would be routed over the hill, concerns were expressed that habitats would be damaged during the event.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/olympics/olympics-road-race-not-in-our-box-hill-55729 |title= Olympics road race: Not in our Box Hill |last= Bingham |first= Keith |date= 15 December 2010 |website= Cycling Weekly |access-date= 25 October 2019 }}</ref> Scrub clearance along the side of the Zig Zag Road to provide space for spectators began in January 2012, after a pre-race survey (commissioned by the [[London Organising Committee of the Olympic and Paralympic Games]]) showed that the work was likely to increase biodiversity.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= London 2012: Box Hill woodland scrub cleared for spectators |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-surrey-17090065 |work= BBC News |location= London |date= 19 February 2012 |access-date= 25 October 2019 }}</ref> A second ecological survey, performed after the Games, showed that no significant damage had occurred, although some areas were subsequently reseeded.<ref>{{cite news |last= Martin |first= Guy |date= 3 August 2012 |title= 'Gold medal' for Box Hill cycling wildlife protection |url= https://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/local-news/gold-medal-box-hill-cycling-4809320 |work= Surrey Live |access-date= 25 October 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Biodiversity===\n{{multiple image\n | width = 110\n | footer = [[Dactylorhiza fuchsii|Common spotted]] (left) and [[Herminium monorchis|Musk]] (right) Orchids growing on Box Hill.\n | image1 = Common_Spotted_Orchid_(Dactylorhiza_fuchsii)_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1359262.jpg\n | alt1 = \n | caption1 = \n | image2 = Musk Orchid (Herminium monorchis) - geograph.org.uk - 863983.jpg\n | alt2 = \n | caption2 =\n }}\nThe chalk downland environment supports notable populations of [[bat]]s, [[lepidopterans]], [[orchids]] and the hill's [[namesake]], the box tree (''[[Buxus sempervirens]]'').<ref>[http://www.boxhill.org.uk/visitors/downland.html Box Hill Community Website] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080306220756/http://www.boxhill.org.uk/visitors/downland.html |date=6 March 2008 }} Retrieved 4 February 2008</ref> Box Hill also has over 40 species of butterflies and plants.\n\n====Orchids====\nA large number of species of [[orchid]] have been recorded on Box Hill, including [[Spiranthes spiralis|autumn lady's-tresses]], [[Ophrys apifera|bee orchids]], [[Neottia nidus-avis|bird's-nest orchids]], [[Epipactis helleborine|broad-leaved helleborines]], [[Dactylorhiza fuchsii|common spotted orchids]], [[Neottia ovata|common twayblades]], [[Gymnadenia conopsea|fragrant orchids]], [[Anacamptis pyramidalis|pyramidal orchids]] and [[Cephalanthera damasonium|white helleborines]].<ref>{{harvnb|Sankey|2000|p=3}}</ref>\n\n====Other wild flowers====\n[[Allium ursinum|Wild garlic]] grows alongside [[Hyacinthoides non-scripta|bluebells]] under the tree canopy beside the River Mole at the western edge of the hill, giving the area its distinctive smell in springtime.<ref name=FOBH+NT_Woodland/>\n\n====Trees====\n[[File:The Whites Box Hill- geograph.org.uk - 1503979.jpg|thumb|Yew and box trees growing on the west side of the hill.{{refn|The [[cut bank|cliff above the River Mole]] is so steep and the [[orthent|soil is so shallow]] that the bare chalk rock is exposed in several places.|group=note}}]]\nThe [[Buxus sempervirens|box]] and [[Taxus baccata|yew]] woodland, on the steep-sloping sides of the hill above the River Mole, is of international importance. Common [[Canopy (biology)|canopy-layer]] species include [[Fagus sylvatica|beech]], [[Fraxinus excelsior|ash]] and [[Quercus robur|oak]]. [[Understory|Understorey]] species include [[Ilex aquifolium|holly]], [[Corylus avellana|hazel]], [[Sambucus|elder]] and [[honeysuckle]].<ref name=FOBH+NT_Woodland/>\n\n[[Invasive species]] found on the hill include [[Buddleja|buddleia]], [[Prunus laurocerasus|cherry laurel]], [[Reynoutria japonica|Japanese knot weed]] and [[Solidago canadensis|Canadian goldenrod]]. [[Boxwood blight]], a [[pathogenic fungus|fungal disease]] caused by [[Cylindrocladium|''Cylindrocladium buxicola'']], is widespread.<ref name=FOBH+NT_Woodland/>\n\n====Bats====\nSeveral abandoned brick and concrete structures provide habitats for [[bat]]s and grills have been placed over their entrances to protect the roosting sites.<ref name=NHL_Betchworth/><ref name=NHL_Brockham/> Three species are known to inhabit The old Box Hill Fort: the [[brown long-eared bat]], the [[common noctule|noctule bat]] and [[Natterer's bat]].<ref>{{harvnb|Tuson|2013|p=22}}</ref> The brown long-eared bat, Natterer's bat, the [[whiskered bat]] and [[Daubenton's bat]] have been recorded at both Betchworth and Brockham quarries.<ref name=SWT_Betchworth/><ref name=SWT_Brockham/> [[Brandt's bat]] has been recorded at Betchworth;<ref name=SWT_Betchworth/> [[Bechstein's bat]] and the [[common pipistrelle]] have been recorded at Brockham.<ref name=SWT_Brockham/>\n\n====Butterflies and Moths====\n {{multiple image\n | width = 110\n | footer = [[Lysandra coridon|Chalkhill blue]] (left) and [[Melanargia galathea|Marbled White]] (right) butterflies on knapweed flowers on Box Hill.\n | image1 = Blue butterfly on Box Hill.jpg\n | alt1 = \n | caption1 = \n | image2 = Marbled white butterfly on Box Hill-by-Ian-Capper.jpg\n | alt2 = \n | caption2 = \n }}\nBox Hill supports 38 different species of butterflies.<ref name=Surrey_Skipper>{{cite web |url= https://butterfly-conservation.org/sites/default/files/56-autumn-2013.pdf |title= News from Box Hill |last= Jeffcoate |first= Gail |year= 2013 |website= Surrey Skipper |publisher= Butterfly Conservation |access-date= 25 October 2019}}</ref> Grassland species include the [[Epargyreus clarus|silver-spotted skipper]] and [[Lysandra coridon|chalkhill blue]].<ref name=Surrey_Skipper/> Scrubland species include the [[brown hairstreak]]<ref name=Surrey_Skipper/> and woodland species include the [[Speckled wood (butterfly)|speckled wood]] and the [[small pearl-bordered fritillary]].<ref>{{harvnb|Chapman|Young|1979|p=97}}</ref>\n\n[[Anthyllis vulneraria|Kidney vetch]], growing in the Zig Zag Valley, supports a population of the [[small blue]] butterfly.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.molevalley.gov.uk/CausewayDocList/DocServlet?ref=MO/2012/0536&docid=404511 |title= Box Hill Ecological Report, November, 2011 |website= Mole Valley District Council |publisher= Mole Valley District Council |access-date= 25 October 2019 }}</ref>\n\nRare moth species found on the hill include the [[Aspitates gilvaria|straw belle]], [[Scotopteryx bipunctaria|chalk carpet]], [[Scopula ornata|lace border]], [[Synanthedon andrenaeformis|orange-tailed clearwing]] and the [[Phyllonorycter scabiosella|Surrey midget moth]].<ref name=Surrey_Skipper/>\n\n====Other insects====\nThe hill has given its name to a species of [[Coreidae|squash bug]], now found throughout south-east England.<ref name=british_bugs/>\n\n==Recreation==\n[[File:Box_Hill_Salomons_Memorial.jpg|thumb|Salomons Memorial viewpoint, looking south, in 2010]]\n\n===Box Hill Country Park===\nThe western part of Box Hill, managed by the [[National Trust]], was designated a [[Country Park]] in 1971.<ref name=Littledate5>{{harvnb|Littledale|Locock|Sankey|1984|p=5}}</ref> In the early 1980s, some of the outbuildings associated with the old Box Hill Fort were taken over by the National Trust for use as a visitor centre, gift shop and servery.<ref>{{harvnb|Littledale|Locock|Sankey|1984|p=24}}</ref> In 2011, a ''Natural Play Trail'' was constructed close to the visitor centre, cofunded by the National Trust and the Friends of Box Hill.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.surreylife.co.uk/out-about/walks/national-trust-s-new-natural-play-trail-at-box-hill-1-1644611 |url-access= |title= National Trust's new natural play trail at Box Hill |last= Brien |first= Emma |date= 24 November 2011 |website= Surrey Life |access-date= 29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn the hill there are [[Parking lot|car parks]]<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Box Hill, Surrey: walk of the week |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/activityandadventure/walkingholidays/8356605/Box-Hill-Surrey-walk-of-the-week.html |date= 2 March 2011 |access-date= 19 October 2019 |work= Daily Telegraph }}</ref> and a panoramic view over the [[Weald]] towards the [[South Downs]] may be enjoyed from the Salomons Memorial (more commonly known as the viewpoint).{{refn|A common misconception is that the Salomons Memorial (at {{convert|172|m|ft|abbr=on}} [[Ordnance Datum|above OD]]) marks the highest point of the hill, however the land continues to rise to the east. The true summit of the hill is at Betchworth Clumps at {{convert|224|m|ft|abbr=on}} above OD and is currently occupied by a water tower and transmitter mast.<ref name=Wooldridge_1957_79/> |group=note}}<ref name=Littledate5/> Juniper Top, on the northern side of the hill, offers views to the northwest towards [[Windsor Castle]].<ref name=Littledate5/>\n\nThe Country Park is crisscrossed by a large number of [[footpath]]s and [[bridle path|bridleways]], and there are several signposted, self-guided trails.\n\n===Cycling===\n{{Infobox cycling hill climb\n| name = Zig Zag Road\n| image = RW1_3172.jpg\n| image_size = 240\n| image_alt =\n| caption = Prudential Ride-London 100: Amateur cyclists ascending the Zig Zag Road (July 2016)\n| max_elevation_m = 175\n| location = Box Hill, Surrey\n| start = \n| altitude_m = 120\n| length_km = 2.5\n| gradient = 5.0\n| maxgradient = 7.3\n| website = [https://www.surreyhills.org/discover-route/box-hill-olympic-route/ Box Hill Olympic Circuit] }} \nBox Hill has been popular with cyclists since the 1880s<ref>{{cite journal |year= 1883 |title=Unknown title |journal= London bicycle club gazette |volume= 6 |page= 147 }}</ref> and by the 1890s, Dorking Cycle Club was organising camps for amateur cyclists from across the south east of England.<ref name=Tuson-10>{{harvnb|Tuson|2013|p=10}}</ref>{{refn|In February 2017 the ''Sunday Times'' newspaper identified Box Hill as one of the top six rural cycling accident blackspots in the UK, stating that seven accidents on the Zig Zag Road had been reported to the Police in 2015.<ref>{{cite journal |last= Hookham |first= M |date= 12 February 2017 |title= Roundabout is UK's deadliest spot for cyclists |journal= The Sunday Times  |location= London |publisher= News International }}</ref>|group=note}} The [[Cycling at the 2012 Summer Olympics|2012 Summer Olympic cycling]] road races included {{convert|15.8|km|mi|adj=on|abbr=on}} mid-race circuits of Box Hill.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.surreyhills.org/discover-route/box-hill-olympic-route/ |title= Box Hill Olympic Route |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= Surrey Hills |access-date= 17 October 2019}}</ref> An estimated 15,000 spectators travelled to the hill on 28 July 2012 to watch the men's race, which included nine circuits<ref name=Tuson-11>{{harvnb|Tuson|2013|p=11}}</ref> and the following day, competitors in the women's race climbed Box Hill twice.<ref name=Tuson-12>{{harvnb|Tuson|2013|p=12}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian1\"/>\n\nThe {{convert|15.8|km|mi|adj=on|abbr=on}} Box Hill Olympic circuit is generally cycled in an [[clockwise|anticlockwise]] direction and begins to the south of the village of [[Mickleham, Surrey|Mickleham]] with an ascent of the hill via the Zig Zag Road. From the National Trust Visitor Centre, the route turns eastwards, running along the escarpment and through the urban area of Box Hill village, reaching a maximum elevation of {{convert|216|m|ft}} above [[Ordnance Datum]]. After {{convert|6.6|km|mi}} the route turns northwest along the B2033, passing through the village of [[Headley, Surrey|Headley]]. After {{convert|9.5|km|mi}}, the circuit begins a continuous descent to the valley of the [[River Mole]], passing to the south of [[Leatherhead]], before turning southwards again through Mickleham to return to the start.\n\nThe Zig Zag Road is a steady climb of {{convert|120|m}} over {{convert|2.5|km}} and has, although on a much smaller scale, been likened to the [[Alpe d'Huez]] in the French Alps.<ref>{{harvnb|Warren|2010|p=37}}</ref>{{refn|On 15 August 2014 Ciaran O'Hara and Roger Barr cycled up the hill 73 times to complete a challenge known as ''Everesting'', in which cyclists repeatedly climb a hill to gain the same vertical elevation (8848&nbsp;m) as [[Mount Everest]].<ref>{{cite journal |last= Smurthwaite |first= T |date= 16 August 2014 |title= Everest attempt succeeds at Box Hill |url= http://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/local-news/everest-attempt-succeeds-box-hill-7627204 |journal= getSurrey |publisher= Trinity Mirror|accessdate= 30 August 2014 }}</ref>|group=note}} The exact date of construction is uncertain: The road first appears on the Ordnance Survey map of 1869,<ref name=Bannister24>{{harvnb|Bannister|1999|p=24}}</ref> but is not shown in a [[watercolor painting|watercolour painting]] dated 1861 by [[William Leighton Leitch]], which is owned by the [[Royal Collection]].<ref name=Littledale15/><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.rct.uk/collection/923641/box-hill-surrey |title= Box Hill, Surrey \u2013 WILLIAM LEIGHTON LEITCH, 1861 |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= The Royal Collection |publisher= Royal Collection Trust |access-date= 14 October 2019}}</ref> The Zig Zag Road is not a public [[right of way]] and is closed for one day each year by the National Trust, to preserve its [[private road]] status.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Box Hill May Get Toll |work= The Times |location= London |date= 18 January 1962 |issue= 55292 |page= 12}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the 2011 [[London Prepares series]], the [[London\u2013Surrey Cycle Classic]] for professional cyclists was organised to test the Olympic course.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cycling/14521435.stm|title=Mark Cavendish wins London 2012 road race test event|author=Ollie Williams|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC Sport|date=14 August 2011|accessdate=18 August 2011}}</ref> The [[Prudential RideLondon-Surrey 100]] and [[London\u2013Surrey Classic]], for amateur and professional cyclists respectively, have taken place annually following the Games and, although the course has undergone several alterations from the 2012 Olympic course, the two races always include a climb of Box Hill.\n\n===High Ashurst===\n{{Main|High Ashurst}}\nHigh Ashurst is an [[outdoor education]] and [[outdoor recreation|activity]] centre on the northern side of Box Hill, adjacent to Headley Heath. The centre is run by Surrey Outdoor Learning and Development on behalf of [[Surrey County Council]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.surreyoutdoorlearning.uk |title= Surrey Outdoor Learning and Development |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= |access-date= 16 October 2019 }}</ref> Previously the site comprised the grounds of a country house, which was demolished in the 1970s, having been derelict for several decades.\n\n===Boidier Hurst campsite===\nThe District [[The Scout Association|Scout Associations]] of [[Leatherhead]] and [[Epsom and Ewell]] own a {{convert|10|acre|ha|adj=on|order=flip}} [[campsite]], located between Box Hill village and Headley Heath.<ref name=Boidier_index>{{cite web |url= http://www.boidierhurst.org.uk/index.html |title= Boidier Hurst Scout campsite |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= Boidier Hurst Scout campsite |access-date= 1 March 2020 }}</ref><ref name=Boidier_site>{{cite web |url= http://www.boidierhurst.org.uk/the-site.html |title= The site |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= Boidier Hurst Scout campsite |access-date= 1 March 2020 }}</ref> There are 11 areas for pitching groups of tents, set within [[coppicing|coppiced]] [[Aesculus hippocastanum|chestnut]] woodland. Washing, toilet facilities and a kitchen are available.<ref name=Boidier_site/><ref name=Boidier_Manly>{{cite web |url= http://www.boidierhurst.org.uk/manly-building.html |title= The Manly Building |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= Boidier Hurst Scout campsite |access-date= 1 March 2020 }}</ref> Use of Boidier Hurst is restricted to members of The Scout Association, [[Girlguiding|The Guide Association]] and to local school groups on [[The Duke of Edinburgh's Award|Duke of Edinburgh's Award]] expeditions.<ref name=Boidier_index/>\n\n==Sights==\n===Broadwood's Folly===\n[[File:Broadwood's_Tower-cropped.jpg|thumb|Broadwood's Folly was built in around 1820.<ref name=NHL_Broadwood>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1391454}}</ref> Part of the Zig Zag Road is visible to the right of the tower.]]\nThe circular flint tower located on the northern tip of Lodge Hill was built for the piano maker [[Broadwood and Sons|Thomas Broadwood]], who purchased [[Juniper Hall]] in 1815.<ref>{{harvnb|Wainwright|1982|p=338}}</ref><ref name=BLB_Broadwood>{{cite web |url= http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-494323-the-broadwood-folly-at-juniper-hall-dork |title= The Broadwood Folly at Juniper Hall, Mickleham |author= Goodge M |year= 2005 |publisher= British Listed Buildings |accessdate=28 April 2011}}</ref> It is approximately {{convert|8|m|ft}} high and originally had two internal floors, linked by a spiral staircase. The original doorway is visible on the east side, but has been sealed with rough flints. An avenue of beech trees linked the folly to Juniper Hall, although these were destroyed by the [[Great Storm of 1987]].<ref name=NHL_Broadwood/> The tower may have been built to commemorate the [[Battle of Waterloo]].<ref>{{cite book |last1= Headley |first1= Gwyn |last2= Meulenkamp |first2= Wim |year= 1986 |title= Follies: A National Trust Guide |location= London |publisher= Cape |isbn= 9780224027908 }}</ref>\n\nA [[sparkling wine]], produced by [[Denbies Wine Estate]] for the [[Lidl]] supermarket chain, has been named after the folly.<ref>{{cite news |last= Williams |first= David |date= 18 September 2016 |title= National treasures: Welcome to the new world of English and Welsh wines |url= https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2016/sep/18/six-of-the-best-english-wines |work= The Guardian |location= London |access-date= 26 October 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Labilliere's Grave===\n{{Main|Peter Labilliere}}\n[[File:Peter Labelliere's grave, Box Hill.JPG|upright|thumb|Labilliere's tombstone]]\n\n[[Peter Labilliere]] was born in [[Dublin]] on 30 May 1725 to a family of French [[Huguenot]] descent. He joined the British Army at the age of 14, becoming a major in 1760.<ref>{{harvnb|Lander|2000|pp=7\u20138}}</ref> After leaving the army he became a political agitator and was accused in 1775 of bribing British troops not to fight in the American War of Independence, although he was never tried for treason.<ref name=Lander_20-21>{{harvnb|Lander|2000|pp=20\u201321}}</ref>\n\nAfter moving to Dorking in around 1789,<ref name=Lander_20-21/> Labilliere often visited Box Hill to meditate.<ref name=Lander_35-36>{{harvnb|Lander|2000|pp=35\u201336}}</ref> With old age he became increasingly eccentric and neglected his own personal hygiene to such an extent that he acquired the nickname \"the walking dung-hill\".<ref name=Lander_35-36/> He died on 6 June 1800.<ref name=Timbs>{{harvnb|Timbs|1877}}</ref> In accordance with his wishes he was [[Burial#Inverted burial|buried head downwards]], on 11 June on the western side of Box Hill above The Whites. In the presence of a crowd of thousands that included visitors from London as well as the local \"quality gentry\",<ref name=Timbs/><ref>[https://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/nostalgia/major-peter-labelliere-strange-history-13643026 Major Peter Labelliere: Strange history of man buried upside down atop Box Hill], Surrey Mirror, by W. H. Chouler, July 1963</ref> Labilliere was buried without any religious ceremony, having reportedly said that the world was \"topsy-turvey\" and that it would be righted in the end if he were interred thus. But this preference was not mentioned in his \"Book of Devotions\": rather he there said that he wished to emulate the example of [[Saint Peter|St Peter]], who was [[Cross of St. Peter|crucified upside-down]] according to tradition.<ref>{{harvnb|Lander|2000|pp=39\u201340}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last= Gittings |first= Clare |date= 20 November 2017 |title= Eccentric or enlightened? Unusual burial and commemoration in England, 1689\u00a0\u2013\u00a01823 |journal= Mortality |volume= 12 |issue= 4 |pages= 321\u2013349 |doi= 10.1080/13576270701609667}}</ref>\n\nThe current memorial stone on Box Hill is not believed to mark the exact location of his burial (which is thought to be several metres to the west on a steep incline). There are two errors on the stone itself: He was buried in ''June'' 1800 (rather than July) and all surviving manuscripts indicate that he spelt his name Lab'''i'''lliere (rather than Lab'''e'''lliere).<ref>{{harvnb|Lander|2000|p=6}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=No |first=Doilum |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/doilum/387839851/ |title=Box Hill, Surrey sur Flickr : partage de photos ! |publisher=Flickr.com |accessdate=27 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Summit===\nThe highest point is on Box Hill is Betchworth Clumps at {{convert|224|m|ft|abbr=on}} [[Ordnance Datum|above OD]], immediately to the east of Box Hill village.<ref name=Wooldridge_1957_79/> The summit is densely wooded to conceal a [[water tower]] and [[Radio masts and towers|transmitter mast]], neither of which are accessible to the public.\n\nThe concrete water tower was built in 1930 by East Surrey Water, the forerunner of [[SES Water]]. The structure was refurbished in 2009 to extend its working life by at least 25 years; modifications included the relining of the water bowl, repair of cracks in the walls and roof, as well as the provision of a new access staircase.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.edie.net/library/CRL-gets-started-on-water-tower-repairs/5046 |title= CRL gets started on water tower repairs |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 10 June 2009 |website= edie.net |access-date= 1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe 30m-high mobile phone mast was constructed in 2003 and is operated by [[Vodafone]] and [[EE Limited]].\n\n===Weypole and Stepping Stones===\n[[File:Stepping stones.jpg|right|thumb|The Stepping Stones at the foot of Box Hill. The photograph is taken from the west bank of the Mole, looking across the river to the Weypole.]]\nThe ''Weypole'' (or ''Waypole'') is a roughly semi-circular {{convert|2.4|ha|acre|abbr=on|adj=on}} area of level ground at the foot of Box Hill, between The Whites and the River Mole.<ref name=\"NT_acq\"/> The area was originally part of the grounds of Burford Lodge, built by John Eckersall in 1776, and the apple and cherry trees in the area suggest that it was used as an orchard for a time.<ref>{{harvnb|Chapman|Young|1979|p=164}}</ref> The Burford Lodge estate was later owned by the horticulturalist [[Sir Trevor Lawrence, 2nd Baronet|Sir Trevor Lawrence]], who created a garden along the banks of the Mole for his collection of orchids.<ref>{{harvnb|Chadwick|Chadwick|2006|p=121}}</ref>\n\nA ford across the River Mole is thought to have existed here since prehistoric times.<ref>{{harvnb|Ashton|Blight|2006|p=65}}</ref> The ''way-pole'' was a notched post secured in the riverbed, to indicate the depth of the water.<ref>{{cite journal |author=A Son of the Marshed |year=1890 |title=A Surrey River |journal= The Living Age |volume= 185 |issue=2395 |pages=486\u2013497 |publisher=Littell}}</ref> Stepping stones at this site are first recorded in 1841 and they may have been installed by an owner of Burford Lodge to facilitate access to the Weypole orchard.<ref>{{harvnb|Brayley|Britton|1841|p=179}}</ref> The current stones were dedicated on 11 September 1946 by Prime Minister [[Clement Attlee]], at the request of [[James Chuter Ede]], local politician and Attlee's Home Secretary,<ref>Chuter Ede papers collection, Surrey History Centre, 6408/13</ref> replacing those destroyed during World War 2 as an anti-invasion measure.<ref name=Telegraph_walk/><ref>{{cite journal |year= 1946 |title= Picture of the Week |journal= Life |volume= 21 |issue= 13 |page= 36 |publisher= Time Inc.}}</ref> The spot is popular with both anglers and families, although swimming is strongly discouraged. The stones give their name to the pub in the nearby village of [[Westhumble]].\n\n===Other===\nThe [[Burford Bridge Hotel]] and [[Juniper Hall]] Field Studies Centre lie at the foot of Box Hill close to the river Mole. Both are rich in historical associations with famous visitors and residents.\n\n==Notable former residents==\n===John Logie Baird===\n[[John Logie Baird]] (1888-1946), the inventor of the first working television system, lived at Swiss Cottage from 1929 until 1932.<ref>{{harvnb|Burns|2000|page=205}}</ref> Baird conducted some of his experiments on Box Hill,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-global/w-localtoyou/w-south_east/w-south_east-countryside/w-south_east-places-north_downs/w-south_east-places-north_downs-box_hill_headley_heath.htm |title=South East &#124; Box Hill & Headley Heath |publisher=National Trust |date=17 November 2011 |accessdate=27 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110911215852/http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-global/w-localtoyou/w-south_east/w-south_east-countryside/w-south_east-places-north_downs/w-south_east-places-north_downs-box_hill_headley_heath.htm |archivedate=11 September 2011  }}</ref> including his Noctovisor,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://geocities.com/neveyaakov/electro_science/baird.html |title=Baird |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=27 October 2009 |accessdate=27 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091027123028/http://geocities.com/neveyaakov/electro_science/baird.html |archivedate=27 October 2009 }}</ref> an infra-red viewing device.\n\n===George Meredith===\n[[File:George_Meredith's_Home.jpg|thumb|George Meredith and family members, photographed in the rear garden of Flint Cottage, Box Hill.]]\nThe author [[George Meredith]] (1828-1909) lived in Flint Cottage from 1868 until his death. He built a chalet in the garden in which he wrote. Today the house is protected by a Grade II listing and is not accessible to the public.<ref name=FlintCott>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1278478}}</ref>\n\nThe part of the hill immediately opposite the cottage is known as ''Barrie's Bank'', supposedly because the author [[J. M. Barrie]] waited there, while summoning the courage to introduce himself to Meredith.\n\n==Registered Charities==\nThe [[National Trust]] owns around half of the land on Box Hill (principally the Country Park in the west and Headley Heath in the north-east). [[Surrey Wildlife Trust]] manage [[Brockham Limeworks]] (owned by [[Surrey County Council]]) as well as [[Betchworth Quarry and Lime Kilns]] (privately owned).<ref name=SWT_Betchworth/><ref name=SWT_Brockham/>  Both Trusts rely on the support of volunteer groups, working alongside paid employees, to carry out conservation and education work.\n\nThe ''Friends of Box Hill'' (FoBH) is a local organisation, which supports the National Trust in its work in the Country Park. Several of its members advise the Trust on its wildlife management plans and the FoBH also fund specific projects, including the purchase of equipment and improvement of visitor facilities. They also organise a programme of social events, which includes regular talks by Trust staff.<ref name=FoBH_WWD>{{cite web |url= http://www.friendsofboxhill.org.uk/what-we-do-3/ |title= What we do |website= Friends of Box Hill |access-date= 29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Friends of Headley Heath'' (FoHH) coordinate volunteer working parties to assist National Trust Rangers and also run a series of social events.<ref name=FoHH>{{cite web |url= http://www.headleysurrey.org.uk/fohh.htm |title= Friends of Headley Heath |website= Headley Village Website |access-date= 29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n(Both the FoBH and FoHH are independent of the National Trust.<ref name=FoBH_WWD/><ref name=FoHH/>)\n\n==Transport Links==\n===Public Transport===\n[[Box Hill & Westhumble railway station|Box Hill & Westhumble]] is the closest railway station to the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] Country Park (approximately 500 m) and is served by trains from both [[London Victoria station|London Victoria]] and [[London Waterloo station|London Waterloo]]. Both [[Dorking Deepdene railway station|Dorking Deepdene]] and [[Dorking railway station|Dorking (Main)]] stations are around 1&nbsp;km from the south western corner of the hill. [[Betchworth railway station|Betchworth]] station is at the south eastern corner of the hill.\n\n[[File:Box Hill bus and bus stop.JPG|thumb|A [[Sunray Travel]] bus passing the visitor centre. Inset left shows the special wooden National Trust bus stop, with logo engraved.]]\nBox Hill is served by local and [[London Buses route 465|London]] bus routes.<ref name=\"localbus\">[http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-vh/w-visits/w-findaplace/w-boxhill/w-boxhill-gettingthere.htm ''Getting there''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080215093704/http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-vh/w-visits/w-findaplace/w-boxhill/w-boxhill-gettingthere.htm |date=15 February 2008 }} from The National Trust website. Retrieved 12 February 2008</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.surreycc.gov.uk/sccwebsite/sccwspublications.nsf/WebLookupFileResourcesByUNID/docidF9D4ED4E860D1F9F8025729600568D66?openDocument |title=Surrey County Council \u2013 516 bus timetable via Box Hill visitor centre |accessdate=27 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628230635/http://www.surreycc.gov.uk/sccwebsite/sccwspublications.nsf/WebLookupFileResourcesByUNID/docidF9D4ED4E860D1F9F8025729600568D66?openDocument |archivedate=28 June 2011  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.surreycc.gov.uk/sccwebsite/sccwspublications.nsf/WebLookupFileResourcesByUNID/docid2D0E4B78B92134EC802572960054AE40?openDocument |title=Surrey County Council \u2013 465 bus timetable via foot of Box Hill |accessdate=27 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628230715/http://www.surreycc.gov.uk/sccwebsite/sccwspublications.nsf/WebLookupFileResourcesByUNID/docid2D0E4B78B92134EC802572960054AE40?openDocument |archivedate=28 June 2011  }}</ref>\n\n===Access for Motor Vehicles===\nAccess to the National Trust Country Park from the [[A24 road (England)|A24]] dual carriageway is via the B2209 and the Zig Zag Road, however this route is not suitable for buses or coaches. Alternative access is via the B2033 and Boxhill Road, which leads through Box Hill village and approaches the Country Park from the west. Headley Heath is directly accessible from the B2033.\n\n===Cycle Routes===\n[[National Cycle Route 22]] runs along the northern boundary of the hill via Lodgebottom Road and Headley Lane, before turning south along the [[A24 road (England)|A24]] close to the western boundary. The Surrey Cycleway approached Box Hill from the west via Westhumble, before turning to the south towards Dorking.\n\n===Walking===\nThe [[North Downs Way]] [[long-distance footpath]] from [[Farnham]] to [[Dover]], crosses the River Mole at the Stepping Stones and then runs from west to east at the top of the scarp slope, passing in front of the Salomons Memorial.<ref>{{cite book |last= Saunders |first= Colin |year= 2016 |title= North Downs Way|location= London |publisher= Aurum Press |isbn= 9781781315002 |series= National Trail Guides }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Thames Down Link]] follows the course of [[Stane Street (Chichester)|Stane Street]] across Mickleham Downs, to the north of Box Hill, and meets the [[North Downs Way]] close to the [[Burford Bridge Hotel]].\n\n==Cultural references==\n[[File:A View of Box Hill, Surrey 1733.jpg|thumb|right|''A view of Box Hill, Surrey'' (1733) by [[George Lambert (English painter)|George Lambert]] \u2013 held by [[The Tate]].]]\n\n===Art===\n[[File:George Lambert - Box Hill, Surrey, with Dorking in the distance - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|right|''Box Hill, Surrey with Dorking in the distance'' (1733) by [[George Lambert (English painter)|George Lambert]] \u2013 held by the [[Yale Center for British Art]].]]\nIn 1733, [[George Lambert (English painter)|George Lambert]] painted two views of Box Hill, now held by [[The Tate]]<ref>[http://www.tate.org.uk/servlet/ViewWork?cgroupid=999999961&workid=8266&searchid=15987&tabview=work \"A view of Box Hill, Surrey\"] at [[Tate|The Tate]]</ref> and the [[Yale Center for British Art]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://collections.britishart.yale.edu/vufind/Record/1669128 |title= Box Hill, Surrey, with Dorking in the distance |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= Yale Center for British Art |publisher= Yale University  |access-date= 13 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n''The Stonebreaker'' (1857 -1858), a painting by [[John Brett (artist)|John Brett]] (1831\u20131902), depicts a young boy breaking stones for road mending, with Box Hill in the background.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/walker/collections/paintings/19c/item-236997.aspx |title= The Stonebreaker JOHN BRETT, 1857\u20131858 |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= Walker Art Gallery |publisher= National Museums Liverpool  |access-date= 13 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Brett The Stonebreaker.jpg|thumb|right|Box Hill forms the backdrop to ''The Stonebreaker'', painted by John Brett in 1857\u20131858.]]\n\nA watercolour entitled \u2018'Box Hill, Surrey'\u2019 dated 1861 by [[William Leighton Leitch]] (1804\u20131883), which depicts the view looking northwards from the Old Fort before the Zig Zag Road was built, is part of the [[Royal Collection]].<ref name=Littledale15/><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.rct.uk/collection/923641/box-hill-surrey |title= Box Hill, Surrey \u2013 WILLIAM LEIGHTON LEITCH, 1861 |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= The Royal Collection |publisher= Royal Collection Trust |access-date= 14 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Box Hill Road River, a highly curved, {{convert|100|m|ft|adj=on}} line painted onto the surface of the Zig Zag Road by the British sculptor and [[land art]]ist [[Richard Long (artist)|Richard Long]], was commissioned jointly by the London 2012 Festival and the National Trust to celebrate the route of the Olympic Cycling road races.<ref>{{cite news |last= Jones |first= Jonathan |date= 30 July 2012 |title= Olympics 2012: Richard Long's cycling art shows British landscape at its best |url= https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/jonathanjonesblog/2012/jul/30/olympics-richard-long-cycling-art |work= The Guardian |access-date= 15 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Literature===\n\n[[John Evelyn]] notes in his ''[[John Evelyn's Diary|Diary]]'' in 1662 that Box Hill was frequented by the ladies and gentlemen from nearby [[Epsom]] spa.<ref>Noted in Alice M. Coats, ''Garden Shrubs and Their Histories'' (1964) 1992, ''s.v.'' \"Buxus\".</ref>\n\nThe 'picnic scene', a pivotal passage of [[Jane Austen]]'s novel ''[[Emma (novel)|Emma]]'' is set at Box Hill.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Austen |first1=Jane |title=Emma |publisher=Public Domain |url=https://www.gutenberg.org/files/158/158-h/158-h.htm |accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref>\n[[File: Hammond-Emma22 (recadr\u00e9e).jpg|thumb|upright|The Picnic at Box Hill: Pen-and-ink drawing by Chris Hammond (1860\u20131900) for the 1898 edition of ''[[Emma (novel)|Emma]]'' by [[Jane Austen]].]]\n\nIn ''England: A Nation'', (London: R. Brimley Johnson, 1904), edited by Lucian Oldershaw, and in a chapter entitled \"The Patriotic Idea\" written by [[G. K. Chesterton]], the beauty of Box Hill violated by an invading army is used to express a healthy patriot's love for his nation as opposed to the jingoistic nationalism of tabloid newspapers:<ref name=Oldershaw>{{cite book |last= Chesterton |first=GK |author-link= G. K. Chesterton |editor-last= Oldershaw |editor-first= Lucian |title=England: A Nation |publisher= R. Brimley Johnson |location= London |date=1904 |pages=100\u2013110 |chapter=Chapter 1: The Patriotic Idea |url= https://archive.org/stream/englandnationbei00patrrich/englandnationbei00patrrich_djvu.txt}}</ref> <blockquote>\"But just as a man who has been in love will find it difficult to write a whole frantic epic about a flirtation, so all that kind of rhetoric about the Union Jack and the Anglo-Saxon blood, which has made amusing the journalism of this country for the last six years, will be merely impossible to the man who has for one moment called up before himself what would be the real sensation of hearing that a foreign army was encamped on Box Hill.\"<ref name=Oldershaw/></blockquote>\n\nMystery author [[Cyril Hare]] sets his 1954 novel, ''That Yew Tree's Shade'' (published in the U.S. as ''Death Walks the Woods''), at \"Yew Hill\", which Hare admits in an introduction is modelled on Box Hill.<ref>{{cite book |last= Hare |first= Cyril |year= 1954 |title= That Yew Tree's Shade |location= London |publisher= Faber |isbn= 9780571138005 |author-link= Cyril Hare}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n\nBritish biker rock band [[Dumpy's Rusty Nuts]] released a single called ''Box Hill or Bust'' in 1984.  The song is something of a cult anthem for bikers and reflects the popularity of Box Hill among the biking community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/dumpys-rusty-nuts-mn0001181852|title=Dumpy's Rusty Nuts \u2013 Biography|first=Steve|last=Huey|publisher=Allmusic|accessdate=17 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Richard Thompson (musician)|Richard Thompson]]'s song ''[[1952 Vincent Black Lightning]]'' (released in 1991), Box Hill is the location to which James and Red Molly ride on James' motorcycle.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://americansongwriter.com/2012/08/1952-vincent-black-lightning-by-richard-thompson/|title='1952 Vincent Black Lightning,' By Richard Thompson |work=American Songwriter|date=12 August 2012|accessdate=7 December 2016}}</ref> In [[cover version]]s of this song by American musicians, Box Hill is sometimes changed to [[Knoxville]], a city in [[Tennessee]].\n\n[[Ben Watt]]'s 1983 debut album ''[[North Marine Drive]]'' contained a song entitled \"On Box Hill.\"\n\nActor and singer [[Tom Felton]]'s song called ''Time Well Spent'' mentions him going to \"chill out on Box Hill\".<ref>{{cite web |url= http://feltbeats.com/music/time-well-spent-lyrics/ |title= Time Well Spent \u2013 Tom Felton |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= Feltbeats.com |publisher= Feltbeats.com  |access-date= 13 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Film===\n\nThe racing scenes during the opening credits of the 1968 film [[Chitty Chitty Bang Bang]] were filmed on the Zig Zag Road.<ref>{{cite news |first= Martin |last= Cholton |title= 10 things you didn\u2019t know about Chitty Chitty Bang Bang |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/chitty-chitty-bang-bang-50-anniversary-dick-van-dyke-a8680251.html |date= 20 December 2018 |access-date= 19 October 2019 |work= The Independent }}</ref>\n\nThe 2012 British film ''[[Berberian Sound Studio]]'' contains a short [[Story within a story#Nested films|film-within-the-film]] \u2013 a spoof 1970s-style documentary about the outstanding natural and man-made features of Box Hill.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/aug/30/berberian-sound-studio-review |title= Berberian Sound Studio \u2013 review |author= Peter Bradshaw |date= 30 August 2012 |website= The Guardian |author-link= Peter Bradshaw |access-date= 13 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==In the news==\nIn 1995 teenager [[Disappearance of Ruth Wilson|Ruth Wilson]] disappeared after being dropped off by taxi on Box Hill.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2002/dec/15/features.magazine57|title=The vanishing|last=Bright|first=Martin|date=2002-12-15|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-06-25}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 a body that had lain undiscovered for two years was found on Box Hill.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/local-news/body-box-hill-identified-missing-4721925|title=Body on Box Hill identified as missing man|last=Martin|first=Guy|date=2013-05-28|work=getsurrey|access-date=2018-06-24}}</ref> It was identified as missing teacher Brian Hynard who had left two suicide notes before disappearing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-vanishing-bs252s00wcv|title=The vanishing|last=Boggan|first=Steve|date=2013-08-11|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=2018-06-24|language=en|issn=0956-1382}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n[[File:Headley Heath (geograph 5380881).jpg|thumb|upright|Pond on Headley Heath.]]\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |title= The South East of England: Exploring Woodland |last1= Ashton |first1= S |last2= Blight |first2= G |year= 2006 | publisher= Frances Lincoln |location= London |isbn= 978-0-7112-2659-3 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= The Box Hill Book of Archaeology |last= Bannister |first=NR |year= 1999 |publisher= Friends of Box Hill |location= Dorking, Surrey |isbn= 0-9534430-1-9 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= The London Mobilisation Centres |last1= Beanse |first1= Alec |last2= Gill |first2= Roger  |year= 2011 |isbn=978-0954845377 |publisher= David Moore |location= Hampshire |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= Box Hill, a descriptive poem |last= Beavan |first= E |year= 1777 |publisher= Wilkie |location= London |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= The Old Road |url= https://archive.org/details/theoldroad00belluoft |last= Belloc |first=H |authorlink=Hilaire Belloc |year= 1911 |publisher= Constable and Company |location= London |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= A topographical history of Surrey |last1= Brayley |first1= E. W. |authorlink1=Edward Wedlake Brayley |last2= Britton |first2=J. |authorlink2=John Britton (antiquary) |year= 1841 | publisher= Dorking |location= Surrey |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1= Burns |first1= RW |title= John Logie Baird: Television pioneer |series= History of Technology |volume= 28 |year= 2000 |publisher= Institution of Electrical Engineers |location= London |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Chadwick |first1=AA |last2=Chadwick |first2=AE |title= The Classic Cattleyas |year= 2006 |publisher= Timber Press |location= Portland, Oregon |isbn= 978-0-88192-764-1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= Box Hill |last1= Chapman |first1= GM |last2= Young |first2= RHD |year= 1979 |publisher= Serendip |location= Lyme Regis |isbn= 0-9504143-1-X|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1= Headley |first1= G |last2= Meulenkamp |first2= W  |title= Follies: A National Trust Guide |year= 1986 |publisher= Jonathan Cape |location= London |isbn= 0-224-02105-2  | ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1= Lander |first1= J |title= Peter Labilliere: The Man Buried Upside Down on Box Hill |year= 2000 |publisher= Post Press |location= Chertsey |isbn= 978-0-9532424-1-2 | ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1= Littledale |first1= H |last2= Locock |first2= L M |last3= Sankey | first3=J H P\n  |title= Box Hill |year= 1984 |publisher= Box Hill Management Committee |location= Dorking, Surrey | ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book  |last= Margary |first= Ivan D |authorlink= Ivan Margary |title= Roman Ways in the Weald |publisher= J M Dent |year= 1948 |location= London |isbn =0-460-07742-2 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1= Mountford |first1= F |title= The Box Hill Guide |year= 1974 |publisher= Mountford |location= Tadworth |isbn= 0-9503540-0-7 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= The Box Hill Book of Orchids |last= Sankey |first= A |year= 2000 |publisher= Friends of Box Hill |location= Dorking, Surrey |isbn= 0-9534430-2-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Shepperd |first=Ronald |title= Micklam the story of a parish |year= 1991 |publisher= Mickleham Publications |isbn= 0-9518305-0-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= English Eccentrics and Eccentricities |last= Timbs |first= J |year= 1877 |volume=1 |publisher= Chatto and Windus |location= London |url= https://archive.org/details/englisheccentric50439gut |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= Box Hill |last= Tuson |first= Dan |year= 2013 |publisher= The National Trust |location= London |isbn= 978-1-84359-367-6 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= Broadwood by Appointment: A History |last= Wainwright |first= D |year= 1982 |publisher= Quiller Press |location= London |isbn= 0-907621-10-4 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1= Warren |first1= S |title= 100 Greatest Cycling Climbs: A road cyclist's guide to Britain's hills |year= 2010  |publisher= Frances Lincoln |location= London |isbn= 978-0-7112-3120-7 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= London's Countryside : Geographical Field Work for Students and Teachers of Geography |url= https://archive.org/details/londonscountrysi0000wool |url-access= registration |last1= Wooldridge |first1= SW |last2= Hutchings |first2= GE |year= 1957 |publisher= Methuen |location= London |ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Box Hill}}\n*[http://www.boxhillcommunity.com/ Box Hill community website]\n*[https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/box-hill Box Hill \u2013 National Trust]\n*[https://www.surreywildlifetrust.org/nature-reserves/betchworth-quarry-lime-kilns Betchworth Quarry \u2013 Surrey Wildlife Trust]\n*[https://www.surreywildlifetrust.org/nature-reserves/brockham-limeworks Brockham Quarry \u2013 Surrey Wildlife Trust]\n*[https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/headley-heath Headley Heath \u2013 National Trust]\n*[https://www.surreyoutdoorlearning.uk/facilities/high-ashurst High Ashurst \u2013 Surrey Outdoor Learning]\n*[https://www.field-studies-council.org/locations/juniperhall/ Juniper Hall \u2013 Field Studies Council]\n\n{{Geographic location\n|title     = '''Nearest Settlements'''\n|Centre    = Box Hill\n|North     = Tyrrells Wood\n|Northeast = [[Headley, Surrey|Headley]]\n|East      = [[Colley Hill]]\n|Southeast = [[Betchworth]]\n|South     = [[Brockham]] \n|Southwest = [[Pixham]]<br>[[Dorking]]\n|West      = [[Westhumble]]\n|Northwest = [[Mickleham, Surrey|Mickleham]]<br>[[Leatherhead]]\n}}\n{{Mole Valley}}\n{{Surrey Hills AONB}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hills of Surrey]]\n[[Category:National Trust properties in Surrey]]\n[[Category:Box Hill, Surrey]]\n[[Category:Climbs in cycle racing in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:RideLondon\u2013Surrey Classic]]\n[[Category:Cycle racing in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Box Hill (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Hill in Surrey, England}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox protected area\n| name = Box Hill\n| alt_name = Part of the [[Mole Gap to Reigate Escarpment]] SSSI\n| iucn_category = IV\n| iucn_ref =\n| photo = Towards_Box_Hill_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1805314.jpg\n| photo_width = 290\n| photo_alt = \n| photo_caption = Box Hill viewed from the south. <br>Photograph taken from Betchworth Park Golf Course.\n| map = United Kingdom Surrey\n| map_width = \n| map_alt = \n| map_caption = \n| relief = 1\n| label = Box Hill\n| label_position = top\n| mark =\n| marker_size =\n| location = \n| nearest_city = \n| nearest_town = [[Dorking]], [[Surrey]], England\n| coordinates = {{coord|51|15|18|N|0|18|31|W|type:mountain_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coords_ref = \n| length =\n| length_mi =\n| length_km =\n| width =\n| width_mi = \n| width_km =\n| area = \n| area_ha =\n| area_acre =\n| area_km2 = 11\n| area_sqmi =\n| area_ref = \n| elevation = \n| elevation_avg = \n| elevation_min = \n| elevation_max = \n| dimensions = \n| designation =\n| authorized =\n| created =\n| designated = \n| established = \n| named_for = \n| visitation_num = \n| visitation_year = \n| visitation_ref =\n| governing_body = \n| administrator =\n| operator =\n| owner =\n| world_heritage_site =\n| website = \n| url = \n| child = \n| embedded = \n{{Infobox mountain\n| name            = Box Hill\n| photo           = \n| photo_size      = \n| photo_alt       = \n| photo_caption   = \n| elevation_m     = 224\n| elevation_ref   =<ref name=Wooldridge_1957_79>{{harvnb|Wooldridge|Hutchings|1957|p=79}}</ref>\n| prominence_m    = 49\n| listing         =\n| location        = \n| range           = [[North Downs]]\n| map_image       = Box hill map.png\n| map_alt         =\n| map_caption     = Map of Box Hill, showing the areas managed by the National Trust (purple), Surrey Wildlife Trust (turquoise) and Surrey County Council (green).  The urban area of Box Hill village is shown in grey.\n| grid_ref_UK     = TQ 178 514\n| topo            = [[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Landranger'' 187\n| type            = [[Cuesta]]\n| geology         = [[Chalk]]\n| geology2        = [[Clay-with-Flints]]\n| age             = Cretaceous and Eocene\n| last_eruption   =\n| first_ascent    =\n| easiest_route   =\n| child = yes\n}}\n}}\n'''Box Hill''' is a summit of the [[North Downs]] in [[Surrey]], approximately {{convert|30|km|mi|abbr=on}} south-west of [[London]].  The hill gets its name from the ancient [[Buxus sempervirens|box woodland]] found on the steepest west-facing chalk slopes overlooking the [[River Mole]]. The western part of the hill is owned and managed by the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]], whilst the village of Box Hill lies on higher ground to the east. The highest point is Betchworth Clumps at {{convert|224|m|ft|abbr=on}} [[Ordnance Datum|above OD]],<ref name=Wooldridge_1957_79/> although the Salomons Memorial (at 172 metres) overlooking the town of [[Dorking]] is the most popular viewpoint.<ref name=MVDC_planning>{{cite web |url= http://www.mole-valley.gov.uk/cwi/getDocument?docId=188328&account=planning&ref=MO/2009/0647&filename=Design%20Statement |title= Box Hill Visitor Facilities and Car Park: Planning Application for Proposed Improvements |publisher= Mole Valley District Council |accessdate=3 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nBox Hill lies within the [[Surrey Hills AONB|Surrey Hills Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]] and forms part of the [[Mole Gap to Reigate Escarpment]] Site of Special Scientific Interest.  The north- and south-facing slopes support an area of chalk downland, noted for its orchids and other rare plant species.<ref name=NT_wildlife>{{cite web |url= http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-vh/w-visits/w-great_days_out/w-nature-places_to_visit/w-nature-places_to_visit-boxhill.htm |title= Box Hill |author= Oates M |year= 2008 |work= Places to Visit for Wildlife |publisher= National Trust |accessdate= 3 April 2011 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110517040554/http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-vh/w-visits/w-great_days_out/w-nature-places_to_visit/w-nature-places_to_visit-boxhill.htm |archivedate= 17 May 2011 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The hill provides a habitat for 40 species of butterfly,<ref name=NT_wildlife/> and has given its name to a species of [[Coreidae|squash bug]], now found throughout south-east England.<ref name=british_bugs>{{cite web |url=http://www.britishbugs.org.uk/heteroptera/Coreidae/gonocerus_acuteangulatus.html |title= ''Gonocerus acuteangulatus'' Box Bug |author= Bantock T and Botting J |year= 2010 |work= British Bugs: An online identification guide to UK Hemiptera |publisher= britishbugs.org.uk |accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nAn estimated 850,000 people visit Box Hill each year.<ref name=MVDC_planning/> The National Trust visitors' centre provides both a cafeteria and gift shop, and the panoramic views of the western Weald may be enjoyed from the [[North Downs Way]], a long-distance footpath that runs along the southern escarpment.  Box Hill featured prominently on the route of the [[Cycling at the 2012 Summer Olympics|2012 Summer Olympics cycling]] road race events.<ref name=\"guardian1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/interactive/2011/feb/10/olympics-2012-cycling-road-race-route |title=Olympics 2012: cycling road race route |work=Guardian|date=11 February 2011 |format=Adobe Flash |accessdate=18 February 2011}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:St Andrew's Church, Box Hill (Geograph Image 2266120 e41e2a89).jpg|thumb|St Andrew's Church, Box Hill village.]]\nBox Hill, approximately {{convert|30|km|mi|abbr=on}} south-west of central London, stands at the south-eastern corner of the Mole Gap, the valley carved by the River Mole through the North Downs.<ref name=Bannister_p2>{{harvnb|Bannister|1999|p=2}}</ref> Its summit, {{convert|224|m|ft}} above [[Ordnance Datum]], is the 12th highest in Surrey.<ref>[http://www.hills-database.co.uk/downloads.html Database of British and Irish Hills] Retrieved 6 March 2015</ref> The western boundary of the hill is defined by the River Mole, which has cut a steep [[cliff]], exposing the chalk bedrock. The [[Vale of Holmesdale]] lies immediately to the south, below the scarp slope. The northern and eastern boundaries are defined by [[dry valley|dry river valleys]], which were created during the [[last glacial period|last Ice Age]]. The total area of the hill is approximately {{convert|11|km2|sqmi}}, of which half is owned by the National Trust.\n\nThe village of Box Hill is within the civil parish of Headley. The earliest flint cottages date from the 1800s, although much of the village was constructed in the first half of the 20th century.<ref>{{harvnb|Mountford|1974|pp=3\u20134}}</ref> By 2005 there were more than 800 dwellings, of which over five hundred were mobile homes.  An estimated 41% of the community is aged 60 or over.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.connectedsurrey.com/stylesheet.asp?file=17032006112104 |title= Box Hill Project |author= Fry R |year= 2006 |work= Community Case Studies |publisher= The Connected Surrey Partnership |accessdate=13 April 2011}}</ref> St Andrew's Church, part of the [[ecclesiastical parish]] of Headley, was consecrated in 1969 and the village hall opened in 1974.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://myweb.tiscali.co.uk/friendsofstandrewsbh/history_part_1.htm |title=History |author=Langley D |year=2000 |work=The Church on the Hill |publisher=Friends of St Andrews Box Hill |accessdate=24 July 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6IMGmoaPS?url=http://myweb.tiscali.co.uk/friendsofstandrewsbh/history_part_1.htm |archivedate=24 July 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Mountford|1974|p=3}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Early history===\n[[File:Beech pollard - Box Hill, Surrey.jpg|thumb|Ancient [[pollarding|pollarded]] [[beech]] tree between the Viewpoint and the Donkey Green.{{refn|The tree marks the boundary between two parishes: [[Mickleham, Surrey|Mickleham]] (to the north) and [[Dorking]] (to the south).<ref name=Bannister6-7>{{harvnb|Bannister|1999|pp=6\u20137}}</ref>|group=note}}]]\nTwo Bronze Age [[round barrow]]s, located close to the Salomons Memorial, provide the earliest archaeological evidence of human activity on Box Hill.<ref>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1007888}}</ref><ref>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1007889}}</ref> The larger barrow is {{convert|20|m|abbr=on}} in diameter and {{convert|2.2|m|abbr=on}} high.  In medieval times the larger barrow was used as a [[boundary marker]] or ''mere'' for the parish of [[Mickleham, Surrey|Mickleham]].<ref name=Bannister12>{{harvnb|Bannister|1999|p=12}}</ref> Traces of prehistoric [[field system|field boundaries]] are visible on Burford Spur and the low [[flint]] banks on the steeper and more wooded White Hill may be contemporaneous.<ref name=Bannister12/>\n\nAn [[Harrow Way|ancient trackway]] along the [[North Downs]] escarpment can be dated to around 600\u2013450&nbsp;BC, but has probably been in existence since the [[stone age]]<ref>{{harvnb|Brayley|Britton|1841|p=218}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Fagg|first=C. C.|author2=Hutchings, G. E.  |others=Tansley, A. G|title=Great Britain: essays in regional geography |editor=Ogilvie, Alan Grant|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge, England|year=1928|page=29|chapter=Prehistory|oclc=59447377}}</ref> and may have crossed the [[River Mole]] at a ford close to the location of the present day stepping stones. In Victorian times the route was dubbed the [[Pilgrims' Way]] and was supposedly followed by visitors to the shrines of [[Thomas Becket]] and [[Swithun]] at [[Canterbury Cathedral|Canterbury]] and [[Winchester Cathedral|Winchester]] respectively.<ref>{{harvnb|Margary|1948|pp=260\u2013263}}</ref>\n\n[[Stane Street (Chichester)|Stane Street]] was constructed by the [[Roman Britain|Romans]] in around 60\u201370 AD to link London ([[Londinium]]) to Chichester ([[Noviomagus Reginorum]]) on the south coast of England.<ref>{{harvnb|Margary|1948|p=XX}}</ref> The course of the road runs in a southwesterly direction across Mickleham Downs,<ref name=Hall>{{cite journal |author= Hall A |year= 2008 |title= The archaeological evidence for the route of Stane Street from Mickleham Downs to London Road, Ewell |journal= Surrey Archaeological Collections |publisher= Surrey Archaeological Society |volume= 94 |pages= 225\u2013250 }}</ref> before turning south to cross the [[River Mole]] at a ford close to the site of the [[Burford Bridge Hotel]].<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= The Mole Crossing at Burford |work= The Times |location= London |date= 25 March 1937 |issue= 47642 |page= 17}}</ref>\n\n===Medieval and early modern periods===\nThe [[Warren#Pillow mounds|pillow mounds]] to the north-east of the Salomons Memorial are thought to date from the medieval period and were probably constructed as artificial [[Warren (domestic)|warrens]] for rabbits. High Ashurst warren is recorded as remaining in use until the late 18th century.<ref name=Bannister20>{{harvnb|Bannister|1999|p=20}}</ref> A second warren was probably situated close to Warren Farm in the Headley Valley and it has been speculated that the present farmhouse was originally the warrener's cottage.<ref name=Bannister20/>\n\n[[File:Boxhill surrey trees.jpg|thumb|right|Box and yew trees growing on the steep, western slope of Box Hill, above the River Mole.]]\nThe origin of the [[buxus|box trees]] growing on the hill is disputed: Several sources from the late 18th century suggest that the first box trees on the hill were planted by [[Thomas Howard, 21st Earl of Arundel]] during the reign of [[Charles I of England|Charles I]].<ref>{{harvnb|Beavan|1777|p=2}}</ref> However Howard never owned the Box Hill estate<ref>{{harvnb|Littledale|Locock|Sankey|1984|p=12}}</ref> and older medieval documents make reference to local individuals with surnames including ''Atteboxe'', ''de la Boxe'' and ''Buxeto'', suggesting that the trees were already common in the area by the 13th century.<ref>{{harvnb|Brayley|Britton|1841|p=461}}</ref> The diarist [[John Evelyn]] records a visit to the hill in August 1655 to view \"those natural bowers, cabinets and shady walks in the box copses.\" The close grain of the box wood made it highly prized for its [[lumber|timber]] for carving and there are numerous accounts of the sale of trees from the hill throughout the 17th and 18th centuries.<ref name=\"Littledale 1984 13\">{{harvnb|Littledale|Locock|Sankey|1984|p=13}}</ref> At the end of the eighteenth century, imports from Portugal reduced the market value of box wood and commercial exploitation of timber from Box Hill appears to have ended with a final sale in 1797.<ref name=\"Littledale 1984 13\"/>\n\n===Ownership and public access <small>(19th and 20th centuries)</small>===\nThe hill was purchased by [[Thomas Hope (banker, born 1769)|Thomas Hope]], shortly before his death in 1831. (Hope was the owner of [[Deepdene House and Gardens|The Deepdene]], the mansion to the east of [[Dorking]].<ref name=\"Littledale 1984 13\"/>) The [[Mickleham, Surrey|Mickleham Parish]] Records credit Hope's widow, Louisa de la Poer Beresford (whom he had married six years previously), with allowing \"free access to the beauties of this hill,\"<ref name=\"Littledale 1984 13\"/> however day-trippers had been arriving in significant numbers for at least a century before that.<ref>{{cite book |last= Macky |first= John |year= 1714 |volume= 1 |title= A journey through England. In familiar letters. From a gentleman here, to his friend abroad |location= London |publisher= J. Hooke |author-link= John Macky}}</ref>\n\nDevelopments in local transport infrastructure over the course of the 18th and 19th centuries, enabled increasing numbers to visit the area. Following the completion of the [[turnpike trust|turnpike road]] between [[Leatherhead]] and [[Dorking]] in 1750, [[stagecoach]]es stopped regularly at the [[Burford Bridge Hotel]].<ref name=Shepperd128>{{harvnb|Shepperd|1991|p=128}}</ref> As late as 1879, a daily coach ran non-stop to Box Hill from [[Piccadilly]] with a journey time of 2.5 hours.<ref name=DailyNews1>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= The Boxhill Coach |work= Daily News |location= London |date= 31 March 1879}}</ref>{{refn|In March 1879 the coach left Piccadilly at 10:30am every day, arriving at the Burford Bridge Hotel at 1pm. The return journey left Box Hill at 4pm, arriving back in London at 6:30pm.<ref name=DailyNews1/>|group=note}}\n\nThe [[South Eastern Railway (England)|South Eastern Railway]] opened the first railway station in Dorking in 1849,{{refn|Now known as [[Dorking West railway station|Dorking West]] station on the [[North Downs Line]].|group=note}} followed in 1867 by the [[London, Brighton and South Coast Railway]] (LBSCR), which opened the station in the village of Westhumble.<ref name=Chapman150-151>{{harvnb|Shepperd|1991|pp=150\u2013151}}</ref><ref name=Shepperd137>{{harvnb|Shepperd|1991|p=137}}</ref> The LBSCR ran dedicated excursion trains to Box Hill on Bank Holiday weekends and over 1300 day-trippers were recorded arriving at Westhumble station on 6 August 1883.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= The Bank Holiday |work= The Times |location= London |date= 7 August 1883}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Box Hill Salomons Memorial 2.jpg|right|thumb|The Salomons Memorial commemorates the gift of {{convert|95|ha|acre|abbr=on|sigfig=2}} of land on Box Hill to the National Trust in 1914.{{refn|Salomons died in September 1915, just over a year after donating the land on Box Hill to the National Trust. His widow opened the Memorial at the viewpoint in 1920.<ref>{{cite news |last= Edwards |first= Mark |date= 11 September 2014 |title= Box Hill viewing point reopens to mark 100th anniversary |url= https://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/nostalgia/box-hill-viewing-point-reopens-7756789 |work= Surrey Live |access-date= 21 October 2019 }}</ref>|group=note}}]]\nThe proposals for a [[land value tax]] outlined by Chancellor [[David Lloyd George]] in his [[People's Budget]] of 1909 prompted the trustees of the Deepdene estate to start to sell the unimproved land on the western side of Box Hill.<ref name=Littledale15>{{harvnb|Littledale|Locock|Sankey|1984|p=15}}</ref> As a result of negotiations led by [[Robert Hunter (National Trust)|Sir Robert Hunter]], [[Leopold Salomons]] of [[Norbury Park]] purchased {{convert|95|ha|acre|abbr=on|sigfig=2}} of Box Hill in 1913 for \u00a316,000. The following year, Salomons donated the land, which included the Old Fort, Swiss Cottage and the western flank of the hill above the River Mole, to the National Trust.<ref name=Littledale15-16>{{harvnb|Littledale|Locock|Sankey|1984|pp=15\u201316}}</ref>\n\nTwo further purchases of {{convert|28|ha|acre|abbr=on|sigfig=2}} and {{convert|102|ha|acre|abbr=on|sigfig=2}} transferred Lodge Hill and Ashurst Rough to National Trust ownership in 1921 and 1923.<ref name=NT_acq>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/servlet/file/store5/item724521/version1/nt_acquisitions_dec2011-2.pdf |title=National Trust Acquisition Data |year=2010 |publisher=National Trust |accessdate=12 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120603070439/http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/servlet/file/store5/item724521/version1/nt_acquisitions_dec2011-2.pdf |archivedate=3 June 2012}}</ref> Following World War 2, National Trust acquired Headley Heath, a geologically distinct area of heathland which lies to the north-east of Box Hill village, in a single purchase in 1946.<ref name=NT_acq/> The Trust continued to purchase land, and by the mid-1980s the estate comprised some {{convert|500|ha|acre|abbr=on|sigfig=2}}.<ref name=NT_acq/> The most recent additions to the Box Hill Estate include farmland at Westhumble and at the foot of the hill, purchased in the late 1990s.<ref name=NT_acq/>\n\n===Military History <small>(19th and 20th centuries)</small>===\n\n[[File:Box Hill Fort.JPG|thumb|Box Hill Fort, constructed in 1899. Note the earth [[blast wall|blast bank]] (left) which protects the south west face of the flat-roofed main building (right).<ref name=NHL_Boxhill_Fort>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1018074}}</ref>]]\nIn the latter half of the 19th century, growing public concern over the ability of the British armed forces to repel an invasion (stoked, in part, by the serialisation of [[George Tomkyns Chesney|George Tomkyns Chesney's]] 1871 novella [[The Battle of Dorking]]<ref name=Tuson-20-21>{{harvnb|Tuson|2013|pp=20\u201321}}</ref>), prompted the government to announce the construction of thirteen fortified mobilisation centres, collectively known as the [[London Defence Positions]].{{refn|A common misconception is that the forts were built to protect against invasion by the French Emperor [[Napoleon]], however he had died in 1821, almost 80 years before construction began. <br>The aftermath of the [[Franco-Prussian War]] of 1870 (which led to the [[unification of Germany]]), the reform of the Russian Army following the Crimean War and colonial disputes with France, prompted British fears of a war against an alliance of the main European powers. Lobbying by [[Edward Bruce Hamley|Sir Edward Hamley MP]]<ref>{{Cite Hansard|house=House of Commons |title= Defences of the Empire - Coast defences of Great Britain |url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/commons/1887/mar/14/observations#S3V0312P0_18870314_HOC_240 |date= 14 March 1887 |volume 312 |column_start=238 |column_end=325}}</ref> resulted in the Secretary of State for War, [[Edward Stanhope]],  presenting the bill for construction of the London Defence Positions to Parliament in 1889.<ref name=Beanse-4-6>{{harvnb|Beanse|Gill|2011|pp=4\u20136}}</ref>|group=note}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WMGCY |title= Box Hill Fort |year= 2006 |work= Historic Forts on Waymarking.com |publisher= waymarking.com |accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> Two centres were built on Box Hill, approximately {{convert|2.5|km|mi|abbr=on}} apart: one close to the present National Trust visitor centre (commonly called Box Hill Fort)<ref name=Beanse-Boxhill>{{harvnb|Beanse|Gill|2011|pp=17\u201319}}</ref> and the other close to the summit of the hill, to the south of the present day Box Hill village (known as Betchworth Fort).<ref name=Beanse-Betchworth>{{harvnb|Beanse|Gill|2011|pp=14\u201316}}</ref>\n\nThe sites were purchased from the trustees of the Hope estate by the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] in 1891, and construction began in 1899.<ref name=Beanse-Boxhill/><ref name=Beanse-Betchworth/> The two centres were laid out in the form of an [[redoubt|infantry redoubt]] typical of the period, but also included [[magazine (artillery)|magazines]] (partially below ground level) for the storage of [[Shell (projectile)|shells]] and [[Cartridge (firearms)|cartridges]].<ref name=Beanse-Betchworth/><ref name=Littledale23>{{harvnb|Littledale|Locock|Sankey|1984|p=23}}</ref> (In common with the majority of the eleven other mobilisation centres, the forts were designed for the use of the infantry only and the stored ammunition was intended for the use of [[Field artillery|mobile field artillery]] which would be deployed nearby as required.)<ref name=Littledale23/> The main flat-roofed buildings were built in brick and reinforced concrete and were protected from [[artillery]] fire by crescent-shaped earth blast banks, surrounded by an outer ditch.<ref name=NHL_Boxhill_Fort/>\n\nA [[Haldane reforms|reform of defence policy]] by the Secretary of War [[Richard Haldane, 1st Viscount Haldane|Viscount Haldane]] in 1905 resulted in all 13 centres being declared redundant, and both forts were sold back to the estate trustees in 1908.<ref name=Beanse-Betchworth/><ref name=Bannister27>{{harvnb|Bannister|1999|p=27}}</ref> Both forts are protected by a Scheduled Monument listing.<ref name=NHL_Boxhill_Fort/><ref name=NHL_Betchworth_Fort>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1020370}}</ref> The National Trust owns the Box Hill Fort and a metal grill has been placed over the entrance to allow bats to access to their roosts.<ref name=NHL_Boxhill_Fort/><ref name=Bannister27/> The Betchworth Fort is in private ownership and is not accessible to the public.<ref name=Beanse-Betchworth/>\n\n[[File:Pill Box - geograph.org.uk - 657135.jpg|thumb|[[Pillbox (military)|Pillbox]] on the south-facing scarp slope of Box Hill (to the north of [[Betchworth Castle]]).]]\nDuring the [[Second World War]] the River Mole, comprised part of the fortified [[GHQ Line|GHQ Line B]]. This defensive line ran along the North Downs from [[Farnham]] via [[Guildford]] to Dorking, before following the river to [[Horley]].<ref name=DA12>{{cite web |url= http://ads.ahds.ac.uk/catalogue//adsdata/arch-455-1/dissemination/pdf/Text_Reports/DA12_TEXT_-_DORKING_GAP.pdf |title= Defence Area 12: Dorking Gap |author= Foot W |year= 2009 |work= Defence Areas: a national study of Second World War anti-invasion landscapes in England |publisher= English Heritage |accessdate=11 December 2010}}</ref> Between Betchworth and Box Hill, the north bank of the River Mole was stabilised and made steeper to prevent wheeled vehicles from crossing. At Boxhill Farm, where access to the river from the north bank was required for the herd of dairy cows, a row of twelve concrete cylinders were cast as an anti-tank measure. Gun mounts were also installed to protect both Boxhill and Deepdene bridges and several [[Pillbox (military)|pillboxes]] were constructed.<ref name=DA12/><ref name=\"Marchington T 2000 96\u2013100\">{{cite journal |author= Marchington T |year= 2000 |title= Wartime Defences: A Second Look |journal= Proceedings of the Leatherhead and District Local History Society |volume= 6 |issue= 4 |pages= 96\u2013100 |publisher= Leatherhead and District Local History Society}}</ref><ref name=Telegraph_walk>{{cite journal |date= 2 March 2011 |title=Box Hill, Surrey: walk of the week |journal=Daily Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/activityandadventure/walkingholidays/8356605/Box-Hill-Surrey-walk-of-the-week.html |accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref> The Stepping Stones at the foot of the hill were removed as an anti-invasion measure.<ref name=Telegraph_walk/>\n\nFrom 1940, [[Headley Court]] was used as the Headquarters for the [[VII Corps (United Kingdom)|VII Corps]] and later for the [[Canadian Corps (World War II)|Canadian Corps]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ibiblio.org/hyperwar/UN/Canada/CA/OpSumm/OpSumm-2.html|title=On Guard in Britain, 1940\u20131941|publisher=The Department of National Defense, Government of Canada|accessdate=13 February 2016}}</ref> and Canadian troops were billeted at [[High Ashurst]].<ref name=Denyer>{{cite web|last= Denyer |first= Peter |url=https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/headley-heath/features/the-second-world-war-on-headley-heath |title=The Second World War on Headley Heath |publisher=The National Trust |accessdate= 21 October 2019}}</ref> Bellasis House was used as training centre both for Czech agents of the [[Special Operations Executive]] and for German [[Prisoner of war|Prisoners of War]].<ref name=Denyer/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://dorkingmuseum.org.uk/wartime-at-dorkings-mansions/ |title= Wartime at Dorking\u2019s mansions|publisher= Dorking Museum |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref> In preparation for [[Normandy landings|D-Day]], Headley Heath was used for tank and combat training by the Canadian armed forces,<ref name=Tuson-30-31>{{harvnb|Tuson|2013|pp=30\u201331}}</ref><ref name=Matharu>{{cite news|last= Matharu |first= Hardeep |url= https://www.yourlocalguardian.co.uk/news/9943474.unexploded-mortar-shells-discovered-on-headley-heath/ |title=Unexploded mortar shells discovered on Headley Heath |work= Sutton and Croydon Guardian |date= 21 September 2012 |accessdate= 21 October 2019}}</ref> and [[Betchworth Quarry and Lime Kilns|Betchworth Quarry]] was used by the British Army in early 1944, to test the firing capabilities of [[Churchill tank]]s.<ref>{{harvnb|Chapman|Young|1979|p=154}}</ref>\n\n==Geology==\n===Rock types===\n[[File:Chalk_Face,_Betchworth_Quarry,_Box_Hill,_Surrey.jpg|thumb|The exposed chalk workings of the former Betchworth Quarry on the south-facing scarp slope of Box Hill. {{refn|Note the transmitter mast in the top-left corner of the photograph which, together with the adjacent water tower (not visible in the picture), marks the true summit of Box Hill at {{convert|224|m|ft|abbr=on}} above OD.|group=note}}]]\nThe [[Chalk Group|chalk]] which comprises the majority of Box Hill (and the rest of the [[North Downs]]), has its origins in the late [[Cretaceous]] period (approximately 100 \u2013 66 million years ago). For the entirety of this period, south east England was covered by a warm, shallow sea in which [[coccolithophores]], single-celled [[alga]]e with small [[calcite]] skeletons, thrived. As the phytoplankton died, their calcium-rich shells were deposited on the sea bed and, over time, formed the chalk we know today.\n\nOverlying the chalk across much of the higher ground on the hill, is a deposit of [[clay-with-flints]]. Although the origins of this layer are uncertain, the clay is thought to have been formed during several periods of glaciation and was produced by [[cryoturbation]] and decalcification of the chalk.<ref name=Gallois>{{cite journal |last1=Gallois |first1= RW |title= The origin of the Clay-with-flints: the missing link|journal=Geoscience in South-West England|date=2009|volume=12|pages=153\u2013161}}</ref> This hypothesis is supported by the presence of flint, which is also found in the underlying strata.<ref name=Gallois/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Anon|title=Clay-with Flints formation|url=http://www.bgs.ac.uk/lexicon/lexicon.cfm?pub=CWF|website=The BGS Lexicon of Named Rock Units|publisher=BGS|accessdate=3 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Betchworth limekiln - geograph.org.uk - 869914.jpg|thumb|right|upright|The Smidth Kiln at [[Betchworth Quarry and Lime Kilns|Betchworth Quarry]] was constructed in around 1901.<ref name=NHL_Betchworth>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1021346}}</ref>]]\nThe sandy deposits on Headley Heath have their origin in the [[Quaternary]]. During this period, south east England began to rise from the sea bed, as a result of the same geological processes which [[Alpine orogeny|formed the Alps]] in central Europe. The sand and gravels found in this area, indicate the presence of the sea shore.<ref name=Chapman26>{{harvnb|Chapman|Young|1979|p=26}}</ref> On Headley Heath, these deposits are thin and the chalk also comes to the surface in several places, allowing [[calcifuge|acid-loving plants]] to thrive alongside those that [[calcicole|prefer alkaline conditions]], producing the rare [[chalk heath]] habitat.<ref name=Tuson-30-31/>\n\n===Quarries and lime kilns===\nChalk and flint have been quarried from Box Hill and the surrounding area for many centuries. There are limited surviving examples of the incorporation of chalk blocks (or [[clunch]]) into the stonework of local buildings (including [[Mickleham, Surrey|Mickleham Church]]).<ref name=Shepperd112>{{harvnb|Shepperd|1991|p=112}}</ref> Walls made of flints, bound together by [[lime mortar]], are particularly common in [[Surrey]]<ref name=Bannister22>{{harvnb|Bannister|1999|p=22}}</ref> and [[calcium oxide|quicklime]] could be produced with relative ease, by heating chalk above {{convert|825|C|F}} in a [[lime kiln|kiln]].<ref>{{cite book |last= Stecher |first= Paul G |year= 1968 |title= The Merck index : an encyclopedia of chemicals and drugs |location= Rahway NJ |publisher= Merck |edition= 8th}}</ref>\n\nEvidence remains of the small-scale chalk quarrying that occurred prior to the [[Industrial Revolution]], including chalk pits both at Warren Farm and close to the Burford Bridge Hotel.<ref name=Bannister22/> The opening of the [[North Downs Line|Dorking to Reigate railway line]] at the bottom of the hill in 1849, enabled new quarry faces to be opened at [[Brockham]]<ref name=NHL_Brockham>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1021322}}</ref> and [[Betchworth]].<ref name=NHL_Betchworth/> Sidings were provided adjacent to the main line and there was an extensive network of narrow-gauge railway tracks at both sites.<ref name=NHL_Betchworth/><ref name=NHL_Brockham/> The [[Brockham Limeworks]] closed in 1935, however a battery of eight kilns (dating from 1870) still stands and is Grade II listed.<ref name=NHL_Brockham/> The larger [[Betchworth Quarry and Lime Kilns]] (approximately 1&nbsp;km to the east) closed in 1960 and a variety of different kiln types have been preserved and protected with a Grade II listing.<ref name=NHL_Betchworth/> The two sites have been designated as Nature Reserves and are managed by [[Surrey Wildlife Trust]].<ref name=SWT_Betchworth>{{cite web |url= https://www.surreywildlifetrust.org/nature-reserves/betchworth-quarry-lime-kilns |title= Betchworth Quarry & Lime Kilns |author=<!--Not stated--> |publisher= Surrey Wildlife Trust |access-date= 23 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=SWT_Brockham>{{cite web |url= https://www.surreywildlifetrust.org/nature-reserves/brockham-limeworks |title= Brockham Limeworks |author=<!--Not stated--> |publisher= Surrey Wildlife Trust |access-date= 23 October 2019}}</ref> A wide range of bat species now roost in the former kilns.<ref name=SWT_Betchworth/><ref name=SWT_Brockham/>\n\nGravel was quarried on the northern side of Headley Heath during the 18th and early 19th centuries, most likely to provide material for building local roads.\n\n==Ecology==\n===Conservation===\n[[File:Belted Galloway Cattle on Box Hill, Surrey.jpg|thumb|[[Belted Galloway]] cattle grazing the Burford Spur on the north western side of the hill.]]\nThe entirety of Box Hill lies within the [[Surrey Hills AONB|Surrey Hills Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.surreyhills.org/board/map-of-the-aonb/ |title= Map of the AONB |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= Surrey Hills AONB |publisher= Surrey Hills Society |access-date= 25 October 2019 }}</ref> The vast majority of the publicly accessible areas of the hill that are managed by the National Trust and Surrey Wildlife Trust, form part of the [[Mole Gap to Reigate Escarpment]] [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]] and have been designated a [[Special Area of Conservation]].<ref name=dsv>{{cite web|url=  https://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/SiteDetail.aspx?SiteCode=S1000977&SiteName=&countyCode=41&responsiblePerson=&SeaArea=&IFCAArea= |title=Designated Sites View: Mole Gap to Reigate Escarpment   | series= Sites of Special Scientific Interest|publisher=Natural England|accessdate = 9 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=map>{{cite web|url= https://magic.defra.gov.uk/MagicMap.aspx?startTopic=Designations&activelayer=sssiIndex&query=HYPERLINK%3D%271000977%27|title=Map of Mole Gap to Reigate Escarpment  |series= Sites of Special Scientific Interest|publisher=Natural England|accessdate= 9 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe chalk downland of Box Hill provides a habitat for a wide range of plant species, which in turn support a varied population of insect species. The alkaline soils are thin and nutrient poor, which prevents deeper-rooted lush grasses (with a high water demand) from dominating. Each square metre of chalk downland may support up to 40 different species.<ref name=Tuson-27>{{harvnb|Tuson|2013|p=27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/features/whats-special-about-chalk-grassland |title= What's special about chalk grassland? |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= National Trust |publisher= National Trust |access-date=  25 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nWithout careful management, the grassland would [[ecological succession|revert to woodland]] and so these areas of the hill are [[conservation grazing|grazed]] in order to prevent [[shrubland|scrub]] from becoming overestablished.<ref name=SWT_CG>{{cite web |url= https://www.surreywildlifetrust.org/what-we-do/restoring-surreys-nature/conservation-grazing |title= Conservation grazing |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= Surrey Wildlife Trust |publisher= Surrey Wildlife Trust |access-date=  25 October 2019}}</ref>{{refn|Although its spread is often considered undesirable, scrub provides valuable habitat for a range of invertebrates on Box Hill, including the [[Helix pomatia|Roman snail]], [[rufous grasshopper]] and the [[dark green fritillary]].<ref name=FOBH+NT_Woodland>{{cite web |url= http://www.friendsofboxhill.org.uk/what-we-do-3/conservation/ |title= Box Hill Woodland Plan 2009: The condition and habitat management of the woodland compartments of Box Hill |last= Dawson |first= Mark |last2= Creasey |first2= Peter |year= 2009 |website= Friends of Box Hill |publisher= Friends of Box Hill |location= Dorking |access-date= 27 October 2019}}</ref>|group=note}} Both the National Trust and Surrey Wildlife Trust use [[Belted Galloway]] cattle (affectionately nicknamed 'Belties'), which crop the grass less hard than other grazers and allow the more delicate wild flowers (including orchids) to flourish.<ref name=SWT_CG/><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/features/conservation-grazing |title= Conservation grazing |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= National Trust |publisher= National Trust |access-date=  25 October 2019}}</ref> At Betchworth Quarry, Surrey Wildlife Trust allows goats to graze, which can eat woodier plants such as [[Ulex europaeus|gorse]] and [[bramble]].<ref name=SWT_CG/> [[European rabbit|Rabbits]] also make a significant contribution to the control of scrub and coarse grasses on the hill, although their numbers have declined since the introduction of [[myxomatosis]] in 1953.<ref>{{harvnb|Chapman|Young|1979|p=95}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Olympic Rings Box Hill-by-Ian-Capper.jpg|thumb|[[Olympic symbols#Olympic rings|Olympic Rings]] were installed at the viewpoint in July 2012.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= London 2012: Box Hill Olympic road race rings unveiled |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-surrey-18920560 |work= BBC News |location= London |date= 20 July 2012 |access-date= 25 October 2012}}</ref>]]\nFor any conservation area, it is important to find a balance between the interests of people visiting and the needs of the wildlife that it seeks to protect. After the announcement that the Olympic cycling road races would be routed over the hill, concerns were expressed that habitats would be damaged during the event.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cyclingweekly.com/news/racing/olympics/olympics-road-race-not-in-our-box-hill-55729 |title= Olympics road race: Not in our Box Hill |last= Bingham |first= Keith |date= 15 December 2010 |website= Cycling Weekly |access-date= 25 October 2019 }}</ref> Scrub clearance along the side of the Zig Zag Road to provide space for spectators began in January 2012, after a pre-race survey (commissioned by the [[London Organising Committee of the Olympic and Paralympic Games]]) showed that the work was likely to increase biodiversity.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= London 2012: Box Hill woodland scrub cleared for spectators |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-surrey-17090065 |work= BBC News |location= London |date= 19 February 2012 |access-date= 25 October 2019 }}</ref> A second ecological survey, performed after the Games, showed that no significant damage had occurred, although some areas were subsequently reseeded.<ref>{{cite news |last= Martin |first= Guy |date= 3 August 2012 |title= 'Gold medal' for Box Hill cycling wildlife protection |url= https://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/local-news/gold-medal-box-hill-cycling-4809320 |work= Surrey Live |access-date= 25 October 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Biodiversity===\n{{multiple image\n | width = 110\n | footer = [[Dactylorhiza fuchsii|Common spotted]] (left) and [[Herminium monorchis|Musk]] (right) Orchids growing on Box Hill.\n | image1 = Common_Spotted_Orchid_(Dactylorhiza_fuchsii)_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1359262.jpg\n | alt1 = \n | caption1 = \n | image2 = Musk Orchid (Herminium monorchis) - geograph.org.uk - 863983.jpg\n | alt2 = \n | caption2 =\n }}\nThe chalk downland environment supports notable populations of [[bat]]s, [[lepidopterans]], [[orchids]] and the hill's [[namesake]], the box tree (''[[Buxus sempervirens]]'').<ref>[http://www.boxhill.org.uk/visitors/downland.html Box Hill Community Website] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080306220756/http://www.boxhill.org.uk/visitors/downland.html |date=6 March 2008 }} Retrieved 4 February 2008</ref> Box Hill also has over 40 species of butterflies and plants.\n\n====Orchids====\nA large number of species of [[orchid]] have been recorded on Box Hill, including [[Spiranthes spiralis|autumn lady's-tresses]], [[Ophrys apifera|bee orchids]], [[Neottia nidus-avis|bird's-nest orchids]], [[Epipactis helleborine|broad-leaved helleborines]], [[Dactylorhiza fuchsii|common spotted orchids]], [[Neottia ovata|common twayblades]], [[Gymnadenia conopsea|fragrant orchids]], [[Anacamptis pyramidalis|pyramidal orchids]] and [[Cephalanthera damasonium|white helleborines]].<ref>{{harvnb|Sankey|2000|p=3}}</ref>\n\n====Other wild flowers====\n[[Allium ursinum|Wild garlic]] grows alongside [[Hyacinthoides non-scripta|bluebells]] under the tree canopy beside the River Mole at the western edge of the hill, giving the area its distinctive smell in springtime.<ref name=FOBH+NT_Woodland/>\n\n====Trees====\n[[File:The Whites Box Hill- geograph.org.uk - 1503979.jpg|thumb|Yew and box trees growing on the west side of the hill.{{refn|The [[cut bank|cliff above the River Mole]] is so steep and the [[orthent|soil is so shallow]] that the bare chalk rock is exposed in several places.|group=note}}]]\nThe [[Buxus sempervirens|box]] and [[Taxus baccata|yew]] woodland, on the steep-sloping sides of the hill above the River Mole, is of international importance. Common [[Canopy (biology)|canopy-layer]] species include [[Fagus sylvatica|beech]], [[Fraxinus excelsior|ash]] and [[Quercus robur|oak]]. [[Understory|Understorey]] species include [[Ilex aquifolium|holly]], [[Corylus avellana|hazel]], [[Sambucus|elder]] and [[honeysuckle]].<ref name=FOBH+NT_Woodland/>\n\n[[Invasive species]] found on the hill include [[Buddleja|buddleia]], [[Prunus laurocerasus|cherry laurel]], [[Reynoutria japonica|Japanese knot weed]] and [[Solidago canadensis|Canadian goldenrod]]. [[Boxwood blight]], a [[pathogenic fungus|fungal disease]] caused by [[Cylindrocladium|''Cylindrocladium buxicola'']], is widespread.<ref name=FOBH+NT_Woodland/>\n\n====Bats====\nSeveral abandoned brick and concrete structures provide habitats for [[bat]]s and grills have been placed over their entrances to protect the roosting sites.<ref name=NHL_Betchworth/><ref name=NHL_Brockham/> Three species are known to inhabit The old Box Hill Fort: the [[brown long-eared bat]], the [[common noctule|noctule bat]] and [[Natterer's bat]].<ref>{{harvnb|Tuson|2013|p=22}}</ref> The brown long-eared bat, Natterer's bat, the [[whiskered bat]] and [[Daubenton's bat]] have been recorded at both Betchworth and Brockham quarries.<ref name=SWT_Betchworth/><ref name=SWT_Brockham/> [[Brandt's bat]] has been recorded at Betchworth;<ref name=SWT_Betchworth/> [[Bechstein's bat]] and the [[common pipistrelle]] have been recorded at Brockham.<ref name=SWT_Brockham/>\n\n====Butterflies and Moths====\n {{multiple image\n | width = 110\n | footer = [[Lysandra coridon|Chalkhill blue]] (left) and [[Melanargia galathea|Marbled White]] (right) butterflies on knapweed flowers on Box Hill.\n | image1 = Blue butterfly on Box Hill.jpg\n | alt1 = \n | caption1 = \n | image2 = Marbled white butterfly on Box Hill-by-Ian-Capper.jpg\n | alt2 = \n | caption2 = \n }}\nBox Hill supports 38 different species of butterflies.<ref name=Surrey_Skipper>{{cite web |url= https://butterfly-conservation.org/sites/default/files/56-autumn-2013.pdf |title= News from Box Hill |last= Jeffcoate |first= Gail |year= 2013 |website= Surrey Skipper |publisher= Butterfly Conservation |access-date= 25 October 2019}}</ref> Grassland species include the [[Epargyreus clarus|silver-spotted skipper]] and [[Lysandra coridon|chalkhill blue]].<ref name=Surrey_Skipper/> Scrubland species include the [[brown hairstreak]]<ref name=Surrey_Skipper/> and woodland species include the [[Speckled wood (butterfly)|speckled wood]] and the [[small pearl-bordered fritillary]].<ref>{{harvnb|Chapman|Young|1979|p=97}}</ref>\n\n[[Anthyllis vulneraria|Kidney vetch]], growing in the Zig Zag Valley, supports a population of the [[small blue]] butterfly.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.molevalley.gov.uk/CausewayDocList/DocServlet?ref=MO/2012/0536&docid=404511 |title= Box Hill Ecological Report, November, 2011 |website= Mole Valley District Council |publisher= Mole Valley District Council |access-date= 25 October 2019 }}</ref>\n\nRare moth species found on the hill include the [[Aspitates gilvaria|straw belle]], [[Scotopteryx bipunctaria|chalk carpet]], [[Scopula ornata|lace border]], [[Synanthedon andrenaeformis|orange-tailed clearwing]] and the [[Phyllonorycter scabiosella|Surrey midget moth]].<ref name=Surrey_Skipper/>\n\n====Other insects====\nThe hill has given its name to a species of [[Coreidae|squash bug]], now found throughout south-east England.<ref name=british_bugs/>\n\n==Recreation==\n[[File:Box_Hill_Salomons_Memorial.jpg|thumb|Salomons Memorial viewpoint, looking south, in 2010]]\n\n===Box Hill Country Park===\nThe western part of Box Hill, managed by the [[National Trust]], was designated a [[Country Park]] in 1971.<ref name=Littledate5>{{harvnb|Littledale|Locock|Sankey|1984|p=5}}</ref> In the early 1980s, some of the outbuildings associated with the old Box Hill Fort were taken over by the National Trust for use as a visitor centre, gift shop and servery.<ref>{{harvnb|Littledale|Locock|Sankey|1984|p=24}}</ref> In 2011, a ''Natural Play Trail'' was constructed close to the visitor centre, cofunded by the National Trust and the Friends of Box Hill.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.surreylife.co.uk/out-about/walks/national-trust-s-new-natural-play-trail-at-box-hill-1-1644611 |url-access= |title= National Trust's new natural play trail at Box Hill |last= Brien |first= Emma |date= 24 November 2011 |website= Surrey Life |access-date= 29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn the hill there are [[Parking lot|car parks]]<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Box Hill, Surrey: walk of the week |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/activityandadventure/walkingholidays/8356605/Box-Hill-Surrey-walk-of-the-week.html |date= 2 March 2011 |access-date= 19 October 2019 |work= Daily Telegraph }}</ref> and a panoramic view over the [[Weald]] towards the [[South Downs]] may be enjoyed from the Salomons Memorial (more commonly known as the viewpoint).{{refn|A common misconception is that the Salomons Memorial (at {{convert|172|m|ft|abbr=on}} [[Ordnance Datum|above OD]]) marks the highest point of the hill, however the land continues to rise to the east. The true summit of the hill is at Betchworth Clumps at {{convert|224|m|ft|abbr=on}} above OD and is currently occupied by a water tower and transmitter mast.<ref name=Wooldridge_1957_79/> |group=note}}<ref name=Littledate5/> Juniper Top, on the northern side of the hill, offers views to the northwest towards [[Windsor Castle]].<ref name=Littledate5/>\n\nThe Country Park is crisscrossed by a large number of [[footpath]]s and [[bridle path|bridleways]], and there are several signposted, self-guided trails.\n\n===Cycling===\n{{Infobox cycling hill climb\n| name = Zig Zag Road\n| image = RW1_3172.jpg\n| image_size = 240\n| image_alt =\n| caption = Prudential Ride-London 100: Amateur cyclists ascending the Zig Zag Road (July 2016)\n| max_elevation_m = 175\n| location = Box Hill, Surrey\n| start = \n| altitude_m = 120\n| length_km = 2.5\n| gradient = 5.0\n| maxgradient = 7.3\n| website = [https://www.surreyhills.org/discover-route/box-hill-olympic-route/ Box Hill Olympic Circuit] }} \nBox Hill has been popular with cyclists since the 1880s<ref>{{cite journal |year= 1883 |title=Unknown title |journal= London bicycle club gazette |volume= 6 |page= 147 }}</ref> and by the 1890s, Dorking Cycle Club was organising camps for amateur cyclists from across the south east of England.<ref name=Tuson-10>{{harvnb|Tuson|2013|p=10}}</ref>{{refn|In February 2017 the ''Sunday Times'' newspaper identified Box Hill as one of the top six rural cycling accident blackspots in the UK, stating that seven accidents on the Zig Zag Road had been reported to the Police in 2015.<ref>{{cite journal |last= Hookham |first= M |date= 12 February 2017 |title= Roundabout is UK's deadliest spot for cyclists |journal= The Sunday Times  |location= London |publisher= News International }}</ref>|group=note}} The [[Cycling at the 2012 Summer Olympics|2012 Summer Olympic cycling]] road races included {{convert|15.8|km|mi|adj=on|abbr=on}} mid-race circuits of Box Hill.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.surreyhills.org/discover-route/box-hill-olympic-route/ |title= Box Hill Olympic Route |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= Surrey Hills |access-date= 17 October 2019}}</ref> An estimated 15,000 spectators travelled to the hill on 28 July 2012 to watch the men's race, which included nine circuits<ref name=Tuson-11>{{harvnb|Tuson|2013|p=11}}</ref> and the following day, competitors in the women's race climbed Box Hill twice.<ref name=Tuson-12>{{harvnb|Tuson|2013|p=12}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian1\"/>\n\nThe {{convert|15.8|km|mi|adj=on|abbr=on}} Box Hill Olympic circuit is generally cycled in an [[clockwise|anticlockwise]] direction and begins to the south of the village of [[Mickleham, Surrey|Mickleham]] with an ascent of the hill via the Zig Zag Road. From the National Trust Visitor Centre, the route turns eastwards, running along the escarpment and through the urban area of Box Hill village, reaching a maximum elevation of {{convert|216|m|ft}} above [[Ordnance Datum]]. After {{convert|6.6|km|mi}} the route turns northwest along the B2033, passing through the village of [[Headley, Surrey|Headley]]. After {{convert|9.5|km|mi}}, the circuit begins a continuous descent to the valley of the [[River Mole]], passing to the south of [[Leatherhead]], before turning southwards again through Mickleham to return to the start.\n\nThe Zig Zag Road is a steady climb of {{convert|120|m}} over {{convert|2.5|km}} and has, although on a much smaller scale, been likened to the [[Alpe d'Huez]] in the French Alps.<ref>{{harvnb|Warren|2010|p=37}}</ref>{{refn|On 15 August 2014 Ciaran O'Hara and Roger Barr cycled up the hill 73 times to complete a challenge known as ''Everesting'', in which cyclists repeatedly climb a hill to gain the same vertical elevation (8848&nbsp;m) as [[Mount Everest]].<ref>{{cite journal |last= Smurthwaite |first= T |date= 16 August 2014 |title= Everest attempt succeeds at Box Hill |url= http://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/local-news/everest-attempt-succeeds-box-hill-7627204 |journal= getSurrey |publisher= Trinity Mirror|accessdate= 30 August 2014 }}</ref>|group=note}} The exact date of construction is uncertain: The road first appears on the Ordnance Survey map of 1869,<ref name=Bannister24>{{harvnb|Bannister|1999|p=24}}</ref> but is not shown in a [[watercolor painting|watercolour painting]] dated 1861 by [[William Leighton Leitch]], which is owned by the [[Royal Collection]].<ref name=Littledale15/><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.rct.uk/collection/923641/box-hill-surrey |title= Box Hill, Surrey \u2013 WILLIAM LEIGHTON LEITCH, 1861 |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= The Royal Collection |publisher= Royal Collection Trust |access-date= 14 October 2019}}</ref> The Zig Zag Road is not a public [[right of way]] and is closed for one day each year by the National Trust, to preserve its [[private road]] status.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Box Hill May Get Toll |work= The Times |location= London |date= 18 January 1962 |issue= 55292 |page= 12}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the 2011 [[London Prepares series]], the [[London\u2013Surrey Cycle Classic]] for professional cyclists was organised to test the Olympic course.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cycling/14521435.stm|title=Mark Cavendish wins London 2012 road race test event|author=Ollie Williams|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC Sport|date=14 August 2011|accessdate=18 August 2011}}</ref> The [[Prudential RideLondon-Surrey 100]] and [[London\u2013Surrey Classic]], for amateur and professional cyclists respectively, have taken place annually following the Games and, although the course has undergone several alterations from the 2012 Olympic course, the two races always include a climb of Box Hill.\n\n===High Ashurst===\n{{Main|High Ashurst}}\nHigh Ashurst is an [[outdoor education]] and [[outdoor recreation|activity]] centre on the northern side of Box Hill, adjacent to Headley Heath. The centre is run by Surrey Outdoor Learning and Development on behalf of [[Surrey County Council]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.surreyoutdoorlearning.uk |title= Surrey Outdoor Learning and Development |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= |access-date= 16 October 2019 }}</ref> Previously the site comprised the grounds of a country house, which was demolished in the 1970s, having been derelict for several decades.\n\n===Boidier Hurst campsite===\nThe District [[The Scout Association|Scout Associations]] of [[Leatherhead]] and [[Epsom and Ewell]] own a {{convert|10|acre|ha|adj=on|order=flip}} [[campsite]], located between Box Hill village and Headley Heath.<ref name=Boidier_index>{{cite web |url= http://www.boidierhurst.org.uk/index.html |title= Boidier Hurst Scout campsite |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= Boidier Hurst Scout campsite |access-date= 1 March 2020 }}</ref><ref name=Boidier_site>{{cite web |url= http://www.boidierhurst.org.uk/the-site.html |title= The site |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= Boidier Hurst Scout campsite |access-date= 1 March 2020 }}</ref> There are 11 areas for pitching groups of tents, set within [[coppicing|coppiced]] [[Aesculus hippocastanum|chestnut]] woodland. Washing, toilet facilities and a kitchen are available.<ref name=Boidier_site/><ref name=Boidier_Manly>{{cite web |url= http://www.boidierhurst.org.uk/manly-building.html |title= The Manly Building |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= Boidier Hurst Scout campsite |access-date= 1 March 2020 }}</ref> Use of Boidier Hurst is restricted to members of The Scout Association, [[Girlguiding|The Guide Association]] and to local school groups on [[The Duke of Edinburgh's Award|Duke of Edinburgh's Award]] expeditions.<ref name=Boidier_index/>\n\n==Sights==\n===Broadwood's Folly===\n[[File:Broadwood's_Tower-cropped.jpg|thumb|Broadwood's Folly was built in around 1820.<ref name=NHL_Broadwood>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1391454}}</ref> Part of the Zig Zag Road is visible to the right of the tower.]]\nThe circular flint tower located on the northern tip of Lodge Hill was built for the piano maker [[Broadwood and Sons|Thomas Broadwood]], who purchased [[Juniper Hall]] in 1815.<ref>{{harvnb|Wainwright|1982|p=338}}</ref><ref name=BLB_Broadwood>{{cite web |url= http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-494323-the-broadwood-folly-at-juniper-hall-dork |title= The Broadwood Folly at Juniper Hall, Mickleham |author= Goodge M |year= 2005 |publisher= British Listed Buildings |accessdate=28 April 2011}}</ref> It is approximately {{convert|8|m|ft}} high and originally had two internal floors, linked by a spiral staircase. The original doorway is visible on the east side, but has been sealed with rough flints. An avenue of beech trees linked the folly to Juniper Hall, although these were destroyed by the [[Great Storm of 1987]].<ref name=NHL_Broadwood/> The tower may have been built to commemorate the [[Battle of Waterloo]].<ref>{{cite book |last1= Headley |first1= Gwyn |last2= Meulenkamp |first2= Wim |year= 1986 |title= Follies: A National Trust Guide |location= London |publisher= Cape |isbn= 9780224027908 }}</ref>\n\nA [[sparkling wine]], produced by [[Denbies Wine Estate]] for the [[Lidl]] supermarket chain, has been named after the folly.<ref>{{cite news |last= Williams |first= David |date= 18 September 2016 |title= National treasures: Welcome to the new world of English and Welsh wines |url= https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2016/sep/18/six-of-the-best-english-wines |work= The Guardian |location= London |access-date= 26 October 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Labilliere's Grave===\n{{Main|Peter Labilliere}}\n[[File:Peter Labelliere's grave, Box Hill.JPG|upright|thumb|Labilliere's tombstone]]\n\n[[Peter Labilliere]] was born in [[Dublin]] on 30 May 1725 to a family of French [[Huguenot]] descent. He joined the British Army at the age of 14, becoming a major in 1760.<ref>{{harvnb|Lander|2000|pp=7\u20138}}</ref> After leaving the army he became a political agitator and was accused in 1775 of bribing British troops not to fight in the American War of Independence, although he was never tried for treason.<ref name=Lander_20-21>{{harvnb|Lander|2000|pp=20\u201321}}</ref>\n\nAfter moving to Dorking in around 1789,<ref name=Lander_20-21/> Labilliere often visited Box Hill to meditate.<ref name=Lander_35-36>{{harvnb|Lander|2000|pp=35\u201336}}</ref> With old age he became increasingly eccentric and neglected his own personal hygiene to such an extent that he acquired the nickname \"the walking dung-hill\".<ref name=Lander_35-36/> He died on 6 June 1800.<ref name=Timbs>{{harvnb|Timbs|1877}}</ref> In accordance with his wishes he was [[Burial#Inverted burial|buried head downwards]], on 11 June on the western side of Box Hill above The Whites. In the presence of a crowd of thousands that included visitors from London as well as the local \"quality gentry\",<ref name=Timbs/><ref>[https://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/nostalgia/major-peter-labelliere-strange-history-13643026 Major Peter Labelliere: Strange history of man buried upside down atop Box Hill], Surrey Mirror, by W. H. Chouler, July 1963</ref> Labilliere was buried without any religious ceremony, having reportedly said that the world was \"topsy-turvey\" and that it would be righted in the end if he were interred thus. But this preference was not mentioned in his \"Book of Devotions\": rather he there said that he wished to emulate the example of [[Saint Peter|St Peter]], who was [[Cross of St. Peter|crucified upside-down]] according to tradition.<ref>{{harvnb|Lander|2000|pp=39\u201340}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last= Gittings |first= Clare |date= 20 November 2017 |title= Eccentric or enlightened? Unusual burial and commemoration in England, 1689\u00a0\u2013\u00a01823 |journal= Mortality |volume= 12 |issue= 4 |pages= 321\u2013349 |doi= 10.1080/13576270701609667}}</ref>\n\nThe current memorial stone on Box Hill is not believed to mark the exact location of his burial (which is thought to be several metres to the west on a steep incline). There are two errors on the stone itself: He was buried in ''June'' 1800 (rather than July) and all surviving manuscripts indicate that he spelt his name Lab'''i'''lliere (rather than Lab'''e'''lliere).<ref>{{harvnb|Lander|2000|p=6}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=No |first=Doilum |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/doilum/387839851/ |title=Box Hill, Surrey sur Flickr : partage de photos ! |publisher=Flickr.com |accessdate=27 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Summit===\nThe highest point is on Box Hill is Betchworth Clumps at {{convert|224|m|ft|abbr=on}} [[Ordnance Datum|above OD]], immediately to the east of Box Hill village.<ref name=Wooldridge_1957_79/> The summit is densely wooded to conceal a [[water tower]] and [[Radio masts and towers|transmitter mast]], neither of which are accessible to the public.\n\nThe concrete water tower was built in 1930 by East Surrey Water, the forerunner of [[SES Water]]. The structure was refurbished in 2009 to extend its working life by at least 25 years; modifications included the relining of the water bowl, repair of cracks in the walls and roof, as well as the provision of a new access staircase.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.edie.net/library/CRL-gets-started-on-water-tower-repairs/5046 |title= CRL gets started on water tower repairs |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 10 June 2009 |website= edie.net |access-date= 1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe 30m-high mobile phone mast was constructed in 2003 and is operated by [[Vodafone]] and [[EE Limited]].\n\n===Weypole and Stepping Stones===\n[[File:Stepping stones.jpg|right|thumb|The Stepping Stones at the foot of Box Hill]]\nThe ''Weypole'' (or ''Waypole'') is a roughly semi-circular {{convert|2.4|ha|acre|abbr=on|adj=on}} area of level ground at the foot of Box Hill, between The Whites and the River Mole.<ref name=\"NT_acq\"/> The area was originally part of the grounds of Burford Lodge, built by John Eckersall in 1776, and the apple and cherry trees in the area suggest that it was used as an orchard for a time.<ref>{{harvnb|Chapman|Young|1979|p=164}}</ref> The Burford Lodge estate was later owned by the horticulturalist [[Sir Trevor Lawrence, 2nd Baronet|Sir Trevor Lawrence]], who created a garden along the banks of the Mole for his collection of orchids.<ref>{{harvnb|Chadwick|Chadwick|2006|p=121}}</ref>\n\nA ford across the River Mole is thought to have existed here since prehistoric times.<ref>{{harvnb|Ashton|Blight|2006|p=65}}</ref> The ''way-pole'' was a notched post secured in the riverbed, to indicate the depth of the water.<ref>{{cite journal |author=A Son of the Marshed |year=1890 |title=A Surrey River |journal= The Living Age |volume= 185 |issue=2395 |pages=486\u2013497 |publisher=Littell}}</ref> Stepping stones at this site are first recorded in 1841 and they may have been installed by an owner of Burford Lodge to facilitate access to the Weypole orchard.<ref>{{harvnb|Brayley|Britton|1841|p=179}}</ref> The current stones were dedicated on 11 September 1946 by Prime Minister [[Clement Attlee]], at the request of [[James Chuter Ede]], local politician and Attlee's Home Secretary,<ref>Chuter Ede papers collection, Surrey History Centre, 6408/13</ref> replacing those destroyed during World War 2 as an anti-invasion measure.<ref name=Telegraph_walk/><ref>{{cite journal |year= 1946 |title= Picture of the Week |journal= Life |volume= 21 |issue= 13 |page= 36 |publisher= Time Inc.}}</ref> The spot is popular with both anglers and families, although swimming is strongly discouraged. The stones give their name to the pub in the nearby village of [[Westhumble]].\n\n===Other===\nThe [[Burford Bridge Hotel]] and [[Juniper Hall]] Field Studies Centre lie at the foot of Box Hill close to the river Mole. Both are rich in historical associations with famous visitors and residents.\n\n==Notable former residents==\n===John Logie Baird===\n[[John Logie Baird]] (1888-1946), the inventor of the first working television system, lived at Swiss Cottage from 1929 until 1932.<ref>{{harvnb|Burns|2000|page=205}}</ref> Baird conducted some of his experiments on Box Hill,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-global/w-localtoyou/w-south_east/w-south_east-countryside/w-south_east-places-north_downs/w-south_east-places-north_downs-box_hill_headley_heath.htm |title=South East &#124; Box Hill & Headley Heath |publisher=National Trust |date=17 November 2011 |accessdate=27 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110911215852/http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-global/w-localtoyou/w-south_east/w-south_east-countryside/w-south_east-places-north_downs/w-south_east-places-north_downs-box_hill_headley_heath.htm |archivedate=11 September 2011  }}</ref> including his Noctovisor,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://geocities.com/neveyaakov/electro_science/baird.html |title=Baird |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=27 October 2009 |accessdate=27 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091027123028/http://geocities.com/neveyaakov/electro_science/baird.html |archivedate=27 October 2009 }}</ref> an infra-red viewing device.\n\n===George Meredith===\n[[File:George_Meredith's_Home.jpg|thumb|George Meredith and family members, photographed in the rear garden of Flint Cottage, Box Hill.]]\nThe author [[George Meredith]] (1828-1909) lived in Flint Cottage from 1868 until his death. He built a chalet in the garden in which he wrote. Today the house is protected by a Grade II listing and is not accessible to the public.<ref name=FlintCott>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1278478}}</ref>\n\nThe part of the hill immediately opposite the cottage is known as ''Barrie's Bank'', supposedly because the author [[J. M. Barrie]] waited there, while summoning the courage to introduce himself to Meredith.\n\n==Registered Charities==\nThe [[National Trust]] owns around half of the land on Box Hill (principally the Country Park in the west and Headley Heath in the north-east). [[Surrey Wildlife Trust]] manage [[Brockham Limeworks]] (owned by [[Surrey County Council]]) as well as [[Betchworth Quarry and Lime Kilns]] (privately owned).<ref name=SWT_Betchworth/><ref name=SWT_Brockham/>  Both Trusts rely on the support of volunteer groups, working alongside paid employees, to carry out conservation and education work.\n\nThe ''Friends of Box Hill'' (FoBH) is a local organisation, which supports the National Trust in its work in the Country Park. Several of its members advise the Trust on its wildlife management plans and the FoBH also fund specific projects, including the purchase of equipment and improvement of visitor facilities. They also organise a programme of social events, which includes regular talks by Trust staff.<ref name=FoBH_WWD>{{cite web |url= http://www.friendsofboxhill.org.uk/what-we-do-3/ |title= What we do |website= Friends of Box Hill |access-date= 29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Friends of Headley Heath'' (FoHH) coordinate volunteer working parties to assist National Trust Rangers and also run a series of social events.<ref name=FoHH>{{cite web |url= http://www.headleysurrey.org.uk/fohh.htm |title= Friends of Headley Heath |website= Headley Village Website |access-date= 29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n(Both the FoBH and FoHH are independent of the National Trust.<ref name=FoBH_WWD/><ref name=FoHH/>)\n\n==Transport Links==\n===Public Transport===\n[[Box Hill & Westhumble railway station|Box Hill & Westhumble]] is the closest railway station to the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] Country Park (approximately 500 m) and is served by trains from both [[London Victoria station|London Victoria]] and [[London Waterloo station|London Waterloo]]. Both [[Dorking Deepdene railway station|Dorking Deepdene]] and [[Dorking railway station|Dorking (Main)]] stations are around 1&nbsp;km from the south western corner of the hill. [[Betchworth railway station|Betchworth]] station is at the south eastern corner of the hill.\n\n[[File:Box Hill bus and bus stop.JPG|thumb|A [[Sunray Travel]] bus passing the visitor centre. Inset left shows the special wooden National Trust bus stop, with logo engraved.]]\nBox Hill is served by local and [[London Buses route 465|London]] bus routes.<ref name=\"localbus\">[http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-vh/w-visits/w-findaplace/w-boxhill/w-boxhill-gettingthere.htm ''Getting there''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080215093704/http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/main/w-vh/w-visits/w-findaplace/w-boxhill/w-boxhill-gettingthere.htm |date=15 February 2008 }} from The National Trust website. Retrieved 12 February 2008</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.surreycc.gov.uk/sccwebsite/sccwspublications.nsf/WebLookupFileResourcesByUNID/docidF9D4ED4E860D1F9F8025729600568D66?openDocument |title=Surrey County Council \u2013 516 bus timetable via Box Hill visitor centre |accessdate=27 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628230635/http://www.surreycc.gov.uk/sccwebsite/sccwspublications.nsf/WebLookupFileResourcesByUNID/docidF9D4ED4E860D1F9F8025729600568D66?openDocument |archivedate=28 June 2011  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.surreycc.gov.uk/sccwebsite/sccwspublications.nsf/WebLookupFileResourcesByUNID/docid2D0E4B78B92134EC802572960054AE40?openDocument |title=Surrey County Council \u2013 465 bus timetable via foot of Box Hill |accessdate=27 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628230715/http://www.surreycc.gov.uk/sccwebsite/sccwspublications.nsf/WebLookupFileResourcesByUNID/docid2D0E4B78B92134EC802572960054AE40?openDocument |archivedate=28 June 2011  }}</ref>\n\n===Access for Motor Vehicles===\nAccess to the National Trust Country Park from the [[A24 road (England)|A24]] dual carriageway is via the B2209 and the Zig Zag Road, however this route is not suitable for buses or coaches. Alternative access is via the B2033 and Boxhill Road, which leads through Box Hill village and approaches the Country Park from the west. Headley Heath is directly accessible from the B2033.\n\n===Cycle Routes===\n[[National Cycle Route 22]] runs along the northern boundary of the hill via Lodgebottom Road and Headley Lane, before turning south along the [[A24 road (England)|A24]] close to the western boundary. The Surrey Cycleway approached Box Hill from the west via Westhumble, before turning to the south towards Dorking.\n\n===Walking===\nThe [[North Downs Way]] [[long-distance footpath]] from [[Farnham]] to [[Dover]], crosses the River Mole at the Stepping Stones and then runs from west to east at the top of the scarp slope, passing in front of the Salomons Memorial.<ref>{{cite book |last= Saunders |first= Colin |year= 2016 |title= North Downs Way|location= London |publisher= Aurum Press |isbn= 9781781315002 |series= National Trail Guides }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Thames Down Link]] follows the course of [[Stane Street (Chichester)|Stane Street]] across Mickleham Downs, to the north of Box Hill, and meets the [[North Downs Way]] close to the [[Burford Bridge Hotel]].\n\n==Cultural references==\n[[File:A View of Box Hill, Surrey 1733.jpg|thumb|right|''A view of Box Hill, Surrey'' (1733) by [[George Lambert (English painter)|George Lambert]] \u2013 held by [[The Tate]].]]\n\n===Art===\n[[File:George Lambert - Box Hill, Surrey, with Dorking in the distance - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|right|''Box Hill, Surrey with Dorking in the distance'' (1733) by [[George Lambert (English painter)|George Lambert]] \u2013 held by the [[Yale Center for British Art]].]]\nIn 1733, [[George Lambert (English painter)|George Lambert]] painted two views of Box Hill, now held by [[The Tate]]<ref>[http://www.tate.org.uk/servlet/ViewWork?cgroupid=999999961&workid=8266&searchid=15987&tabview=work \"A view of Box Hill, Surrey\"] at [[Tate|The Tate]]</ref> and the [[Yale Center for British Art]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://collections.britishart.yale.edu/vufind/Record/1669128 |title= Box Hill, Surrey, with Dorking in the distance |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= Yale Center for British Art |publisher= Yale University  |access-date= 13 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n''The Stonebreaker'' (1857 -1858), a painting by [[John Brett (artist)|John Brett]] (1831\u20131902), depicts a young boy breaking stones for road mending, with Box Hill in the background.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/walker/collections/paintings/19c/item-236997.aspx |title= The Stonebreaker JOHN BRETT, 1857\u20131858 |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= Walker Art Gallery |publisher= National Museums Liverpool  |access-date= 13 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Brett The Stonebreaker.jpg|thumb|right|Box Hill forms the backdrop to ''The Stonebreaker'', painted by John Brett in 1857\u20131858.]]\n\nA watercolour entitled \u2018'Box Hill, Surrey'\u2019 dated 1861 by [[William Leighton Leitch]] (1804\u20131883), which depicts the view looking northwards from the Old Fort before the Zig Zag Road was built, is part of the [[Royal Collection]].<ref name=Littledale15/><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.rct.uk/collection/923641/box-hill-surrey |title= Box Hill, Surrey \u2013 WILLIAM LEIGHTON LEITCH, 1861 |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= The Royal Collection |publisher= Royal Collection Trust |access-date= 14 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Box Hill Road River, a highly curved, {{convert|100|m|ft|adj=on}} line painted onto the surface of the Zig Zag Road by the British sculptor and [[land art]]ist [[Richard Long (artist)|Richard Long]], was commissioned jointly by the London 2012 Festival and the National Trust to celebrate the route of the Olympic Cycling road races.<ref>{{cite news |last= Jones |first= Jonathan |date= 30 July 2012 |title= Olympics 2012: Richard Long's cycling art shows British landscape at its best |url= https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/jonathanjonesblog/2012/jul/30/olympics-richard-long-cycling-art |work= The Guardian |access-date= 15 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Literature===\n\n[[John Evelyn]] notes in his ''[[John Evelyn's Diary|Diary]]'' in 1662 that Box Hill was frequented by the ladies and gentlemen from nearby [[Epsom]] spa.<ref>Noted in Alice M. Coats, ''Garden Shrubs and Their Histories'' (1964) 1992, ''s.v.'' \"Buxus\".</ref>\n\nThe 'picnic scene', a pivotal passage of [[Jane Austen]]'s novel ''[[Emma (novel)|Emma]]'' is set at Box Hill.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Austen |first1=Jane |title=Emma |publisher=Public Domain |url=https://www.gutenberg.org/files/158/158-h/158-h.htm |accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref>\n[[File: Hammond-Emma22 (recadr\u00e9e).jpg|thumb|upright|The Picnic at Box Hill: Pen-and-ink drawing by Chris Hammond (1860\u20131900) for the 1898 edition of ''[[Emma (novel)|Emma]]'' by [[Jane Austen]].]]\n\nIn ''England: A Nation'', (London: R. Brimley Johnson, 1904), edited by Lucian Oldershaw, and in a chapter entitled \"The Patriotic Idea\" written by [[G. K. Chesterton]], the beauty of Box Hill violated by an invading army is used to express a healthy patriot's love for his nation as opposed to the jingoistic nationalism of tabloid newspapers:<ref name=Oldershaw>{{cite book |last= Chesterton |first=GK |author-link= G. K. Chesterton |editor-last= Oldershaw |editor-first= Lucian |title=England: A Nation |publisher= R. Brimley Johnson |location= London |date=1904 |pages=100\u2013110 |chapter=Chapter 1: The Patriotic Idea |url= https://archive.org/stream/englandnationbei00patrrich/englandnationbei00patrrich_djvu.txt}}</ref> <blockquote>\"But just as a man who has been in love will find it difficult to write a whole frantic epic about a flirtation, so all that kind of rhetoric about the Union Jack and the Anglo-Saxon blood, which has made amusing the journalism of this country for the last six years, will be merely impossible to the man who has for one moment called up before himself what would be the real sensation of hearing that a foreign army was encamped on Box Hill.\"<ref name=Oldershaw/></blockquote>\n\nMystery author [[Cyril Hare]] sets his 1954 novel, ''That Yew Tree's Shade'' (published in the U.S. as ''Death Walks the Woods''), at \"Yew Hill\", which Hare admits in an introduction is modelled on Box Hill.<ref>{{cite book |last= Hare |first= Cyril |year= 1954 |title= That Yew Tree's Shade |location= London |publisher= Faber |isbn= 9780571138005 |author-link= Cyril Hare}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n\nBritish biker rock band [[Dumpy's Rusty Nuts]] released a single called ''Box Hill or Bust'' in 1984.  The song is something of a cult anthem for bikers and reflects the popularity of Box Hill among the biking community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/dumpys-rusty-nuts-mn0001181852|title=Dumpy's Rusty Nuts \u2013 Biography|first=Steve|last=Huey|publisher=Allmusic|accessdate=17 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Richard Thompson (musician)|Richard Thompson]]'s song ''[[1952 Vincent Black Lightning]]'' (released in 1991), Box Hill is the location to which James and Red Molly ride on James' motorcycle.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://americansongwriter.com/2012/08/1952-vincent-black-lightning-by-richard-thompson/|title='1952 Vincent Black Lightning,' By Richard Thompson |work=American Songwriter|date=12 August 2012|accessdate=7 December 2016}}</ref> In [[cover version]]s of this song by American musicians, Box Hill is sometimes changed to [[Knoxville]], a city in [[Tennessee]].\n\n[[Ben Watt]]'s 1983 debut album ''[[North Marine Drive]]'' contained a song entitled \"On Box Hill.\"\n\nActor and singer [[Tom Felton]]'s song called ''Time Well Spent'' mentions him going to \"chill out on Box Hill\".<ref>{{cite web |url= http://feltbeats.com/music/time-well-spent-lyrics/ |title= Time Well Spent \u2013 Tom Felton |author=<!--Not stated--> |website= Feltbeats.com |publisher= Feltbeats.com  |access-date= 13 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Film===\n\nThe racing scenes during the opening credits of the 1968 film [[Chitty Chitty Bang Bang]] were filmed on the Zig Zag Road.<ref>{{cite news |first= Martin |last= Cholton |title= 10 things you didn\u2019t know about Chitty Chitty Bang Bang |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/chitty-chitty-bang-bang-50-anniversary-dick-van-dyke-a8680251.html |date= 20 December 2018 |access-date= 19 October 2019 |work= The Independent }}</ref>\n\nThe 2012 British film ''[[Berberian Sound Studio]]'' contains a short [[Story within a story#Nested films|film-within-the-film]] \u2013 a spoof 1970s-style documentary about the outstanding natural and man-made features of Box Hill.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/aug/30/berberian-sound-studio-review |title= Berberian Sound Studio \u2013 review |author= Peter Bradshaw |date= 30 August 2012 |website= The Guardian |author-link= Peter Bradshaw |access-date= 13 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==In the news==\nIn 1995 teenager [[Disappearance of Ruth Wilson|Ruth Wilson]] disappeared after being dropped off by taxi on Box Hill.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2002/dec/15/features.magazine57|title=The vanishing|last=Bright|first=Martin|date=2002-12-15|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-06-25}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 a body that had lain undiscovered for two years was found on Box Hill.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/local-news/body-box-hill-identified-missing-4721925|title=Body on Box Hill identified as missing man|last=Martin|first=Guy|date=2013-05-28|work=getsurrey|access-date=2018-06-24}}</ref> It was identified as missing teacher Brian Hynard who had left two suicide notes before disappearing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-vanishing-bs252s00wcv|title=The vanishing|last=Boggan|first=Steve|date=2013-08-11|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=2018-06-24|language=en|issn=0956-1382}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n[[File:Headley Heath (geograph 5380881).jpg|thumb|upright|Pond on Headley Heath.]]\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |title= The South East of England: Exploring Woodland |last1= Ashton |first1= S |last2= Blight |first2= G |year= 2006 | publisher= Frances Lincoln |location= London |isbn= 978-0-7112-2659-3 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= The Box Hill Book of Archaeology |last= Bannister |first=NR |year= 1999 |publisher= Friends of Box Hill |location= Dorking, Surrey |isbn= 0-9534430-1-9 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= The London Mobilisation Centres |last1= Beanse |first1= Alec |last2= Gill |first2= Roger  |year= 2011 |isbn=978-0954845377 |publisher= David Moore |location= Hampshire |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= Box Hill, a descriptive poem |last= Beavan |first= E |year= 1777 |publisher= Wilkie |location= London |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= The Old Road |url= https://archive.org/details/theoldroad00belluoft |last= Belloc |first=H |authorlink=Hilaire Belloc |year= 1911 |publisher= Constable and Company |location= London |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= A topographical history of Surrey |last1= Brayley |first1= E. W. |authorlink1=Edward Wedlake Brayley |last2= Britton |first2=J. |authorlink2=John Britton (antiquary) |year= 1841 | publisher= Dorking |location= Surrey |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1= Burns |first1= RW |title= John Logie Baird: Television pioneer |series= History of Technology |volume= 28 |year= 2000 |publisher= Institution of Electrical Engineers |location= London |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Chadwick |first1=AA |last2=Chadwick |first2=AE |title= The Classic Cattleyas |year= 2006 |publisher= Timber Press |location= Portland, Oregon |isbn= 978-0-88192-764-1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= Box Hill |last1= Chapman |first1= GM |last2= Young |first2= RHD |year= 1979 |publisher= Serendip |location= Lyme Regis |isbn= 0-9504143-1-X|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1= Headley |first1= G |last2= Meulenkamp |first2= W  |title= Follies: A National Trust Guide |year= 1986 |publisher= Jonathan Cape |location= London |isbn= 0-224-02105-2  | ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1= Lander |first1= J |title= Peter Labilliere: The Man Buried Upside Down on Box Hill |year= 2000 |publisher= Post Press |location= Chertsey |isbn= 978-0-9532424-1-2 | ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1= Littledale |first1= H |last2= Locock |first2= L M |last3= Sankey | first3=J H P\n  |title= Box Hill |year= 1984 |publisher= Box Hill Management Committee |location= Dorking, Surrey | ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book  |last= Margary |first= Ivan D |authorlink= Ivan Margary |title= Roman Ways in the Weald |publisher= J M Dent |year= 1948 |location= London |isbn =0-460-07742-2 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1= Mountford |first1= F |title= The Box Hill Guide |year= 1974 |publisher= Mountford |location= Tadworth |isbn= 0-9503540-0-7 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= The Box Hill Book of Orchids |last= Sankey |first= A |year= 2000 |publisher= Friends of Box Hill |location= Dorking, Surrey |isbn= 0-9534430-2-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Shepperd |first=Ronald |title= Micklam the story of a parish |year= 1991 |publisher= Mickleham Publications |isbn= 0-9518305-0-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= English Eccentrics and Eccentricities |last= Timbs |first= J |year= 1877 |volume=1 |publisher= Chatto and Windus |location= London |url= https://archive.org/details/englisheccentric50439gut |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= Box Hill |last= Tuson |first= Dan |year= 2013 |publisher= The National Trust |location= London |isbn= 978-1-84359-367-6 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= Broadwood by Appointment: A History |last= Wainwright |first= D |year= 1982 |publisher= Quiller Press |location= London |isbn= 0-907621-10-4 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1= Warren |first1= S |title= 100 Greatest Cycling Climbs: A road cyclist's guide to Britain's hills |year= 2010  |publisher= Frances Lincoln |location= London |isbn= 978-0-7112-3120-7 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= London's Countryside : Geographical Field Work for Students and Teachers of Geography |url= https://archive.org/details/londonscountrysi0000wool |url-access= registration |last1= Wooldridge |first1= SW |last2= Hutchings |first2= GE |year= 1957 |publisher= Methuen |location= London |ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Box Hill}}\n*[http://www.boxhillcommunity.com/ Box Hill community website]\n*[https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/box-hill Box Hill \u2013 National Trust]\n*[https://www.surreywildlifetrust.org/nature-reserves/betchworth-quarry-lime-kilns Betchworth Quarry \u2013 Surrey Wildlife Trust]\n*[https://www.surreywildlifetrust.org/nature-reserves/brockham-limeworks Brockham Quarry \u2013 Surrey Wildlife Trust]\n*[https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/headley-heath Headley Heath \u2013 National Trust]\n*[https://www.surreyoutdoorlearning.uk/facilities/high-ashurst High Ashurst \u2013 Surrey Outdoor Learning]\n*[https://www.field-studies-council.org/locations/juniperhall/ Juniper Hall \u2013 Field Studies Council]\n\n{{Geographic location\n|title     = '''Nearest Settlements'''\n|Centre    = Box Hill\n|North     = Tyrrells Wood\n|Northeast = [[Headley, Surrey|Headley]]\n|East      = [[Colley Hill]]\n|Southeast = [[Betchworth]]\n|South     = [[Brockham]] \n|Southwest = [[Pixham]]<br>[[Dorking]]\n|West      = [[Westhumble]]\n|Northwest = [[Mickleham, Surrey|Mickleham]]<br>[[Leatherhead]]\n}}\n{{Mole Valley}}\n{{Surrey Hills AONB}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hills of Surrey]]\n[[Category:National Trust properties in Surrey]]\n[[Category:Box Hill, Surrey]]\n[[Category:Climbs in cycle racing in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:RideLondon\u2013Surrey Classic]]\n[[Category:Cycle racing in England]]\n", "name_user": "Mertbiol", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWeypole and Stepping Stones:photo caption", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Box_Hill,_Surrey"}
{"title_page": "Salman Butt", "text_new": "{{Short description|Pakistani cricketer}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2011}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n|                name = Salman Butt<br />{{Nastaliq|\u0633\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0679 }}\n|               image = \n|             country = Pakistan\n|            fullname = Salman Butt\n|            nickname = \n|          birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1984|10|7|df=y}}\n|         birth_place = [[Lahore]], [[Punjab, Pakistan]]\n|            heightft = \n|          heightinch = \n|             heightm = 1.70\n|             batting = Left-handed\n|             bowling = Right-arm [[off spin]]\n|                role = Opening [[batsman]]\n|               club1 = Lahore Whites\n|               year1 = 2000/01\u20132004/05\n|         clubnumber1 = \n|               club2 = Lahore Blues\n|               year2 = 2001/02\n|         clubnumber2 = \n|               club3 = [[National Bank of Pakistan cricket team|National Bank of Pakistan]]\n|               year3 = 2000/01\u20132007/08\n|         clubnumber3 = \n|               club4 = Lahore Shalimar\n|               year4 = 2006/07\n|         clubnumber4 = 8\n|               club5 = [[Lahore Eagles]]\n|               year5 = 2004/05\u20132006/07\n|         clubnumber5 = \n|               club6 = [[Kolkata Knight Riders]]\n|               year6 = 2008\n|         clubnumber6 = \n|               club7 = [[Lahore Lions]]\n|               year7 = 2009\n|         clubnumber7 = \n|               club8 = [[Lahore Qalandars]]\n|               year8 = 2019 - present\n|         clubnumber8 =\n|               year9 = 2019 - present\n|               club9 = [[Central Punjab cricket team|Central Punjab]]\n|         clubnumber9 =\n|               \n|       international = true\n|       testdebutdate = 3 September\n|   internationalspan = 2003\u20132010\n|       testdebutyear = 2003\n|    testdebutagainst = Bangladesh\n|             testcap = 178\n| lasttestdate = 26 August\n| lasttestyear = 2010\n| lasttestagainst = England\n|odidebutdate = 22 September\n|odidebutyear = 2004\n|odidebutagainst = West Indies\n|odicap = 150\n|odishirt = 1\n|        lastodidate = 19 June\n|        lastodiyear = 2010\n|     lastodiagainst = India\n|       T20Idebutdate = 2 September\n|       T20Idebutyear = 2007\n|    T20Idebutagainst = Bangladesh\n|             oneT20I = \n|        lastT20Idate = 6 July\n|        lastT20Iyear = 2010\n|     lastT20Iagainst = Australia\n|             T20Icap = 18\n|columns = 4\n|column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n|matches1 = 33\n|runs1 = 1,889\n|bat avg1 = 30.46\n|100s/50s1 = 3/10\n|top score1 = 122\n|deliveries1 = 137\n|wickets1 = 1\n|bowl avg1 = 106.00\n|fivefor1 = 0\n|tenfor1 = 0\n|best bowling1 = 1/36\n|catches/stumpings1 = 12/\u2013\n|column2 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n|matches2 = 78\n|runs2 = 2,725\n|bat avg2 = 36.82\n|100s/50s2 = 8/14\n|top score2 = 136\n|deliveries2 = 69\n|wickets2 = 0\n|bowl avg2 = \u2013\n|fivefor2 = \u2013\n|tenfor2 = \u2013\n|best bowling2 = \u2013\n|catches/stumpings2 = 20/\u2013\n|             column3 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n|            matches3 = 121\n|               runs3 = 8,020\n|            bat avg3 = 39.90\n|           100s/50s3 = 22/32\n|          top score3 = 290\n|         deliveries3 = 1,096\n|            wickets3 = 13\n|           bowl avg3 = 56.30\n|            fivefor3 = 0\n|             tenfor3 = 0\n|       best bowling3 = 4/82\n|  catches/stumpings3 = 50/\u2013\n|             column4 = [[List A cricket|LA]]\n|            matches4 = 202\n|               runs4 = 8,432\n|            bat avg4 = 46.32\n|           100s/50s4 = 23/47\n|          top score4 = 150[[not out|*]]\n|         deliveries4 = 547\n|            wickets4 = 10\n|           bowl avg4 = 50.00\n|            fivefor4 = 0\n|             tenfor4 = 0\n|       best bowling4 = 2/26\n|  catches/stumpings4 = 56/\u2013\n|date = 23 March\n|year = 2019\n|source = http://www.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/player/42683.html Cricinfo\n}}\n{{Contains Urdu text}}\n'''Salman Butt''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0633\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0679 }}}}, born 7 October 1984) is a Pakistani cricketer and YouTuber who currently plays for [[Lahore Qalandars]]. He is a former captain of Pakistan cricket team who was previously banned for five years for his involvement in [[Pakistan cricket spot-fixing scandal|2010 spot-fixing scandal]].\n\nHe had been a regular [[Test cricket|Test]] and [[One Day International|ODI]] left-handed [[batting order (cricket)#opening batsman|opening batsman]]. He made his Test debut on 3 September 2003 in the third Test against [[Bangladesh national cricket team|Bangladesh]], and a year later, made his ODI debut against [[West Indies national cricket team|West Indies]] on 22 September 2004. He was appointed captain of the Pakistan Test squad on 16 July 2010.\n\nOn 29 August 2010, he was implicated in allegations of [[spot-fixing]]. On 31 August 2010, he was stripped of the Pakistan captaincy, and removed from the ODI Squad pending criminal proceedings. He was banned from playing cricket for ten years, of which five years was a suspended sentence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsoftheworld.co.uk/news/924349/Cricket-in-the-dock-as-we-expose-match-fixing-scandal-England-Pakistan-Test-no-balls-bribes.html|title=Match-fixer pockets \u00a3150k as he rigs England Test at Lord's|work=News of the World|accessdate=2 October 2010}}</ref> In November 2011, he was convicted and jailed for 30 months for conspiracy charges relating to the spot-fixing, along with [[Mohammad Amir]] and [[Mohammad Asif (cricketer)|Mohammad Asif]].<ref name=BBCConvict>{{cite news|title=Pakistan cricketers guilty of betting sca|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-15538516|accessdate=1 November 2011|newspaper=BBC News |date=1 November 2011}}</ref> On June 21, 2012, he was released from jail.\n\nIn August 2015, bans on Butt and fellow conspirators [[Mohammad Amir]] and [[Mohammad Asif (cricketer)|Mohammad Asif]] were lifted by the [[International Cricket Council]], allowing them to return to all forms of cricket from September 2, 2015.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/911071.html?CMP=chrome Amir, Asif, Butt free to play all cricket from September 2]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.icc-cricket.com/news/2015/media-releases/89520/icc-confirms-sanctions-against-asif-and-butt-will-expire-on-1-september-2015 |title=ICC confirms sanctions against Asif and Butt will expire on 1 September 2015 |access-date=19 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924044107/http://www.icc-cricket.com/news/2015/media-releases/89520/icc-confirms-sanctions-against-asif-and-butt-will-expire-on-1-september-2015 |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Career ==\n\n===Early career===\n\nButt started in the Under-15 then Under-17s where he played first international match during Asia cup under-17 series held in Karachi as a opening batsman and captain of the team. Other Pakistan team players like Najaf Shah, [[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wahab_Riaz|Whahab Riaz]], [[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adnan_Akmal|Adnan Akmal]], and Famous Pakistani [https://adeelchaudry.pk Food connoisseur], chef and [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCUJAmh8MQVK31FpeC7cHXNw?view_as=subscriber philanthropist Adeel Chaudry] was also part of the team. and quickly progressed through Under-19 level, although at that time he was much younger than the age limits suggest, making his senior debut for Lahore Whites in 2000 aged only 15. His talent was noticed immediately, which led to him being given a place in the Pakistan A team against [[England national cricket team|England]] soon after. However, instead of rushing straight for the limelight of international cricket, he got his head down and consolidated by playing consistently for his region and the youth teams, until the Pakistan selectors finally drafted him in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricketfundas.com/salmanbutt.html |title=Salman Butt: Opening the Future of Success |publisher=Cricketfundas.com |accessdate=4 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n===International cricket===\n\nAfter his debut, Butt was dropped, and he struggled to regain his place due to some stiff competition for the openers' spots. He returned for the Champions' Trophy in 2004 and scored his first fifty for Pakistan in the Paktel Cup against [[Sri Lanka national cricket team|Sri Lanka]]. In the ODI against India on 13 November 2004, as Pakistan chased down 292, he formed partnerships first with [[Shoaib Malik]], putting on 113, and subsequently with [[Inzamam-Ul-Haq]]. Despite having retired for seven overs due to severe cramp, he returned to steer Pakistan home, finishing on 108 not out.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mGcTn9ZAWEI |title=Inzamam and Salman Butt sink India!! |publisher=YouTube |date=28 March 2007 |accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nYet 2005 saw little improvement, and doubts circulated about his defensive technique, causing him to be shuffled in and out of the side. But things started looking up again during the winter Test series against England, in which he scored a century and two fifties, with a more cautious attitude to his innings building than he had previously shown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/player/42683.html |title=Cricinfo \u2013 Players and Officials \u2013 Salman Butt |publisher=Content-usa.cricinfo.com |accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nFor his performances in 2008, he was named as 12th man in the World ODI XI by the ICC.<ref>http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci-icc/content/story/369272.html</ref>\n\n===Appointment as Test captain===\n\nOn 17 July 2010, the [[Pakistan Cricket Board]] appointed Butt as captain of the Pakistani Test squad in place of [[Shahid Afridi]], who announced his retirement from Test cricket after Pakistan lost the first [[Australian cricket team against Pakistan in England in 2010|test match against Australia]].<ref name=\"captain\">{{cite web|title=Salman Butt named captain for rest of England tour|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/pakistan-v-australia-2010/content/current/story/467691.html|publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=17 July 2010|author=Osman Samiuddin}}</ref> He became the 28th captain of the Pakistani Test team and the fifth to lead them since January 2009.<ref name=\"captain\"/>\n\nOn 23 July 2010, Salman Butt led Pakistan to victory against Australia in his first appearance as Pakistan's test team captain.\n\n===Spot-fixing scandal===\n\n{{main|Pakistan cricket spot-fixing controversy}}\nIn August 2010, Butt and two other players, [[Mohammad Amir]] and [[Mohammad Asif (cricketer)|Mohammad Asif]], were among those named by a ''[[News of the World]]'' sting where undercover reporters paid an agent loosely affiliated with several players on Pakistan's squad a bribe in return for detailed information on when no-balls would be bowled.\n\nButt, Amir, and Asif were dropped from the Pakistan team for the limited-over series (two Twenty20 games, and five ODI games). However, on 2 September 2010, after the warm-up [[List A]] game between Pakistan and Somerset, the [[International Cricket Council]] announced that they had suspended Asif, Amir and Butt under the provisions of the ICC's Anti-Corruption Code. The statement from the ICC stated that the three players were charged \"under various offences under Article 2 of the ICC Anti-Corruption Code for Players and Player Support Personnel relating to alleged irregular behaviour during, and in relation to, the fourth Test between England and Pakistan at Lord's last month\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/england-v-pakistan-2010/content/current/story/475624.html|title=ICC suspend trio under anti-corruption code|work=Cricinfo|accessdate=2 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nLater it became known that Butt and the other two players implicated in the scandal were in possession of bills with the same serial numbers as those the reporter had paid Majeed earlier. Butt was provisionally suspended from playing International Cricket due to the fact that the ICC wanted his name cleared before he resumed playing cricket. In late September, Butt filed an appeal to the ICC asking them to lift his temporary suspension.<ref>{{cite web|title=Salman Butt appeals against ICC suspension|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/current/story/479203.html|work=Cricinfo|accessdate=2 October 2010}}</ref> After Mohammad Asif had dropped his appeal against the charges so that he could understand the charges filed against him, Butt said he was determined to prove his innocence and that his appeal was going to go ahead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/483267.html |title=Spot-fixing controversy: Salman Butt determined to prove innocence &#124; Pakistan Cricket News &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with the Associated Press, Butt stated \"I do not want to comment on ''The News of the World'' because everybody knows what kind of paper it is. Everybody knows about its reputation across the world.\" He also stated that he was linked to [[Mazhar Majeed]] as a player agent but not in any spot-fixing. He also stated that the video can easily be edited and modified and manipulated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/483933.html |title=Spot-fixing controversy: News of the World Sting not reliable, says Salman Butt &#124; Pakistan Cricket News &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref> One day before the hearing, Butt continued to state his innocence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/69374/i-am-not-guilty-and-i-am-very-sure-about-it/ |title=\u2018I am not guilty and I am very sure about it\u2019 \u2013 The Express Tribune |publisher=Tribune.com.pk |date=29 October 2010 |accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref> The tribunal announced that a verdict on the decision had been deferred to 5 February 2011 and that the ICC also stated that the tribunal would rule on charges pertaining to the third Test match between England and Pakistan. Butt was the only player before the tribunal to face these additional charges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/496306.html |title=Spot-fixing controversy: Tribunal defers spot-fixing verdict till February 5 &#124; Pakistan Cricket News |publisher=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 February 2011, the three-man tribunal delivered its verdict. One charge was dismissed against Butt from the third Test match (batting out a maiden over), but the other charges (failing to report an advance from the third Test match and ordering Asif and Amir to bowl no-balls in the fourth Test) were proved, and Butt was banned from the sport of cricket for ten years, five of which were suspended should he not commit any further offences and participate in a Pakistani Cricket Board anti-corruption program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci-icc/content/current/story/499614.html |title=The spot-fixing scandal: Butt out for 10 years, Asif 7 and Amir 5 &#124; Cricket News &#124; Cricinfo ICC Site |publisher=ESPN Cricinfo |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Return to domestic cricket===\nIn January 2016, the [[Pakistan Cricket Board|PCB]] allowed Butt to play in the National One Day Cup, in which he played for [[Water and Power Development Authority cricket team|WAPDA]] and scored 536 in 7 matches at an average of 107, ending up one of the leading run-scorers in the tournament. He was the man of the match in the final of the [[2016\u201317 Quaid-e-Azam Trophy]], scoring a century in both innings. WAPDA won the title.<ref name=\"WAPDA\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/quaid-e-azam-2016-17/content/story/1072756.html |title=Butt ton secures WAPDA's maiden title |accessdate=15 December 2016 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref> During the [[2017-18 National T20 Cup]] he jointly with [[Kamran Akmal]] set the world record opening partnership in T20 history of unbeaten 209 runstand, surpassing the previous highest opening partnership of 207 in any form of T20 cricket held by [[Joe Denly]] and [[Daniel Bell-Drummond]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/1125657.html|title=27th Match, National T20 Cup at Rawalpindi, Nov 24 2017 {{!}} Match Summary {{!}} ESPNCricinfo|website=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/cricket/salman-butt-kamran-akmal-create-batting-record-in-pakistan-s-national-t20-cup/story-fUzuhtHP1b92Ldt8IVqMKM.html|title=Salman Butt, Kamran Akmal set opening record in Pakistan\u2019s National T20 Cup|date=2017-11-24|work=hindustantimes.com/|access-date=2017-11-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/sports/cricket/kamran-akmal-salman-butt-create-record-for-highest-t20-partnership-for-opening-wicket-4952395/|title=Kamran Akmal, Salman Butt create record for highest T20 partnership for opening wicket|date=2017-11-24|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2017-11-26|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/21536116/kamran-akmal,-butt-blitz-record-opening-stand-lahore-win|title=Kamran Akmal, Butt blitz record opening stand in Lahore win|work=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/305253.html|title=Records {{!}} Twenty20 matches {{!}} Partnership records {{!}} Highest partnership for the first wicket {{!}} ESPN Cricinfo|work=Cricinfo|access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref> The record runstand was also the third highest partnership in terms of runs for any wicket in T20 history.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/305251.html|title=Records {{!}} Twenty20 matches {{!}} Partnership records {{!}} Highest partnerships for any wicket {{!}} ESPN Cricinfo|work=Cricinfo|access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, he was named in [[Sindh cricket team|Sindh]]'s squad for the [[2018 Pakistan Cup]].<ref name=\"squads1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/191967-pakistan-cup-one-day-tournament-to-begin-in-faisalabad |title=Pakistan Cup one-day tournament to begin in Faisalabad next week |accessdate=21 April 2018 |work=Geo TV}}</ref><ref name=\"squads2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/306831-pakistan-cup-cricket-from-25th |title=Pakistan Cup Cricket from 25th |accessdate=21 April 2018 |work=The News International}}</ref> He was the leading run-scorer in the [[2018\u201319 Quaid-e-Azam One Day Cup]], with 559 runs in ten matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=12569;type=tournament |title=Quaid-e-Azam One Day Cup, 2018/19: Most runs |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=4 November 2018}}</ref> He was also the leading run-scorer for Water and Power Development Authority in the [[2018\u201319 Quaid-e-Azam Trophy]], with 610 runs in ten matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=12568;team=3185;type=tournament |title=Quaid-e-Azam Trophy, 2018/19 - Water and Power Development Authority: Batting and bowling averages |accessdate=22 November 2018}}</ref> In March 2019, he was named as the captain of [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa cricket team|Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]'s squad for the [[2019 Pakistan Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcb.com.pk/press-release-detail/federal-areas-aim-to-complete-hat-trick-of-pakistan-cup-titles.html |title=Federal Areas aim to complete hat-trick of Pakistan Cup titles |work=Pakistan Cricket Board |accessdate=25 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/447913-pakistan-cup-one-day-cricket-from-april-2 |title=Pakistan Cup one-day cricket from April 2 |accessdate=25 March 2019 |work=The International News}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, he was named in [[Central Punjab cricket team|Central Punjab]]'s squad for the [[2019\u201320 Quaid-e-Azam Trophy]] tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcb.com.pk/press-release-detail/pcb-announces-squads-for-2019-20-domestic-season.html |title=PCB announces squads for 2019-20 domestic season |work=Pakistan Cricket Board |accessdate=4 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/27527401/sarfaraz-ahmed-babar-azam-take-charge-pakistan-domestic-sides |title=Sarfaraz Ahmed and Babar Azam to take charge of Pakistan domestic sides |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=4 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December he was selected to play for the Falcon Hunters in the inaugural Qatar T10 League. In his first game he made 39 of 27 and with 5 needed of he last ball hit a Miandad-esque 6 leading his team to victory. https://www.republicworld.com/sports-news/cricket-news/qatar-t10-salman-butt-does-a-javed-miandad-hits-six-off-the-last-ball.html\n\n==Playing style==\n\nAn accumulator, Butt works hard for his runs, not indulging in too many big hits; his statistics show the low number of 19 international sixes to date (1 September 2010) of which he's scored 10 in Twenty20 cricket, 7 in One-Day Internationals and only six in Test cricket.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cricketpointer.com/salman-butt-adnan-akmal-under-consideration-for-australia-tour/|title=PAKISTAN PLAYER PROFILES &#124; Sporting Life \u2013 Cricket News &#124; Live Cricket Scores, New Zealand v England, CB Series, Live Coverage & Stats |publisher=Sporting Life |accessdate=6 February 2011 }} </ref> He scores a lot of his runs between [[Cricket fielding positions|backward point]] and [[Cricket fielding positions|extra cover]]. He uses his superb wrist work to angle the bat, placing the ball into gaps using the pace of the ball to his advantage; a very good technique for ODIs where it is best to keep the scoreboard ticking all the time. He also has the ability to cut the ball very fine down to [[Cricket fielding positions|third man]] if there are no [[Cricket fielding positions|slips]], especially against spin bowlers, as he showed to great effect in his above-mentioned innings of 108 not out. These are his specialties, but he has large range of shots. However, many commentators have expressed that his defensive technique has flaws, and that he is prone to playing at balls outside off-stump which should be left.<ref>[https://cricketpointer.com/salman-butt-adnan-akmal-under-consideration-for-australia-tour/] </ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of cricketers banned for match fixing]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{cricinfo|id=42683}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|\nbefore= [[Shahid Afridi]]|\ntitle= [[Pakistani national cricket captains|Pakistani national cricket captain]] ([[Test Cricket|Tests]])|\nyears= 2010|\nafter= [[Misbah-ul-Haq]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Pakistan Test Cricket Captains}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= Pakistan squads \n|bg= #01411C\n|fg= #F8B800\n|bordercolor= #00A000\n|list1=\n{{Pakistan Squad 2009 ICC World Twenty20}}\n}}\n{{Lahore Qalandars squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Butt, Salman}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pakistani people of Kashmiri descent]]\n[[Category:Pakistan One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Lahore cricketers]]\n[[Category:Kolkata Knight Riders cricketers]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Test cricket captains]]\n[[Category:Pakistani cricketers]]\n[[Category:Pakistani people imprisoned abroad]]\n[[Category:Cricketers from Lahore]]\n[[Category:Lahore Whites cricketers]]\n[[Category:National Bank of Pakistan cricketers]]\n[[Category:Lahore Blues cricketers]]\n[[Category:Lahore Eagles cricketers]]\n[[Category:Lahore Qalandars cricketers]]\n[[Category:Punjab (Pakistan) cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers banned for corruption]]\n[[Category:Water and Power Development Authority cricketers]]\n[[Category:Khyber Pakhtunkhwa cricketers]]\n[[Category:Pakistani YouTubers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Pakistani cricketer}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2011}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n|                name = Salman Butt<br />{{Nastaliq|\u0633\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0679 }}\n|               image = \n|             country = Pakistan\n|            fullname = Salman Butt\n|            nickname = \n|          birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1984|10|7|df=y}}\n|         birth_place = [[Lahore]], [[Punjab, Pakistan]]\n|            heightft = \n|          heightinch = \n|             heightm = 1.70\n|             batting = Left-handed\n|             bowling = Right-arm [[off spin]]\n|                role = Opening [[batsman]]\n|               club1 = Lahore Whites\n|               year1 = 2000/01\u20132004/05\n|         clubnumber1 = \n|               club2 = Lahore Blues\n|               year2 = 2001/02\n|         clubnumber2 = \n|               club3 = [[National Bank of Pakistan cricket team|National Bank of Pakistan]]\n|               year3 = 2000/01\u20132007/08\n|         clubnumber3 = \n|               club4 = Lahore Shalimar\n|               year4 = 2006/07\n|         clubnumber4 = 8\n|               club5 = [[Lahore Eagles]]\n|               year5 = 2004/05\u20132006/07\n|         clubnumber5 = \n|               club6 = [[Kolkata Knight Riders]]\n|               year6 = 2008\n|         clubnumber6 = \n|               club7 = [[Lahore Lions]]\n|               year7 = 2009\n|         clubnumber7 = \n|               club8 = [[Lahore Qalandars]]\n|               year8 = 2019 - present\n|         clubnumber8 =\n|               year9 = 2019 - present\n|               club9 = [[Central Punjab cricket team|Central Punjab]]\n|         clubnumber9 =\n|               \n|       international = true\n|       testdebutdate = 3 September\n|   internationalspan = 2003\u20132010\n|       testdebutyear = 2003\n|    testdebutagainst = Bangladesh\n|             testcap = 178\n| lasttestdate = 26 August\n| lasttestyear = 2010\n| lasttestagainst = England\n|odidebutdate = 22 September\n|odidebutyear = 2004\n|odidebutagainst = West Indies\n|odicap = 150\n|odishirt = 1\n|        lastodidate = 19 June\n|        lastodiyear = 2010\n|     lastodiagainst = India\n|       T20Idebutdate = 2 September\n|       T20Idebutyear = 2007\n|    T20Idebutagainst = Bangladesh\n|             oneT20I = \n|        lastT20Idate = 6 July\n|        lastT20Iyear = 2010\n|     lastT20Iagainst = Australia\n|             T20Icap = 18\n|columns = 4\n|column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n|matches1 = 33\n|runs1 = 1,889\n|bat avg1 = 30.46\n|100s/50s1 = 3/10\n|top score1 = 122\n|deliveries1 = 137\n|wickets1 = 1\n|bowl avg1 = 106.00\n|fivefor1 = 0\n|tenfor1 = 0\n|best bowling1 = 1/36\n|catches/stumpings1 = 12/\u2013\n|column2 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n|matches2 = 78\n|runs2 = 2,725\n|bat avg2 = 36.82\n|100s/50s2 = 8/14\n|top score2 = 136\n|deliveries2 = 69\n|wickets2 = 0\n|bowl avg2 = \u2013\n|fivefor2 = \u2013\n|tenfor2 = \u2013\n|best bowling2 = \u2013\n|catches/stumpings2 = 20/\u2013\n|             column3 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n|            matches3 = 121\n|               runs3 = 8,020\n|            bat avg3 = 39.90\n|           100s/50s3 = 22/32\n|          top score3 = 290\n|         deliveries3 = 1,096\n|            wickets3 = 13\n|           bowl avg3 = 56.30\n|            fivefor3 = 0\n|             tenfor3 = 0\n|       best bowling3 = 4/82\n|  catches/stumpings3 = 50/\u2013\n|             column4 = [[List A cricket|LA]]\n|            matches4 = 202\n|               runs4 = 8,432\n|            bat avg4 = 46.32\n|           100s/50s4 = 23/47\n|          top score4 = 150[[not out|*]]\n|         deliveries4 = 547\n|            wickets4 = 10\n|           bowl avg4 = 50.00\n|            fivefor4 = 0\n|             tenfor4 = 0\n|       best bowling4 = 2/26\n|  catches/stumpings4 = 56/\u2013\n|date = 23 March\n|year = 2019\n|source = http://www.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/player/42683.html Cricinfo\n}}\n{{Contains Urdu text}}\n'''Salman Butt''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0633\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0679 }}}}, born 7 October 1984) is a Pakistani cricketer and YouTuber who currently plays for [[Lahore Qalandars]]. He is a former captain of Pakistan cricket team who was previously banned for five years for his involvement in [[Pakistan cricket spot-fixing scandal|2010 spot-fixing scandal]].\n\nHe had been a regular [[Test cricket|Test]] and [[One Day International|ODI]] left-handed [[batting order (cricket)#opening batsman|opening batsman]]. He made his Test debut on 3 September 2003 in the third Test against [[Bangladesh national cricket team|Bangladesh]], and a year later, made his ODI debut against [[West Indies national cricket team|West Indies]] on 22 September 2004. He was appointed captain of the Pakistan Test squad on 16 July 2010.\n\nOn 29 August 2010, he was implicated in allegations of [[spot-fixing]]. On 31 August 2010, he was stripped of the Pakistan captaincy, and removed from the ODI Squad pending criminal proceedings. He was banned from playing cricket for ten years, of which five years was a suspended sentence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsoftheworld.co.uk/news/924349/Cricket-in-the-dock-as-we-expose-match-fixing-scandal-England-Pakistan-Test-no-balls-bribes.html|title=Match-fixer pockets \u00a3150k as he rigs England Test at Lord's|work=News of the World|accessdate=2 October 2010}}</ref> In November 2011, he was convicted and jailed for 30 months for conspiracy charges relating to the spot-fixing, along with [[Mohammad Amir]] and [[Mohammad Asif (cricketer)|Mohammad Asif]].<ref name=BBCConvict>{{cite news|title=Pakistan cricketers guilty of betting sca|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-15538516|accessdate=1 November 2011|newspaper=BBC News |date=1 November 2011}}</ref> On June 21, 2012, he was released from jail.\n\nIn August 2015, bans on Butt and fellow conspirators [[Mohammad Amir]] and [[Mohammad Asif (cricketer)|Mohammad Asif]] were lifted by the [[International Cricket Council]], allowing them to return to all forms of cricket from September 2, 2015.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/911071.html?CMP=chrome Amir, Asif, Butt free to play all cricket from September 2]</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.icc-cricket.com/news/2015/media-releases/89520/icc-confirms-sanctions-against-asif-and-butt-will-expire-on-1-september-2015 |title=ICC confirms sanctions against Asif and Butt will expire on 1 September 2015 |access-date=19 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924044107/http://www.icc-cricket.com/news/2015/media-releases/89520/icc-confirms-sanctions-against-asif-and-butt-will-expire-on-1-september-2015 |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Career ==\n\n===Early career===\n\nButt started in the Under-17s and quickly progressed through Under-19 level, although at that time he was much younger than the age limits suggest, making his senior debut for Lahore Whites in 2000 aged only 15. His talent was noticed immediately, which led to him being given a place in the Pakistan A team against [[England national cricket team|England]] soon after. However, instead of rushing straight for the limelight of international cricket, he got his head down and consolidated by playing consistently for his region and the youth teams, until the Pakistan selectors finally drafted him in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricketfundas.com/salmanbutt.html |title=Salman Butt: Opening the Future of Success |publisher=Cricketfundas.com |accessdate=4 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n===International cricket===\n\nAfter his debut, Butt was dropped, and he struggled to regain his place due to some stiff competition for the openers' spots. He returned for the Champions' Trophy in 2004 and scored his first fifty for Pakistan in the Paktel Cup against [[Sri Lanka national cricket team|Sri Lanka]]. In the ODI against India on 13 November 2004, as Pakistan chased down 292, he formed partnerships first with [[Shoaib Malik]], putting on 113, and subsequently with [[Inzamam-Ul-Haq]]. Despite having retired for seven overs due to severe cramp, he returned to steer Pakistan home, finishing on 108 not out.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mGcTn9ZAWEI |title=Inzamam and Salman Butt sink India!! |publisher=YouTube |date=28 March 2007 |accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nYet 2005 saw little improvement, and doubts circulated about his defensive technique, causing him to be shuffled in and out of the side. But things started looking up again during the winter Test series against England, in which he scored a century and two fifties, with a more cautious attitude to his innings building than he had previously shown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/player/42683.html |title=Cricinfo \u2013 Players and Officials \u2013 Salman Butt |publisher=Content-usa.cricinfo.com |accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nFor his performances in 2008, he was named as 12th man in the World ODI XI by the ICC.<ref>http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci-icc/content/story/369272.html</ref>\n\n===Appointment as Test captain===\n\nOn 17 July 2010, the [[Pakistan Cricket Board]] appointed Butt as captain of the Pakistani Test squad in place of [[Shahid Afridi]], who announced his retirement from Test cricket after Pakistan lost the first [[Australian cricket team against Pakistan in England in 2010|test match against Australia]].<ref name=\"captain\">{{cite web|title=Salman Butt named captain for rest of England tour|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/pakistan-v-australia-2010/content/current/story/467691.html|publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=17 July 2010|author=Osman Samiuddin}}</ref> He became the 28th captain of the Pakistani Test team and the fifth to lead them since January 2009.<ref name=\"captain\"/>\n\nOn 23 July 2010, Salman Butt led Pakistan to victory against Australia in his first appearance as Pakistan's test team captain.\n\n===Spot-fixing scandal===\n\n{{main|Pakistan cricket spot-fixing controversy}}\nIn August 2010, Butt and two other players, [[Mohammad Amir]] and [[Mohammad Asif (cricketer)|Mohammad Asif]], were among those named by a ''[[News of the World]]'' sting where undercover reporters paid an agent loosely affiliated with several players on Pakistan's squad a bribe in return for detailed information on when no-balls would be bowled.\n\nButt, Amir, and Asif were dropped from the Pakistan team for the limited-over series (two Twenty20 games, and five ODI games). However, on 2 September 2010, after the warm-up [[List A]] game between Pakistan and Somerset, the [[International Cricket Council]] announced that they had suspended Asif, Amir and Butt under the provisions of the ICC's Anti-Corruption Code. The statement from the ICC stated that the three players were charged \"under various offences under Article 2 of the ICC Anti-Corruption Code for Players and Player Support Personnel relating to alleged irregular behaviour during, and in relation to, the fourth Test between England and Pakistan at Lord's last month\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/england-v-pakistan-2010/content/current/story/475624.html|title=ICC suspend trio under anti-corruption code|work=Cricinfo|accessdate=2 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nLater it became known that Butt and the other two players implicated in the scandal were in possession of bills with the same serial numbers as those the reporter had paid Majeed earlier. Butt was provisionally suspended from playing International Cricket due to the fact that the ICC wanted his name cleared before he resumed playing cricket. In late September, Butt filed an appeal to the ICC asking them to lift his temporary suspension.<ref>{{cite web|title=Salman Butt appeals against ICC suspension|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/current/story/479203.html|work=Cricinfo|accessdate=2 October 2010}}</ref> After Mohammad Asif had dropped his appeal against the charges so that he could understand the charges filed against him, Butt said he was determined to prove his innocence and that his appeal was going to go ahead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/483267.html |title=Spot-fixing controversy: Salman Butt determined to prove innocence &#124; Pakistan Cricket News &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with the Associated Press, Butt stated \"I do not want to comment on ''The News of the World'' because everybody knows what kind of paper it is. Everybody knows about its reputation across the world.\" He also stated that he was linked to [[Mazhar Majeed]] as a player agent but not in any spot-fixing. He also stated that the video can easily be edited and modified and manipulated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/pakistan/content/story/483933.html |title=Spot-fixing controversy: News of the World Sting not reliable, says Salman Butt &#124; Pakistan Cricket News &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref> One day before the hearing, Butt continued to state his innocence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/69374/i-am-not-guilty-and-i-am-very-sure-about-it/ |title=\u2018I am not guilty and I am very sure about it\u2019 \u2013 The Express Tribune |publisher=Tribune.com.pk |date=29 October 2010 |accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref> The tribunal announced that a verdict on the decision had been deferred to 5 February 2011 and that the ICC also stated that the tribunal would rule on charges pertaining to the third Test match between England and Pakistan. Butt was the only player before the tribunal to face these additional charges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/pakistan/content/current/story/496306.html |title=Spot-fixing controversy: Tribunal defers spot-fixing verdict till February 5 &#124; Pakistan Cricket News |publisher=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 February 2011, the three-man tribunal delivered its verdict. One charge was dismissed against Butt from the third Test match (batting out a maiden over), but the other charges (failing to report an advance from the third Test match and ordering Asif and Amir to bowl no-balls in the fourth Test) were proved, and Butt was banned from the sport of cricket for ten years, five of which were suspended should he not commit any further offences and participate in a Pakistani Cricket Board anti-corruption program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci-icc/content/current/story/499614.html |title=The spot-fixing scandal: Butt out for 10 years, Asif 7 and Amir 5 &#124; Cricket News &#124; Cricinfo ICC Site |publisher=ESPN Cricinfo |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Return to domestic cricket===\nIn January 2016, the [[Pakistan Cricket Board|PCB]] allowed Butt to play in the National One Day Cup, in which he played for [[Water and Power Development Authority cricket team|WAPDA]] and scored 536 in 7 matches at an average of 107, ending up one of the leading run-scorers in the tournament. He was the man of the match in the final of the [[2016\u201317 Quaid-e-Azam Trophy]], scoring a century in both innings. WAPDA won the title.<ref name=\"WAPDA\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/quaid-e-azam-2016-17/content/story/1072756.html |title=Butt ton secures WAPDA's maiden title |accessdate=15 December 2016 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref> During the [[2017-18 National T20 Cup]] he jointly with [[Kamran Akmal]] set the world record opening partnership in T20 history of unbeaten 209 runstand, surpassing the previous highest opening partnership of 207 in any form of T20 cricket held by [[Joe Denly]] and [[Daniel Bell-Drummond]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/1125657.html|title=27th Match, National T20 Cup at Rawalpindi, Nov 24 2017 {{!}} Match Summary {{!}} ESPNCricinfo|website=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/cricket/salman-butt-kamran-akmal-create-batting-record-in-pakistan-s-national-t20-cup/story-fUzuhtHP1b92Ldt8IVqMKM.html|title=Salman Butt, Kamran Akmal set opening record in Pakistan\u2019s National T20 Cup|date=2017-11-24|work=hindustantimes.com/|access-date=2017-11-26|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/sports/cricket/kamran-akmal-salman-butt-create-record-for-highest-t20-partnership-for-opening-wicket-4952395/|title=Kamran Akmal, Salman Butt create record for highest T20 partnership for opening wicket|date=2017-11-24|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2017-11-26|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/21536116/kamran-akmal,-butt-blitz-record-opening-stand-lahore-win|title=Kamran Akmal, Butt blitz record opening stand in Lahore win|work=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/305253.html|title=Records {{!}} Twenty20 matches {{!}} Partnership records {{!}} Highest partnership for the first wicket {{!}} ESPN Cricinfo|work=Cricinfo|access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref> The record runstand was also the third highest partnership in terms of runs for any wicket in T20 history.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/305251.html|title=Records {{!}} Twenty20 matches {{!}} Partnership records {{!}} Highest partnerships for any wicket {{!}} ESPN Cricinfo|work=Cricinfo|access-date=2017-11-26}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, he was named in [[Sindh cricket team|Sindh]]'s squad for the [[2018 Pakistan Cup]].<ref name=\"squads1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/191967-pakistan-cup-one-day-tournament-to-begin-in-faisalabad |title=Pakistan Cup one-day tournament to begin in Faisalabad next week |accessdate=21 April 2018 |work=Geo TV}}</ref><ref name=\"squads2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/306831-pakistan-cup-cricket-from-25th |title=Pakistan Cup Cricket from 25th |accessdate=21 April 2018 |work=The News International}}</ref> He was the leading run-scorer in the [[2018\u201319 Quaid-e-Azam One Day Cup]], with 559 runs in ten matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=12569;type=tournament |title=Quaid-e-Azam One Day Cup, 2018/19: Most runs |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=4 November 2018}}</ref> He was also the leading run-scorer for Water and Power Development Authority in the [[2018\u201319 Quaid-e-Azam Trophy]], with 610 runs in ten matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=12568;team=3185;type=tournament |title=Quaid-e-Azam Trophy, 2018/19 - Water and Power Development Authority: Batting and bowling averages |accessdate=22 November 2018}}</ref> In March 2019, he was named as the captain of [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa cricket team|Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]'s squad for the [[2019 Pakistan Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcb.com.pk/press-release-detail/federal-areas-aim-to-complete-hat-trick-of-pakistan-cup-titles.html |title=Federal Areas aim to complete hat-trick of Pakistan Cup titles |work=Pakistan Cricket Board |accessdate=25 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/447913-pakistan-cup-one-day-cricket-from-april-2 |title=Pakistan Cup one-day cricket from April 2 |accessdate=25 March 2019 |work=The International News}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, he was named in [[Central Punjab cricket team|Central Punjab]]'s squad for the [[2019\u201320 Quaid-e-Azam Trophy]] tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcb.com.pk/press-release-detail/pcb-announces-squads-for-2019-20-domestic-season.html |title=PCB announces squads for 2019-20 domestic season |work=Pakistan Cricket Board |accessdate=4 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/27527401/sarfaraz-ahmed-babar-azam-take-charge-pakistan-domestic-sides |title=Sarfaraz Ahmed and Babar Azam to take charge of Pakistan domestic sides |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=4 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December he was selected to play for the Falcon Hunters in the inaugural Qatar T10 League. In his first game he made 39 of 27 and with 5 needed of he last ball hit a Miandad-esque 6 leading his team to victory. https://www.republicworld.com/sports-news/cricket-news/qatar-t10-salman-butt-does-a-javed-miandad-hits-six-off-the-last-ball.html\n\n==Playing style==\n\nAn accumulator, Butt works hard for his runs, not indulging in too many big hits; his statistics show the low number of 19 international sixes to date (1 September 2010) of which he's scored 10 in Twenty20 cricket, 7 in One-Day Internationals and only six in Test cricket.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cricketpointer.com/salman-butt-adnan-akmal-under-consideration-for-australia-tour/|title=PAKISTAN PLAYER PROFILES &#124; Sporting Life \u2013 Cricket News &#124; Live Cricket Scores, New Zealand v England, CB Series, Live Coverage & Stats |publisher=Sporting Life |accessdate=6 February 2011 }} </ref> He scores a lot of his runs between [[Cricket fielding positions|backward point]] and [[Cricket fielding positions|extra cover]]. He uses his superb wrist work to angle the bat, placing the ball into gaps using the pace of the ball to his advantage; a very good technique for ODIs where it is best to keep the scoreboard ticking all the time. He also has the ability to cut the ball very fine down to [[Cricket fielding positions|third man]] if there are no [[Cricket fielding positions|slips]], especially against spin bowlers, as he showed to great effect in his above-mentioned innings of 108 not out. These are his specialties, but he has large range of shots. However, many commentators have expressed that his defensive technique has flaws, and that he is prone to playing at balls outside off-stump which should be left.<ref>[https://cricketpointer.com/salman-butt-adnan-akmal-under-consideration-for-australia-tour/] </ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of cricketers banned for match fixing]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{cricinfo|id=42683}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|\nbefore= [[Shahid Afridi]]|\ntitle= [[Pakistani national cricket captains|Pakistani national cricket captain]] ([[Test Cricket|Tests]])|\nyears= 2010|\nafter= [[Misbah-ul-Haq]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Pakistan Test Cricket Captains}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= Pakistan squads \n|bg= #01411C\n|fg= #F8B800\n|bordercolor= #00A000\n|list1=\n{{Pakistan Squad 2009 ICC World Twenty20}}\n}}\n{{Lahore Qalandars squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Butt, Salman}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pakistani people of Kashmiri descent]]\n[[Category:Pakistan One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Lahore cricketers]]\n[[Category:Kolkata Knight Riders cricketers]]\n[[Category:Pakistan Test cricket captains]]\n[[Category:Pakistani cricketers]]\n[[Category:Pakistani people imprisoned abroad]]\n[[Category:Cricketers from Lahore]]\n[[Category:Lahore Whites cricketers]]\n[[Category:National Bank of Pakistan cricketers]]\n[[Category:Lahore Blues cricketers]]\n[[Category:Lahore Eagles cricketers]]\n[[Category:Lahore Qalandars cricketers]]\n[[Category:Punjab (Pakistan) cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers banned for corruption]]\n[[Category:Water and Power Development Authority cricketers]]\n[[Category:Khyber Pakhtunkhwa cricketers]]\n[[Category:Pakistani YouTubers]]\n", "name_user": "Adeel akhtar chaudry", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly career", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salman_Butt"}
{"title_page": "Amnesty International UK Media Awards 1997", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Amnesty International UK Media Awards Side Navbar}}\nThe awards were hosted by [[Janet Suzman]] on 18 June 1997 - [[Park Lane Hotel]], [[London]].<ref name=\"Amnesty AIUK Press Release 29 April 1996 001\"/>\n\nThere were 7 awards in 6 categories: National Print, Periodicals, Photojournalism, Radio, Television Documentary and Television News. Two awards were issued in the National Print category.\n\nThe overall winner was [[Lindsey Hilsum]], Diplomatic Correspondent for the [[Channel Four News|ITN Channel Four News]] Team for her body of work over through 1996-97 from Rwanda and the former Zaire (Now [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]])\n\nThe year's judges for all categories Keiko Itoh,<ref group=lower-alpha name=KeikoItoh/> [[John Mortimer|John Mortimer QC]], Norma Johnston,<ref group=lower-alpha name=NormaJohnston/> Sharon Welch,<ref group=lower-alpha name=SharonWelch/> [[Marc Riboud]], [[Cristina Odone]] and [[James Naughtie]].<ref name=\"Amnesty AIUK Press Release 29 April 1996 001\"/><ref name=\"Amnesty AIUK Press Release 29 April 1996 002\"/><ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards INDEX\"/>\n\nFollowing the awards, [[Peter Bottomley]] MP placed an [[Early day motion]] before the UK Parliament requesting that parliament agree \"That this House notes the importance of the Amnesty International Press Awards, ...recognises that links with victims are usually achieved through the Press and broadcasters; and acknowledges that the search for the truth is sometimes a ticket to jail or worse for journalists.\"<ref name=\"1997 Amnesty AIUK EDM 143 Petter Bottomley 18.06.1997\"/>\n\n==Awards 1997==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\" align=\"centre\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"background:#ffdead\" align=\"center\"| '''1997'''\n|-\n! width=20% | Category\n! width=30% | Title\n! width=23% | Organisation\n! width=22% | Journalists\n! width=5% | Refs\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" align=\"center\" | '''National Print'''<br />''Joint Winners''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | '''Articles from Afghanistan'''\n| align=\"center\" | [[The Daily Telegraph]]\n| align=\"center\" | Alex Spillius\n| align=\"center\" | <ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards NATIONAL PRINT\"/><ref name=\"1997 AIUK Award - Alex Spillius Biog 001\"/><br /><br />\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | '''\u201cBlack Gold Fuels Columbia Killing Machine\u201d'''\n| align=\"center\" | [[The Observer]]\n| align=\"center\" | David Harrison<br />Melissa Jones\n| align=\"center\" | <ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards NATIONAL PRINT\"/><ref name=\"1997 AIUK AWARDS - \u201cBlack Gold Fuels Columbia Killing Machine\u201d 001\"/><br /><br />\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f2f2f2\"| <!--Blank Row To Improve Readability -->\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | '''Periodicals'''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | '''\u201cWhere Girls are Killed for Going to School\u201d'''\n| align=\"center\" | [[Marie Claire]]\n| align=\"center\" | [[Lara Marlowe]]\n| align=\"center\" | <ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards PERIODICALS\"/><ref name=\"1997 Periodicals \u201cWhere Girls are Killed for Going to School\u201d 001\"/><br />\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f2f2f2\"| <!--Blank Row To Improve Readability -->\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | '''Photojournalism'''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | '''\u201cThe Highway to Hell\u201d'''\n| align=\"center\" |\n| align=\"center\" | Gary Knight\n| align=\"center\" |<ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards PHOTOJOURNALISM\"/><ref name=\"Garry Knights Rwanda Genocide 001\"/><br /><ref name=\"Garry Knights Rwanda Genocide 002\"/>\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f2f2f2\"| <!--Blank Row To Improve Readability -->\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | '''Radio'''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |  '''\u201cChocolate Soldier from the USA\u201d'''\n| align=\"center\" |  BBC Radio South\n| align=\"center\" |  Marc Jobst<br />George Pixley\n| align=\"center\" | <ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards RADIO \"/><ref name=\"1997 Radio Chocolate Soldier From the USA 001\"/><br /><ref name=\"1997 Radio Chocolate Soldier From the USA 002\"/><ref name=\"1997 Radio Chocolate Soldier From the USA 003\"/><ref name=\"1997 Radio Chocolate Soldier From the USA 004\"/>\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f2f2f2\"| <!--Blank Row To Improve Readability -->\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | '''Television<br />Documentary'''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | '''\u201cRwanda - The Betrayal\u201d'''\n| align=\"center\" | Blackstone Pictures for<br />Channel Four Witness\n| align=\"center\" | [[Lindsey Hilsum]]<br />Peter Bate\n| align=\"center\" | <ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards TELEVISION DOCUMENTARY\"/><ref name=\"1997 Channel Four Witness Rwanda - The Betrayal 001\"/><br /><ref name=\"1997 Channel Four Witness Rwanda - The Betrayal 002\"/>\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f2f2f2\"| <!--Blank Row To Improve Readability -->\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | '''Television<br />News'''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | '''\u201cWomen under the Veil\u201d'''\n| align=\"center\" | [[Channel 4 News|ITN Channel Four News]]\n| align=\"center\" | [[Saira Shah]]\n| align=\"center\" | <ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards TELEVISION NEWS\"/><ref name=\"1997 Television News - Women under the Veil, Saira Shah 001\"/><br /><ref name=\"1997 Television News - Women under the Veil, Saira Shah 002\"/>\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" style=\"background:#f2f2f2\"| <!--Blank Row To Improve Readability -->\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n\n{{Amnesty International UK Media Awards Nav Bar}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha|refs=\n\n<ref name=KeikoItoh>At the time of the 1997 Awards, Keiko Itoh was Media Relations Consultant for [[World Bank Group|The World Bank]]</ref>\n\n<ref name=NormaJohnston>At the time of the 1997 Awards, Moram Johnston was Communications Director for Amnesty International UK</ref>\n\n<ref name=SharonWelch>At the time of the 1997 Awards, Sharon Welch was Director of the London Millennium Festival</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2|refs=\n<!--  #######          Ref List - Ref List - Ref List          ######  -->\n\n<ref name=\"Amnesty AIUK Press Release 29 April 1996 001\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org.uk/press_awards/riboud.html |title=AMNESTY INTERNATIONAL PRESS AWARDS 1997 MARC RIBOUD JOINS PANEL OF JUDGES 29 April 1996 |publisher=Amnesty International UK (AIUK) |date=29 April 1996 |accessdate=18 January 2013 |author=Amnesty UK Press Office |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19970530094540/http://www.amnesty.org.uk/press_awards/riboud.html |archivedate=30 May 1997 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Amnesty AIUK Press Release 29 April 1996 002\">{{cite web |url=https://www.amnesty.org.uk/press_awards/riboud.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19970530094540/http://www.amnesty.org.uk/press_awards/riboud.html|title=AIUK Press Release 29 April 1996 AMNESTY INTERNATIONAL PRESS AWARDS 1997 MARC RIBOUD JOINS PANEL OF JUDGES 29 April 1996 |archivedate=30 May 1997 |url-status=dead |accessdate=June 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"1997 Amnesty Media Awards INDEX\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org.uk/pressawards97/index.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=17 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060211140852/http://www.amnesty.org.uk/pressawards97/index.html |archivedate=11 February 2006 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"1997 Amnesty AIUK EDM 143 Petter Bottomley 18.06.1997\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.parliament.uk/edm/print/1997-98/143 |title=Early day motion 143 AMNESTY INTERNATIONAL PRESS AWARDS Date tabled: 18.06.1997 |author=Bottomley Peter |journal=House of Commons Business Papers |date=June 1997 |issue=Session: 1997\u201398 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6DlHny2FG |arch